{"title_page": "Walter Munk", "text_new": "{{good article}}\n{{short description|American oceanographer}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| birth_name = Walter Heinrich Munk\n| image = Crafoordprize 2010-03.jpg\n| caption = Munk in [[Stockholm]] in 2010 to accept his [[Crafoord Prize]].\n| birth_date = {{birth date|mf=yes|1917|10|19}}\n| birth_place = [[Vienna]], [[Austria-Hungary]]\n| death_date = {{death date and age|2019|2|8|1917|10|19}}<ref name=Scripps_obit/>\n<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dicke |first1=William |title=Walter H. Munk, Scientist-Explorer Who Illuminated the Deep, Dies at 101 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/02/09/obituaries/walter-h-munk-scientist-explorer-who-illuminated-the-deep-dies-at-101.html |accessdate=11 February 2019 |work=The New York Times |date=9 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=NBC 7 Staff |title=World-Renowned Oceanographer Walter Munk Dies at 101 |url=https://www.nbcsandiego.com/news/local/World-Renowned-Oceanographer-Walter-Munk-Dies-at-101-505598621.html |accessdate=11 February 2019 |work=NBC 7 San Diego |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"latimesobit\">{{cite news |last1=Robbins |first1=Gary |title=Walter Munk, La Jolla scientist-explorer dubbed the 'Einstein of the Oceans,' dies at 101 |url=https://www.latimes.com/local/obituaries/la-me-ln-walter-munk-obit-20190209-story.html |accessdate=11 February 2019 |work=latimes.com}}</ref>\n| death_place  =  [[La Jolla, California]], U.S.\n| nationality = USA\n| fields = [[Oceanography]], [[geophysics]]\n| alma_mater        = [[California Institute of Technology]] (BS,MS)<br />[[Scripps Institution of Oceanography]]/[[University of California, Los Angeles]] (PhD)\n| doctoral_advisor = [[Harald Sverdrup (oceanographer)|Harald Ulrik Sverdrup]]\n| thesis_title =  Increase in the period of waves traveling over large distances : with applications to tsunamis, swell, and seismic surface waves (1946)\n<ref name=\"PhD\">{{cite web | url=https://catalog.library.ucla.edu/vwebv/holdingsInfo?bibId=2498202 | \ntitle =Increase in the period of waves traveling over large distances: with applications to tsunamis, swell, and seismic surface waves|author=Walter Munk|publisher =University of California, Los Angeles Library |date=1946|pages=41|accessdate=February 18, 2019}}</ref> \n| doctoral_students = [[Charles Shipley Cox]]\n| awards = {{nowrap|[[Maurice Ewing Medal]] (1976)<br />[[Alexander Agassiz Medal]] (1976)<br />[[National Medal of Science]] (1985)<br />[[Bakerian Lecture]] (1986)<br />[[William Bowie Medal]] (1989)<br />[[Vetlesen Prize]] (1993)<br />[[Kyoto Prize]] (1999)<br />[[Prince Albert I Medal]] (2001)<br />[[Crafoord Prize]] (2010)}}\n}}\n'''Walter Heinrich Munk''' (October 19, 1917,  [[Vienna]], [[Austria-Hungary]]<ref name=\"NYTimes1\" /> \u2013 February 8, 2019,  La Jolla, California.<ref name=\"Scripps_obit\">{{Cite web|url=https://scripps.ucsd.edu/news/obituary-notice-walter-munk-world-renowned-oceanographer-revered-scientist|title=Obituary Notice: Walter Munk, World-Renowned Oceanographer, Revered Scientist|date=February 8, 2019|website=Scripps Institution of Oceanography|language=en|access-date=February 9, 2019}}</ref> ) was an American [[physical oceanography|physical oceanographer]].<ref name=Scripps_obit/><ref name=\"Yam\">{{cite journal|last1=Yam|first1=P|year=1995|title=Profile: Walter H. Munk \u2013 The Man Who Would Hear Ocean Temperatures|url=|journal=[[Scientific American]]|volume=272|issue=1|pages=38\u201340|doi=10.1038/scientificamerican0195-38|bibcode=1995SciAm.272a..38Y}}</ref> One of the first scientists to bring statistical methods to the analysis of oceanographic data, Munk's work is noted for creating fruitful areas of research that continue to be explored by other scientists. For these achievements. Munk received a number of prestigious awards including the [[National Medal of Science]], the [[Kyoto Prize]], and induction to the French [[Legion of Honour]].\n\nMunk worked on a wide range of topics, including [[Surface wave|surface waves]], geophysical implications of [[Milankovitch cycles|variations in the Earth's rotation]], [[tide]]s, [[internal wave]]s, deep-ocean drilling into the sea floor, acoustical measurements of ocean properties, [[sea level rise]], and [[Global warming|climate change]]. Beginning in 1975, Munk and [[Carl Wunsch]] developed [[ocean acoustic tomography]], to exploit the ease with which sound travels in the ocean and use acoustical signals for measurement of broad-scale temperature and current. In a 1991 experiment, Munk and his collaborators investigated the ability of underwater sound to propagate from the Southern Indian Ocean across all ocean basins. The aim was to measure global ocean temperature. The experiment was criticized by environmental groups, who expected that the loud acoustic signals would adversely affect marine life. Munk continued to develop and advocate for acoustical measurements of the ocean throughout his career.\n\nMunk's career was long and complicated. World War II disrupted his doctoral studies at the [[Scripps Institution of Oceanography]] (Scripps), and led to his participation in U.S. military research efforts.  Munk and his doctoral advisor [[Harald Sverdrup (oceanographer)|Harald Sverdrup]] developed methods for forecasting wave conditions which were used in support of beach landings in all theaters of the war.  He was involved with oceanographic programs during the [[Operation Crossroads|atomic bomb tests in Bikini Atoll]].  For most of his career, he was a professor of [[geophysics]] at Scripps at the [[University of California]] in [[La Jolla, California|La Jolla]].  Additionally, Munk and his wife [[Judith Munk|Judy]] were active in developing the Scripps campus and integrating it with the new [[University of California, San Diego]]. Munk's career included a number of prestigious positions, including being a member of the [[JASON (advisory group)|JASON]] [[think tank]], and holding the Secretary of the Navy/Chief of Naval Operations Oceanography Chair.   \n\n== Early life and education ==\nIn 1917, Munk was born to a Jewish family in [[Vienna]], [[Austria-Hungary]].<ref name=\"NYTimes1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/25/science/walter-munk-einstein-of-the-oceans-at-97.html|title=Walter Munk, the 'Einstein of the Oceans'|last=Galbraith|first=Kate|date=August 24, 2015|work=The New York Times|access-date=February 10, 2019|language=en-US}}</ref> His father, Dr. Hans Munk, and his mother, Rega Brunner, divorced when he was ten years old.<ref name=\"70yrs\"/>{{rp|14}}<ref name=\"DDay\"/> His maternal grandfather was Lucian Brunner (1850\u20131914), a prominent banker and Austrian politician. His stepfather, Dr. Rudolf Engelsberg, was head of the salt mine monopoly of the Austrian government and a member of the Austrian governments of Chancellor [[Engelbert Dollfuss]] and Chancellor [[Kurt Schuschnigg]].<ref name=\"70yrs\"/>{{rp|14}}<ref name=\"munk30s\">{{cite journal|title=Introducing Walter Munk, or \"The Old Man and the Sea\"|last=Adelmann|first=Pepita|date=April 15, 2008|journal=Bridges|volume=17|url=https://ostaustria.org/bridges-magazine/volume-17-april-28-2008/item/3027-introducing-walter-munk-or-the-old-man-and-the-sea|access-date=February 16, 2019|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"Armi\">{{cite web | url=https://opensky.ucar.edu/islandora/object/archives%3A7621 | \ntitle =Transcript of Oral History interview of Walter Munk |author=Lawrence Armi|publisher =American Meteorological Society Oral History Project, National Center for Atmospheric Research |date=28 September 1994|accessdate=February 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 1932, Munk was performing poorly in school because he was spending too much time skiing, so his family sent him from Austria to a boys' preparatory school in upper New York state.<ref name=\"Affairs\">{{cite journal|doi=10.1146/annurev.ea.08.050180.000245|journal=[[Annual Review of Earth and Planetary Sciences]]|volume=8|date=1980|pages=1\u201317|title=Affairs of the Sea|author=Munk, Walter H.|bibcode=1980AREPS...8....1M|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/1f1caf61e70de4060320f71365ad11a95077a824}}</ref><ref name=\"70yrs\">{{cite book|publisher=Springer-Verlag|location=Berlin|title=Seventy Years of Exploration in Oceanography: A Prolonged Weekend Discussion with Walter Munk|date=2010|first=Hans|last=von Storch|author2=Klaus Hasselmann|isbn=978-3-642-12086-2|doi=10.1007/978-3-642-12087-9 |url=http://www.hvonstorch.de/klima/books/munk-springer-final.pdf}}</ref>{{rp|14}} His family envisioned a career for him in finance with a New York bank connected to the family business.<ref name=\"70yrs\"/>{{rp|14}} He worked at the family's banking firm for three years and studied at [[Columbia University]].<ref name=\"70yrs\"/>{{rp|14}}\n\nMunk hated banking. In 1937, he left the firm to attend the [[California Institute of Technology]] (Caltech) in [[Pasadena]].<ref name=\"70yrs\"/>{{rp|17}} While at Caltech, he took a summer job in 1939 at the [[Scripps Institution of Oceanography]] (Scripps) in [[La Jolla, California]].<ref name=\"munk30s\" /><ref name=WunschObit>{{cite journal |last1=Wunsch |first1=Carl |title=Walter Munk (1917-2019) |journal=Nature |date=28 February 2019 |volume=567 |issue=7747 |pages=176 |doi=10.1038/d41586-019-00750-5|bibcode=2019Natur.567..176W |doi-access=free }}</ref>  Munk earned a [[Bachelor's degree|B.S.]] in applied physics in 1939<ref name=\"Affairs\"/> and an [[master's degree|M.S.]] in geophysics (under [[Beno Gutenberg]]<ref name=\"Affairs\"/>) in 1940 at Caltech.<ref name=\"70yrs\"/>{{rp|105}}<ref name=\"msthesis\">{{cite thesis|last=Munk|first=Walter H.|date=1940|title=Internal waves in the Gulf of California|publisher=California Institute of Technology|url=http://resolver.caltech.edu/CaltechETD:etd-06162004-140251}}</ref> The master's degree work was based on oceanographic data collected in the [[Gulf of California]] by the [[Norway|Norwegian]] oceanographer [[Harald Sverdrup (oceanographer)|Harald Sverdrup]], then director of Scripps.<ref name=\"Armi\"/>\n\nIn 1939, Munk asked Sverdrup to take him on as a doctoral student. Sverdrup agreed, although Munk recalled him saying \"I can't think of a single job that's going to become available in the next ten years in oceanography\".<ref name=\"Armi\"/> Munk's studies were interrupted by the outbreak of [[World War II]]. He completed his doctoral degree in oceanography at Scripps under the [[University of California, Los Angeles]] in 1947.<ref name=\"PhD\"/><ref name=\"70yrs\"/>{{rp|105}} He wrote it in three weeks and it is the \"shortest Scripps dissertation on record.\" He later realized that its principal conclusion is wrong.<ref name=\"Affairs\"/>\n\n== Wartime activities ==\nIn 1940, Munk enlisted the [[U.S. Army]]. This was unusual for a student at Scripps: all the others joined the [[U.S. Naval Reserve]].<ref name=\"DDay\">{{cite web|url=http://scilib.ucsd.edu/sio/biogr/Munk_Biogr.pdf|title=Walter Heinrich Munk Biography|author=D. Day|date=August 31, 2005|work=Scripps Institution of Oceanography Archives|accessdate=February 17, 2019}}</ref> After serving 18 months in [[Field Artillery Branch (United States)|Field Artillery]] and the [[Ski warfare|Ski Troops]],<ref name=\"Affairs\"/> he was discharged at the request of Sverdrup and [[Roger Revelle]] so he could undertake defense-related research at Scripps. In December 1941, a week before the Japanese [[Attack on Pearl Harbor]], he joined several of his colleagues from Scripps at the [[U.S. Navy]] [[Radio and Sound Laboratory]].<ref name=\"70yrs\"/>{{rp|20}} For six years they developed methods related to [[Anti-submarine warfare|antisubmarine]] and [[amphibious warfare]].<ref name=\"Affairs\"/> This research involved marine acoustics, and eventually led to his work on [[#Ocean acoustic tomography|ocean acoustic tomography]].<ref name=\"Scripps_obit\"/>\n\n===Predicting surf conditions for Allied landings===\nIn 1943, Munk and Sverdrup began looking for a way to predict the heights of ocean surface waves. The Allies were preparing for a [[Operation Torch|landing in North Africa]], where two out of every three days the waves are above six feet. Practice beach landings in [[the Carolinas]] were suspended when waves reached this height because they were dangerous to people and landing craft.<ref name=\"Affairs\"/><ref name=\"70yrs\"/>{{rp|3}} Munk and Sverdrup found an empirical law that related wave height and period to the speed and duration of the wind and the [[Fetch (geography)|distance over which it blows]].<ref name=\"Affairs\"/> The Allies applied this method in the [[Pacific War|Pacific theater of war]] and the [[Normandy invasion]] on [[D-Day]].<ref name=\"munk30s\" /><ref>{{Citation|last=U.S. Navy|title=Dr Walter Munk explains his role in Operation Overlord|date=April 8, 2014|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=t7DtckkgvWQ|accessdate=June 7, 2018}}</ref> \n\nOfficials at the time estimated that many lives were saved by these predictions.<ref name=\"Kinsman\">{{cite book|publisher=Prentice Hall|location=Englewood Cliffs, N.J.|title=Wind Waves: Their Generation and Propagation on the Ocean Surface|date=1965|first=Blair|last=Kinsman|isbn=978-0139603440|doi=}}</ref>{{rp|321}} Munk commented in 2009:<ref name=\"CBS8\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cbs8.com/Global/story.asp?S=9866733|title=Walter Munk: One Of The World's Greatest Living Oceanographers|work=CBS 8|date=November 2, 2009|accessdate=August 20, 2010}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote|text=The Normandy landing is famous because weather conditions were very poor and you may not realize it was postponed by General Eisenhower for 24 hours because of the prevailing wave conditions. And then he did decide, in spite of the fact that conditions were not favorable, it would be better to go in than lose the surprise element, which would have been lost if they waited for the next tidal cycle [in] two weeks.}}\n\n===Oceanographic measurements during atomic weapons tests in the Pacific===\nIn 1946, the United States tested two fission [[nuclear weapons]] (20 kilotons) at [[Bikini Atoll]] in the equatorial Pacific in [[Operation Crossroads]]. Munk helped to determine the [[Ocean current|currents]], diffusion, and water exchanges affecting the radiation contamination from the second test, code-named Baker.<ref name=\"munk30s\"/><ref name=\"NYTimes1\"/> Six years later he returned to the equatorial Pacific for the 1952 test of the first fusion nuclear weapon (10 megatons) at [[Eniwetok Atoll]], code-named [[Ivy Mike]].<ref name=\"70yrs\"/>{{rp|25}}  [[Roger Revelle]], [[John Dove Isaacs|John Isaacs]], and Munk had initiated a program for monitoring for the possibility of a large [[tsunami]] generated from the test.<ref name=\"70yrs\"/>{{rp|26}}\n\n===Later association with the military===\nMunk continued to have a close association with the military in later decades. He was one of the first academics to be funded by the [[Office of Naval Research]], and had his last grant from them when he was 97.<ref name=WunschObit/> In 1968, he became a member of [[JASON (advisory group)|JASON]], a panel of scientists who advise the Pentagon, and he continued in that role until the end of his life.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Walter Munk|date=October 17, 2017|work=Physics Today|language=en-US|doi=10.1063/PT.6.6.20171019a}}</ref> He held a Secretary of the Navy/Chief of Naval Operations Oceanography Chair from 1985 until his death in 2019.<ref name=\"70yrs\"/>{{rp|99,105}}\n\n==The Institute of Geophysics and Planetary Physics in La Jolla==\nAfter receiving his doctorate in 1947, Munk was hired by Scripps as an assistant professor of geophysics. He became a full professor there in 1954,<ref>{{cite web|title=Walter Munk Biography, Research Professor of Geophysics Cecil H. and Ida M. Green Institute of Geophysics and Planetary Physics|work= Scripps Institution of Oceanography University of California, San Diego|date=March 2017|access-date=February 14, 2019|url=http://scrippsscholars.ucsd.edu/wmunk/biocv}}</ref> but his appointment was at the Institute of Geophysics (IGP) at the [[University of California, Los Angeles]] (UCLA). In 1955, Munk took a sabbatical at Cambridge, England.<ref name=\"70yrs\"/>{{rp|75}}  His experience at Cambridge led to the idea of starting a new IGP branch at Scripps.<ref name=\"70yrs\"/>{{rp|75}}\n\nAt the time of Munk's return to Scripps, it was still under the administration of UCLA, as it had been since 1938. It became part of the [[University of California, San Diego]] (UCSD) when that campus was founded in 1958.<ref name=\"Stadtman1\">{{cite book |url=https://archive.org/details/universityofcali00stad|url-access=registration|last=Stadtman |first=Verne A. |year=1970 |title=The University of California, 1868-1968|pages= [https://archive.org/details/universityofcali00stad/page/407 407]\u2013411|publisher=[[McGraw-Hill]]|accessdate=May 5, 2013}}</ref> Revelle, its director at the time, was a primary advocate for establishing the La Jolla campus.<ref>{{cite journal|journal = Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America|title =Tribute to Roger Revelle and his contribution to studies of carbon dioxide and climate change | year = 1997| last1 = Munk|first1 = W.|volume = 94|issue = 16|pages = 8275\u20138279|doi = 10.1073/pnas.94.16.8275 |pmid = 11607733|pmc = 33716|bibcode =1997PNAS...94.8275M }}</ref> At this time Munk was considering offers for new positions at the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] and [[Harvard University]], but Revelle encouraged Munk to remain in La Jolla.<ref name=\"70yrs\"/>{{rp|75}} Munk's founding of IGP at La Jolla was concurrent with the creation of the UCSD campus.\n\nThe IGPP laboratory was built between 1959 and 1963 with funding from the University of California, the U.S. Air Force Office of Scientific Research, the [[National Science Foundation]], and private foundations.<ref name=\"IGPP\">{{cite news|title=The Cecil H. and Ida M. Green Institute of Geophysics and Planetary Physics (IGPP)|author=W. Munk|author2=F. Gilbert|author3=J. Orcutt|author4=M. Zumberg|author5=R. Parker|journal=Oceanography|volume=16|pages=34\u201344|date=2003|url=http://scilib.ucsd.edu/sio/hist/igpp-oceanography.pdf|doi=10.5670/oceanog.2003.29}}</ref><ref name=\"IGPPWEB\">{{cite news|title=The Cecil H. and Ida M. Green Institute of Geophysics and Planetary Physics (IGPP)|url=http://igpp.ucsd.edu/about/history|accessdate=November 2, 2010}}</ref> (After planetary physics was added, IGP changed its name to the Institute of Geophysics and Planetary Physics (IGPP).<ref name=\"70yrs\"/>{{rp|75}}) The redwood building was designed by architect Lloyd Ruocco, in close consultation with Judith and Walter Munk. The IGPP buildings have become the center of the Scripps campus. Among the early faculty appointments were [[Carl Eckart]], [[George E. Backus|George Backus]], [[Freeman Gilbert]] and [[John W. Miles|John Miles]]. The eminent geophysicist [[Edward Bullard|Sir Edward \"Teddy\" Bullard]] was a regular visitor to IGPP. In 1971 an endowment of $600,000 was established by [[Cecil Howard Green|Cecil Green]] to support visiting scholars, now known as Green Scholars. Munk served as director of IGPP/LJ from 1962 to 1982.<ref name=\"IGPP\"/><ref name=\"70yrs\"/>{{rp|81}}\n\nIn the late 1980s, plans for an expansion of IGPP were developed by Judith and Walter Munk, and Sharyn and John Orcutt, in consultation with a local architect, Fred Liebhardt.<ref name=\"IGPP\"/> The Revelle Laboratory was completed in 1993. At this time the original IGPP building was renamed the Walter and Judith Munk Laboratory for Geophysics. In 1994 the Scripps branch of IGPP was renamed the Cecil H. and Ida M. Green Institute of Geophysics and Planetary Physics.<ref name=\"IGPP\"/>\n\n==Research==\nMunk's career in oceanography and geophysics touched on disparate and innovative topics.  A pattern of Munk's work was that he would initiate a completely new topic; ask challenging, fundamental questions about the subject and its larger meaning; and then, having created an entirely new sub-field of science, move on to another new topic.<ref name=Scripps_obit/><ref name=\"RSPW\">{{cite journal|last1=Spindel|first1=R.C.|last2=Worcester|first2=P.F. |year=2016|title=Walter H. Munk: Seventy-Five Years of Exploring the Seas|journal=Acoustics Today|volume=12|issue=1|pages=36\u201342|url=https://acousticstoday.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/Walter-H.-Munk-Seventy-Five-Years-of-Exploring-the-Seas.pdf|access-date=February 19, 2019|doi=|bibcode=}}</ref>  As [[Carl Wunsch]], one of Munk's frequent collaborators,<ref name=\"Wunsch\">{{cite journal|title=A Conversation with Walter Munk|last1=Munk|first1=Walter|last2=Wunsch|first2=Carl|year=2019|journal=Annual Review of Marine Science|volume=11|pages=15\u201325|doi=10.1146/annurev-marine-010318-095353|pmid=29751736|bibcode=2019ARMS...11...15M}}</ref> commented:<ref name=\"70yrs\"/>{{rp|vi}}\n\n{{Quote|text=[Walter has] a sometimes uncanny ability to delineate the essence - that had eluded his predecessors - of a central problem. He has the knack of defining a field in a way that requires decades of subsequent work by others to fully flesh-out, while he himself moves on. One of his explicitly stated themes is that it is more important to ask the right questions than it is to give the right answers.}}\n\n===Wind-driven gyres===\n[[File:Oceanic gyres.png|thumb|300px|right|The five major ocean gyres]]\nIn 1948, Munk took a year's sabbatical to visit Sverdrup in [[Oslo]], Norway on his first [[Guggenheim Fellowship]].<ref name=\"DDay\"/>  He worked on the problem of wind-driven [[ocean circulation]],<ref name=\"70yrs\"/>{{rp|34}} obtaining the first comprehensive solution for currents based on observed wind patterns.<ref name=Pond>{{cite book |last1=Pond |first1=Stephen |last2=Pickard |first2=George L. |title=Introductory dynamical oceanography |date=2013 |publisher=Elsevier |isbn=9780080570549 |pages=138\u2013144 |edition=Second}}</ref> This included two types of [[viscosity|friction]]: horizontal friction between water masses moving at different velocities or between water and the edges of the oceanic basin,<ref name=CrafoordInfo>{{cite web |last1=Royal Swedish Academy of Sciences |title=Always count on the oceans |url=https://s3.eu-de.cloud-object-storage.appdomain.cloud/crafoord-image-pdf/2017/11/pop_CraGeo_en_100121_FINAL.pdf |website=The Crafoord Prize |accessdate=9 January 2020}}</ref> and friction from a vertical velocity gradient in the top layer of the ocean (the [[Ekman layer]]).<ref name=Pond/> The model predicted the five main [[ocean gyre]]s (pictured), with rapid, narrow currents  in the west flowing towards the poles and broader, slower currents in the east flowing away from the poles.<ref name=CrafoordInfo/> Munk coined the term \"ocean gyres,\" a term now widely used.<ref name=\"70yrs\"/>{{rp|34}} The currents predicted for the western boundaries (e.g., for the [[Gulf Stream]] and the [[Kuroshio Current]]) were about half of the accepted values at the time, but those only considered the most intense flow and neglected a large return flow. Later estimates agreed well with Munk's predictions.<ref name=Pond/>\n\n===Rotation of the Earth===\nIn the 1950s, Munk investigated irregularities in the Earth's rotation \u2013 [[Day length fluctuations|changes in the length of day]] (rate of the Earth's rotation) and changes in the axis of rotation (such as the [[Chandler wobble]], which has a period of about 14 months). The latter gives rise to a small tide called the [[Long period tide#Pole tide|pole tide]]. Although the scientific community knew of these fluctuations, they did not have adequate explanations for them. With [[Gordon J. F. MacDonald]], Munk published ''The Rotation of the Earth: A Geophysical Discussion'' in 1960. This book discusses the effects from a geophysical, rather than astronomical, perspective. It shows that short-term variations are caused by movement in the atmosphere, ocean, underground water, and interior of the Earth, including [[tide]]s in the ocean and solid Earth. Over longer times (a century or more), the largest influence is the [[tidal acceleration]] that causes the Moon to move away from the Earth at about four centimeters per year. This gradually slows Earth's rotation, so that over 500 million years the length of day has increased from 21 hours to 24.<ref name=CrafoordInfo/> The monograph remains a standard reference.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Groves|first1=G.W. |editor1-last=Kopal |editor1-first=Zden\u011bk |title=Physics and Astronomy of the Moon|publisher=Academic Press|date=1961|chapter=Dynamics of the Earth-Moon System|pages=61\u201398|location=New York|isbn=9781483270784}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|journal=Phil. Trans. Roy. Soc. A|title=The Earth's variable rate of rotation: A discussion of some meteorological and oceanic causes and consequences|date=1977|last1=Lambeck|first1=K.|last2=Cazenave|first2=A.|volume=284|issue=1326|pages=495\u2013506|doi=10.1098/rsta.1977.0025|bibcode=1977RSPTA.284..495L}}</ref>\n<!-- Munk was the first to show rigorously why one side of the [[Moon]] always faces the Earth (Munk and McDonald, 1960; and later papers up to 1975), a phenomenon known as [[tidal locking]].{{cn|date=February 2019}}{{dubious|Tidal locking|date=February 2019}} [[William Thomson, 1st Baron Kelvin|Lord Kelvin]] had also considered this question, and had fashioned a non-quantitative answer being roughly correct. The Moon does not have a molten liquid core, so cannot rotate through the egg-shaped distortion caused by the Earth's gravitational pull. Rotation through this shape requires internal shearing, and only fluids are capable of such rotation with small frictional losses. Thus, the pointy end of the \"egg\" is gravitationally locked to always point directly towards the Earth, with some small [[Libration|''librations'']], or wobbles. Large objects may strike the Moon from time to time, causing it to rotate about some axis, but it will quickly stop rotating. All frictional effects from such events will also cause the Moon to regress further away from the Earth.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Groves|first1=G.W. |editor1-last=Kopal |editor1-first=Z.|title=Physics and Astronomy of the Moon|publisher=Academic Press|date=1961|chapter=Dynamics of the Earth-Moon System|pages=61-98|location=New York}}</ref> -->\n\n=== Project Mohole ===\n{{Main|Project Mohole}}\n[[File:Mohopix-1.gif|thumb|200px|Project Mohole contracted with a consortium of oil companies to use their oil drillship ''CUSS I''.<ref name=\"IODP\">{{cite web|url=http://www.iodp.org/project-mohole|title=Project Mohole|publisher=[[International Ocean Discovery Program|IODP]]|accessdate=5 March 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140306005146/http://www.iodp.org/project-mohole|archivedate = 6 March 2014 }}</ref>]]\nIn 1957, Munk and [[Harry Hammond Hess|Harry Hess]] suggested the idea behind [[Project Mohole]]: to drill into the [[Mohorovi\u010di\u0107 discontinuity]] and obtain a sample of the Earth's [[mantle (geology)|mantle]]. While such a project was not feasible on land, drilling in the open ocean would be more feasible, because the mantle is much closer to the [[sea floor]]. Initially led by the informal group of scientists known as the [[American Miscellaneous Society]] (AMSOC), a group that included Hess, [[Maurice Ewing]], and [[Roger Revelle]],<ref name=\"70yrs\" />{{rp|67}} the project was eventually taken over by the National Science Foundation. Initial test drillings into the sea floor led by [[Willard Bascom]] occurred off [[Guadalupe Island]], Mexico in March and April 1961.<ref name=\"Life Mohole\">{{cite news|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9lEEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA110&source=gbs_toc_r&cad=2#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=High drama of bold thrust through the ocean floor: Earth's second layer is tapped in prelude to MOHOLE|first=John|last=Steinbeck|work=Life Magazine|date=April 14, 1961|accessdate=September 11, 2010}}</ref> However, the project was mismanaged and grew in expense after the construction company [[KBR (company)|Brown and Root]] won the contract to continue the effort. Toward the end of 1966, Congress discontinued the project.<ref name=\"nomohole\">{{cite news|url=http://americanheritage.com/articles/magazine/it/1993/1/1993_1_54.shtml|title=Why Mohole was no hole|first=Daniel|last=Sweeney|work=Invention and Technology Magazine \u2013 American Heritage|date=1993|pages=55\u201363|volume=9|accessdate=August 14, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201150256/http://americanheritage.com/articles/magazine/it/1993/1/1993_1_54.shtml|archivedate=December 1, 2008}}</ref> While Project Mohole was not successful, the idea and its innovative initial phase directly led to the successful NSF [[Deep Sea Drilling Program]] for obtaining sediment cores.<ref name=\"mohole\">{{cite news |url=http://www.nationalacademies.org/mohole/index.html |title=Project Mohole: Commemorating the Accomplishments of Project Mohole 1961-2011|author=The National Academies|accessdate=July 7, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Winterer\">{{Cite book |first1=Edward L. |last1=Winterer |date= 2000 |chapter=Scientific Ocean Drilling, from AMSOC to COMPOST |title=50 Years of Ocean Discovery: National Science Foundation 1950-2000|location=Washington, D.C.|chapter-url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK208831/ |publisher=National Academies Press (US) }}</ref>\n\n=== Ocean swell ===\n[[File:FLoatingInstrumentPlatform.jpg|thumb|alt=FLIP: FLoating Instrument Platform|Munk used [[R/P FLIP]] to measure waves traveling across ocean basins.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ocean.si.edu/human-connections/exploration/flip-floating-instrument-platform|title=FLIP: The FLoating Instrument Platform|last=Waters|first=Hannah|date=July 2012|work=[[Smithsonian Institution]]|accessdate=June 7, 2018}}</ref>]]\nStarting in the late 1950s, Munk returned to the study of [[Swell (ocean)|ocean waves]]. Thanks to his acquaintance with [[John Tukey]], he pioneered the use of [[spectral density|power spectra]] in describing wave behavior. This work culminated with an expedition that he led in 1963 called \"Waves Across the Pacific\" to observe waves generated by storms in the Southern Indian Ocean. Such waves traveled northward for thousands of miles across the Pacific Ocean. To trace the path and decay of the waves, he established measurement stations on islands and at sea (on [[R/P FLIP]]) along a great circle from [[New Zealand]], to the [[Palmyra Atoll]], and finally to [[Alaska]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Munk|first1=Walter|title=Excerpts from Waves Across the Pacific|url=http://palmyraarchive.org/items/show/147|website=Palmyra Atoll Digital Archive|year=1964}}</ref> Munk and his family spent nearly the whole of 1963 on [[American Samoa]] for this experiment. Walter and Judith Munk collaborated in making a film to document the experiment.<ref name=\"Dutton2013\">{{cite book|author=Lee S. Dutton|title=Anthropological Resources: A Guide to Archival, Library, and Museum Collections|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rcbIgOCqreIC&pg=PA77|date=May 13, 2013|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-134-81893-8|page=77}}</ref> The results show little decay of wave energy with distance traveled.<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1098/rsta.1966.0022|journal=Philos. Trans. R. Soc. Lond. A|title=Propagation of ocean swell across the Pacific|date=1966|last=Snodgrass|first=F.E.|author2=G.W. Groves|author3=K.F. Hasselmann|author4=G.R. Miller|author5=W.H. Munk|author6=W.H. Powers|volume=259|pages=431\u2013497|issue=1103|bibcode=1966RSPTA.259..431S}}</ref> This work, together with the wartime work on wave forecasting, led to the science of [[surf forecasting]], one of Munk's best-known accomplishments.<ref name=\"CBS8\" /> Munk's pioneering research into surf forecasting was acknowledged in 2007 with an award from the Groundswell Society, a surfing advocacy organization.<ref name=\"NCT\">{{cite news|url=http://www.nctimes.com/app/blogs/wp/?p=6809|title=SIO's Walter Munk Wins Crafoord Prize|first=Bradley|last=Fikes|work=North County Times blogs|date=January 21, 2010|accessdate=August 20, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100126133745/http://www.nctimes.com/app/blogs/wp/?p=6809|archivedate=January 26, 2010|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"Explorations Swell\">{{cite news|url=http://explorations.ucsd.edu/Around_the_Pier/2007/May/Munk/|title=Isn't He Swell?|first=Shannon|last=Casey|work=Explorations|date=May 2007|accessdate=August 20, 2010}}</ref>{{refn|In 2019, the Groundswell Society established the Dr. Walter Munk Scholarship \"to support a student intending to pursue a career in oceanography, meteorology, or marine biology.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Groundswell Society |title=Dr. Walter Munk Scholarship |url=http://groundswell-society.org/2019/02/dr-walter-munk-scholarship/ |accessdate=10 January 2020 |date=23 February 2019}}</ref>}}\n\n=== Ocean tides ===\nBetween 1965 and 1975, Munk turned to investigations of [[tide|ocean tides]], partly motivated by their effects on the Earth's rotation. Modern methods of [[time series]] and [[Spectral density estimation|spectral analysis]] were brought to bear on [[Theory of tides#Tidal analysis and prediction|tidal analysis]], leading to work with [[David Edgar Cartwright|David Cartwright]] developing the \"response method\" of tidal analysis.<ref name=\"Response\">{{cite journal|journal=Philos Trans R Soc Lond|title=Tidal spectroscopy and prediction|date=1966|last=Munk|first=W.|author2=D.E Cartwright|volume=A 259|pages=533\u2013581}}</ref> With [[Frank E. Snodgrass|Frank Snodgrass]], Munk developed deep-ocean pressure sensors that could be used to provide tidal data far from any land.<ref name=\"Affairs\" /><ref name=\"Cartwright\">{{cite book|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge|title=Tides: A Scientific History|url=https://archive.org/details/tidesscientifich0000cart|url-access=registration|date=1999|first=David|last=Cartwright|isbn=978-0-521-62145-8}}</ref> One highlight of this work was the discovery of the semidiurnal [[Amphidromic point|amphidrome]] midway between California and Hawaii.<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1080/03091927009365772|journal=Geophys. Fluid Dyn.|title=Tides off shore: transition from California coastal to deep-sea waters|date=1970|last=Munk|first=W.|author2=F. Snodgrass| author2-link = Frank E. Snodgrass|author3=M. Wimbush| last-author-amp = yes|volume=1|issue=1\u20132|pages=161\u2013235|bibcode=1970GApFD...1..161M}}</ref>\n\n===Internal waves: The Garrett-Munk Spectrum===\nAt the time of Munk's dissertation for his master's degree in 1939, [[internal wave]]s were considered an uncommon phenomenon.<ref name=\"70yrs\"/>{{rp|48}}  By the 1970s, there were extensive published observations of internal-wave variability in the oceans in temperature, salinity, and velocity as functions of time, horizontal distance, and depth.  Motivated by a 1958 paper by [[Owen Martin Phillips|Owen Philips]] that described a universal spectral form for the variance of ocean surface waves as a function of [[wave number]],<ref name=\"Affairs\"/> [[Christopher Garrett|Chris Garrett]] and Munk attempted to make sense of the observations by postulating a universal spectrum for internal waves.<ref name=\"GM72\">{{cite journal|journal=Geophys. Fluid Dyn.|title=Space-time scales of internal waves|date=1972|last1=Munk|first1=W.|last2=Garrett|first2=C.J.R.|volume=2|issue=1|pages=225\u2013264|doi=10.1080/03091927208236082|bibcode=1972GApFD...3..225G}}</ref> \n\nAccording to Munk,<ref name=\"70yrs\" />{{rp|48}} they chose a spectrum that could be factored into a function of frequency times a function of vertical wave number.  The resulting spectrum, now called the Garrett-Munk Spectrum, is roughly consistent with a large number of diverse measurements that had been obtained over the global ocean.  The model evolved over the subsequent decade, denoted GM72, GM75, GM79, etc.,<ref name=\"GM79\">{{cite journal|journal=Annual Review of Fluid Mechanics|title=Internal waves in the ocean|date=1979|last1=Munk|first1=W.|last2=Garrett|first2=C.J.R.|volume=11|issue=1|pages=339\u2013369|doi=10.1146/annurev.fl.11.010179.002011|bibcode=1979AnRFM..11..339G}}</ref> according to the year of publication of the revised model.  Although Munk expected the model to be rapidly obsolete, it proved to be a universal model that is still in use. Its universality is interpreted as a sign of profound processes governing internal wave dynamics, turbulence and fine-scale mixing.<ref name=\"Affairs\" />  [[Klaus Hasselmann]] commented in 2010, \"...the publication of the GM spectrum has indeed been extremely fruitful for oceanography, both in the past and still today.\"<ref name=\"70yrs\" />{{rp|50}}\n\n=== Ocean acoustic tomography ===\n{{Main|Ocean acoustic tomography}}\n[[File:1991 Heard Island Feasibility Test.png|thumb|Ocean topography (see scale) and some paths traveled by sound waves during the \n1991 Heard Island Feasibility Test.]]\nBeginning in 1975, Munk and [[Carl Wunsch]] of the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] pioneered the development of [[Ocean acoustic tomography|acoustic tomography]] of the ocean.<ref name=\"OAT\">{{cite book|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge|title=Ocean Acoustic Tomography|date=1995|first=Walter|last=Munk|author2=Peter Worcester|author3=Carl Wunsch| last-author-amp = yes|isbn=978-0-521-47095-7}}</ref> With Peter Worcester and Robert Spindel,<ref name=\"RSPW\"/> Munk developed the use of sound propagation, particularly sound arrival patterns and travel times, to infer important information about the ocean's large-scale temperature and current. This work, together with the work of other groups,<ref name=\"JLS\">{{cite journal|last=Spiesberger|first=J.L.|author2=K. Metzger|year=1991|title=Basin-scale tomography: A new tool for studying weather and climate|journal=J. Geophys. Res.|volume=96|issue=C3|pages=4869\u20134889|doi=10.1029/90JC02538|bibcode=1991JGR....96.4869S}}</ref> eventually motivated the 1991 \"Heard Island Feasibility Test\" (HIFT), to determine if man-made acoustic signals could be transmitted over [[Antipodes|antipodal]] distances to measure the ocean's [[climate change|climate]]. The experiment came to be called \"the sound heard around the world.\" During six days in January 1991, acoustic signals were transmitted by sound sources lowered from the [[MV Cory Chouest|M/V Cory Chouest]] near [[Heard Island]] in the southern Indian Ocean. These signals traveled half-way around the globe to be received on the east and west coasts of the United States, as well as at many other stations around the world.<ref name=\"HIFT\">{{cite journal|doi=10.1121/1.411316|journal=Journal of the Acoustical Society of America|title=The Heard Island Papers: A contribution to global acoustics|date=1994|last=Munk|first=W.|author2=A. Baggeroer|volume=96|pages=2327\u20132329|issue=4|bibcode=1994ASAJ...96.2327M}}</ref>\n\nThe follow-up to this experiment was the 1996\u20132006 [[Ocean acoustic tomography|Acoustic Thermometry of Ocean Climate]] (ATOC) project in the North Pacific Ocean.<ref name=\"Yam\" /><ref name=\"Science-1998\">{{cite news|author=The ATOC Consortium|title=Ocean Climate Change: Comparison of Acoustic Tomography, Satellite Altimetry, and Modeling|date=August 28, 1998|publisher=Science Magazine|url=http://www.sciencemag.org/cgi/content/abstract/281/5381/1327?maxtoshow=&HITS=150&hits=150&RESULTFORMAT=&fulltext=ocean&searchid=QID_NOT_SET&FIRSTINDEX=&fdate=3/1/1998|pages=1327\u20131332|accessdate=May 28, 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"decade\">{{cite news|first=B.D.|last=Dushaw|display-authors=etal|title=A decade of acoustic thermometry in the North Pacific Ocean|date=July 19, 2009|publisher=J. Geophys. Res.|volume=114, C07021|doi=10.1029/2008JC005124|bibcode=2009JGRC..114.7021D}}</ref>  Both HIFT and ATOC engendered considerable public controversy concerning the possible effects of man-made sounds on marine mammals.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/NATURE/9906/30/sea.noise.part1/|title=Low-frequency sonar raises whale advocates' hackles|work=CNN|date=June 30, 1999|author=Stephanie Siegel|accessdate=October 23, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/library/national/science/102798sci-sound.html|title=Global Thermometer Imperiled by Dispute|work=NY Times|date=June 30, 1999|author=Malcolm W. Browne|accessdate=October 23, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=J. R.|last=Potter|title=ATOC: Sound Policy or Enviro-Vandalism? Aspects of a Modern Media-Fueled Policy Issue|date=1994|publisher=The Journal of Environment & Development|url=http://jed.sagepub.com/cgi/content/abstract/3/2/47|volume=3|doi=10.1177/107049659400300205|pages=47\u201362|accessdate=November 20, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"Yam\" /> In addition to the decade-long measurements obtained in the North Pacific, acoustic thermometry has been employed to measure temperature changes of the upper layers of the Arctic Ocean basins,<ref name=\"PNM\">{{cite journal|doi=10.3402/polar.v20i2.6516|journal=Polar Research|title=Acoustic thermometry in the Arctic Ocean|date=2001|last1=Mikhalevsky|first1=P. N.|last2=Gavrilov|first2=A.N.|volume=20|issue=2|pages=185\u2013192|url=http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/j.1751-8369.2001.tb00055.x/abstract| access-date=February 19, 2015|bibcode=2001PolRe..20..185M}}</ref> which continues to be an area of active interest.<ref name=\"PNM_Arctic\">{{cite journal|doi=10.14430/arctic4449|journal=Arctic|title=Multipurpose acoustic networks in the integrated Arctic Ocean observing system|date=2015|last1=Mikhalevsky|first1=P. N.|last2=Sagan|first2=H.| display-authors = etal|volume=28, Suppl. 1|issue=5|pages=17|hdl=20.500.11937/9445|url=https://espace.curtin.edu.au/bitstream/20.500.11937/9445/2/235904_235904.pdf}}</ref> Acoustic thermometry has also been used to determine changes to global-scale ocean temperatures using data from acoustic pulses traveling from Australia to Bermuda.<ref name=\"ABMunk\">{{cite journal|doi=10.1175/1520-0485(1988)018<1876:ABSTER>2.0.CO;2|journal=Journal of Physical Oceanography|title=Australia-Bermuda Sound Transmission Experiment (1960) Revisited.|date=1988|last1=Munk|first1=W.H.|last2=O'Reilly|first2=W.C.|last3=Reid|first3=J.L.|volume=18|issue=12|pages=1876\u20131998|bibcode=1988JPO....18.1876M|doi-access=free}}</ref><ref name=\"ABDushaw\">{{cite journal|doi=10.1016/j.dsr.2013.12.008|journal=Deep-Sea Research Part I|title=Antipodal acoustic thermometry: 1960, 2004|date=2014|last1=Dushaw|first1=B.D.|last2=Menemenlis|first2=D.|volume=86|pages=1\u201320|bibcode=2014DSRI...86....1D|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\nTomography has come to be a valuable method of ocean observation,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Fischer|first1=A.S.|last2=Hall|first2=J.|last3=Harrison|first3=D.E.|last4=Stammer|first4=D.|last5=Benveniste|first5=J. |editor1-last=Hall |editor1-first=J.|editor2-last=Harrison |editor2-first=D.E.|editor3-last=Stammer |editor3-first=D.|title=Proceedings of OceanObs'09: Sustained Ocean Observations and Information for Society|volume=1|publisher=ESA Publication WPP-306|date=2010|chapter=Conference Summary-Ocean Information for Society: Sustaining the Benefits, Realizing the Potential|chapterurl=http://www.oceanobs09.net/proceedings/summary/}}</ref> exploiting the characteristics of long-range acoustic propagation to obtain synoptic measurements of average ocean temperature or current. Applications have included the measurement of deep water formation in the Greenland Sea in 1989,<ref name=\"GSP\">{{cite journal|doi=10.1175/1520-0485(1996)026<2316:TDOOAD>2.0.CO;2|journal=Journal of Physical Oceanography|title=Three-dimensional observations of a deep convective chimney in the Greenland sea during Winter 1988/89|date=1996|last1=Morawitz|first1=W.M.L.|last2=Sutton|first2=P.J.|last3=Worcester|first3=P.F.|last4=Cornuelle|first4=B.D.|last5=Lynch|first5=J.F.|last6=Pawlowicz|first6=R.|volume=26|issue=11|pages=2316\u20132343|bibcode=1996JPO....26.2316M|doi-access=free}}</ref> measurement of ocean tides,<ref name=\"Stammer\">{{cite journal|doi=10.1002/2014RG000450|journal=Reviews of Geophysics|title=Accuracy assessment of global barotropic ocean tide models|date=2014|last1=Stammer|first1=D.| display-authors= etal|volume=52|issue=3|pages=243\u2013282|bibcode=2014RvGeo..52..243S|hdl=2027.42/109077|hdl-access=free}}</ref><ref name=\"Dushaw\">{{cite journal|doi=10.1016/j.dsr.2011.04.002|journal=Deep-Sea Research Part I|title=On the predictability of mode-1 internal tides|date=2011|last1=Dushaw|first1=B.D.|last2=Worcester|first2=P.F.|last3=Dzieciuch|first3=M.A.|volume=58|issue=6|pages=677\u2013698|bibcode=2011DSRI...58..677D}}</ref> and the estimation of [[Eddy (fluid dynamics)#Mesoscale ocean eddies|ocean mesoscale dynamics]] by combining tomography, [[Satellite geodesy|satellite altimetry]], and ''in situ'' data with ocean dynamical models.<ref name=\"Lebedev\">{{cite journal|journal=Journal of Physical Oceanography|title=Monitoring the Kuroshio Extension through dynamically constrained synthesis of the acoustic tomography, satellite altimeter and in situ data|date=2003|last1=Lebedev|first1=K.V.|last2=Yaremchuck|first2=M.|last3=Mitsudera|first3=H.|last4=Nakano|first4=I.|last5=Yuan|first5=G.|volume=59|issue=6|pages=751\u2013763|doi=10.1023/b:joce.0000009568.06949.c5}}</ref> \n\nMunk advocated for acoustical measurements of the ocean for much of his career, such as his 1986 [[Bakerian Lecture]] ''Acoustic Monitoring of Ocean Gyres'',<ref name=\"Bakerian\"/> the 1995 monograph ''Ocean Acoustic Tomography'' written with Worcester and Wunsch,<ref name=\"OAT\"/> and his 2010 [[Crafoord Prize]] lecture ''The Sound of Climate Change''.<ref name=\"Crafoord\"/><ref name=\"Crafoord_Lecture\">{{cite journal|journal=Tellus|title=The Sound of Climate Change|date=2011|last1=Munk|first1=W.|volume=63|issue=2|pages=190\u2013197|doi=10.1111/j.1600-0870.2010.00494.x|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\n=== Tides and mixing ===\nIn the 1990s, Munk returned to the work on the role of tides in producing mixing in the ocean.<ref>{{Cite journal|doi=10.1016/S0967-0637(98)00070-3|author=Munk, W.|author2=Wunsch, C. | last-author-amp = yes|date=1998|title=Abyssal recipes II: Energetics of tidal and wind mixing|journal=Deep-Sea Research|volume=45|pages=1977\u20132010|bibcode=1998DSRI...45.1977M|issue=12}}</ref> In a 1966 paper \"Abyssal Recipes\", Munk was one of the first to assess quantitatively the rate of mixing in the abyssal ocean in maintaining oceanic [[Stratification (water)|stratification]].<ref>{{Cite journal|author=Munk, W.|date=1966|title=Abyssal recipes|journal=Deep-Sea Research|volume=13|issue=4|pages=707\u2013730|doi=10.1016/0011-7471(66)90602-4|bibcode=1966DSROA..13..707M}}</ref>  At that time, the tidal energy available for mixing was thought to occur by processes near ocean boundaries. According to [[Johan Sandstr\u00f6m|Sandstr\u00f6m's theorem]] (1908), without the occurrence deep mixing, driven by, e.g., [[internal tides]] or tidally-driven turbulence in shallow regions, most of the ocean would become cold and stagnant, capped by a thin, warm surface layer.<ref>{{Cite journal|doi=10.1111/j.1600-0870.2008.00357.x|author=Kuhlbrodt, T.|date=2008|title=On Sandstr\u00f6m's inferences from his tank experiments: a hundred years later|journal=Tellus A: Dynamic Meteorology and Oceanography|volume=60|pages=819\u2013836|issue=5|bibcode=2008TellA..60..819K|doi-access=free}}</ref>  The question of tidal energy available for mixing was reawakened in the 1990s with the discovery, by acoustic tomography and satellite altimetry, of large-scale internal tides radiating energy away from the [[Hawaiian\u2013Emperor seamount chain|Hawaiian Ridge]] into the interior of the North Pacific Ocean.<ref name=\"Dushaw2\">{{cite journal |journal = Journal of Physical Oceanography| title = Baroclinic and barotropic tides in the central North Pacific Ocean determined from long-range reciprocal acoustic transmissions|year = 1995|last1 = Dushaw|first1 = B.D.|last2= Cornuelle|first2= B.D.|last3= Worcester|first3= P.F.|last4=Howe|first4= B.M.|last5= Luther|first5= D.S.|volume = 25| issue = 4|pages = 631\u2013647|doi=10.1175/1520-0485(1995)025<0631:BABTIT>2.0.CO;2 | issn = 1520-0485|doi-access= free}}</ref><ref name=\"Ray2\">{{cite journal|journal = Geophys. Res. Lett.|title = Surface manifestation of internal tides generated near Hawaii| year = 1996| last1 = Ray|first1 = R.D.|last2 = Mitchum|first2 = G.T.|volume = 23|issue = 16|pages = 2101\u20132104|doi = 10.1029/96GL02050 |bibcode = 1996GeoRL..23.2101R}}</ref> Munk recognized that the tidal energy from the scattering and radiation of large-scale internal waves from mid-ocean ridges was significant, hence it could drive abyssal mixing.<ref name=\"MunkMoon\">{{cite journal | journal = Oceanography|year=1997|title = The Moon, of course...|last1=Munk|first1=W. M.|last2=Wunsch|first2=C.|volume = 10|issue = 3 |pages = 132\u2013134|doi=10.5670/oceanog.1997.06|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\n===Munk's enigma===\nIn his later work, Munk focused on the relation between changes in ocean temperature, sea level, and the transfer of mass between continental ice and the ocean.<ref>{{cite journal|journal = Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America|title = Twentieth century sea level: An enigma| year = 2002| last1 = Munk|first1 = W.|volume = 99|issue = 10|pages = 6550\u20136555|doi = 10.1073/pnas.092704599 |pmid = 12011419|pmc = 124440}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|journal = Science|title = Ocean Freshening, Sea Level Rising| year = 2003| last1 = Munk|first1 = W.|volume = 300|issue = 5628|pages = 2041\u20132043|doi = 10.1126/science.1085534 |pmid = 12829770}}</ref>  This work described what came to be known as \"Munk's enigma\", a large discrepancy between observed rate of sea level rise and its expected effects on the earth's rotation.<ref>{{cite journal | doi=10.1126/sciadv.1500679 | pmid=26824058 | pmc=4730844 | title=Reconciling past changes in Earth's rotation with 20th century global sea-level rise: Resolving Munk's enigma | journal=Science Advances | volume=1 | issue=11 | pages=e1500679 | year=2015 | authorlink1=Jerry X. Mitrovica|last1=Mitrovica | first1=Jerry X. | last2=Hay | first2=Carling C. | last3=Morrow | first3=Eric | last4=Kopp | first4=Robert E. | last5=Dumberry | first5=Mathieu | last6=Stanley | first6=Sabine | bibcode=2015SciA....1E0679M }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Scientists may have just solved one of the most troubling mysteries about sea-level rise|author=C. Harvey |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/energy-environment/wp/2015/12/11/scientists-may-have-just-solved-one-of-the-most-troubling-mysteries-about-sea-level-rise/ |accessdate=17 February 2019 |work=Washington Post |date=11 December 2015 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=San Diego Oceanographer, 98, Spurs Research Proving Climate Change Makes Days Longer|author=D. Wagner |url=https://www.kpbs.org/news/2016/may/16/climate-change-making-days-earth-longer/ |accessdate=17 February 2019 |publisher=KPBS, San Diego Public Radio and TV |date=16 May 2016 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\n[[File:Crafoordprize 2010-34.jpg|thumb|[[Carl XVI Gustaf of Sweden]] presents the Crafoord Prize to Munk]]\nMunk was elected to the [[United States National Academy of Sciences|National Academy of Sciences]] in 1956 and to the [[Royal Society of London]] in 1976. He was both a [[Guggenheim Fellow]] (1948, 1953, 1962)<ref>{{cite web|title=Walter H. Munk|publisher=John Simon Guggenheim Memorial Foundation|url=https://www.gf.org/fellows/all-fellows/walter-h-munk/|accessdate=February 17, 2019}}</ref> and a [[Fulbright Fellow]]. He was named California Scientist of the Year by the [[California Museum of Science and Industry]] in 1969. Munk gave the 1986 [[Bakerian Lecture]] at the [[Royal Society]] on ''Ships from Space'' (paper)<ref>{{cite journal|journal=Phil. Trans. Roy. Soc. A|title=The Bakerian Lecture, 1986: Ships from Space|date=1987|last1=Munk|first1=W.H.|last2=Scully-Power|first2=P.|last3=Zachariasen|first3=F.|volume=412|issue=1843|pages=231\u2013254|bibcode=1987RSPSA.412..231M|doi=10.1098/rspa.1987.0087}}</ref> and ''Acoustic monitoring of ocean gyres'' (lecture).<ref name=\"Bakerian\">{{cite journal|journal= Bulletin of the American Meteorological Society|volume=67|issue=6|title= Conference on the variability of the atmosphere and the oceans on time scales of a month to several years |date=1986|pages=785\u2013803|doi=10.1175/1520-0477-67.6.785|bibcode=1986BAMS...67..785.|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web|publisher=The Royal Society|title=Walter Munk Biography|url=https://royalsociety.org/people/walter-munk-11986/| access-date=February 14, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|journal=J. Fluid Mech.|title=Acoustic monitoring of ocean gyres|date=1986|last1=Munk|first1=W.H.|volume=173|pages=43\u201353|doi=10.1017/S0022112086001064|bibcode=1986JFM...173...43M}}</ref> In July 2018 at the age of 100, Munk was appointed a Chevalier of France's [[Legion of Honour]] in recognition of his contributions to oceanography.<ref name=\"latimesobit\"/>\n\nAmong the many other awards and honors Munk received are the [[Arthur L. Day Medal]] of the [[Geological Society of America]] in 1965, the [[Sverdrup Gold Medal Award|Sverdrup Gold Medal]] of the [[American Meteorological Society]] in 1966, the Gold Medal of the [[Royal Astronomical Society]] in 1968, the first [[Maurice Ewing Medal]] of the [[American Geophysical Union]] and the [[U.S. Navy]] in 1976, the [[Alexander Agassiz Medal]] of the [[United States National Academy of Sciences|National Academy of Sciences]] in 1976, the [[Captain Robert Dexter Conrad Award]] of the U.S. Navy in 1978, the [[National Medal of Science]] in 1983,<ref>{{cite web |title=Walter H. Munk |url=https://www.nsf.gov/od/nms/recip_details.jsp?recip_id=248 |website=The President's National Medal of Science: Recipient Details |publisher=National Science Foundation |accessdate=8 January 2020}}</ref> the [[William Bowie Medal]] of the [[American Geophysical Union]] in 1989,<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Revelle |first1=Roger |title=1989 Bowie Medal to Walter H. Munk |journal=Eos, Transactions American Geophysical Union |date=1990 |volume=71 |issue=1 |pages=13 |doi=10.1029/EO071i001p00013|bibcode=1990EOSTr..71...13R }}</ref> the [[Vetlesen Prize]] in 1993,<ref>{{cite web |title=Walter H. Munk |url=https://www.ldeo.columbia.edu/the-vetlesen-prize/past-recipients/walter-h-munk |website=The Vetlesen Prize |publisher=Lamont-Doherty Earth Observatory |accessdate=8 January 2020}}</ref> the [[Kyoto Prize]] in 1999,<ref>{{cite web |title=Walter H. Munk |url=https://www.kyotoprize.org/en/laureates/walter_h_munk/ |website=Kyoto Prize |accessdate=8 January 2020}}</ref> the first [[Prince Albert I Medal]] in 2001, and the [[Crafoord Prize]] of the [[Royal Swedish Academy of Sciences]] in 2010 \"for his pioneering and fundamental contributions to our understanding of ocean circulation, tides and waves, and their role in the Earth's dynamics\".<ref name=\"Crafoord\">{{cite web |title=The Crafoord Prize in Geosciences 2010 |url=https://www.crafoordprize.se/press_release/the-crafoord-prize-in-geosciences-2010 |publisher=The Royal Swedish Academy of Sciences |accessdate=8 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Crafoord_Lecture\"/>\n\nIn 1993, Munk was the first recipient of the [[Oceanography Society#Walter Munk Award|Walter Munk Award]] given \"in Recognition of Distinguished Research in Oceanography Related to Sound and the Sea.\"<ref name=\"ocea-munk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tos.org/awards_honors/munk_award.html|title=The Walter Munk Award|publisher=Oceanography Society|accessdate=July 26, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100323035643/http://www.tos.org/awards_honors/munk_award.html|archivedate=March 23, 2010}}</ref> This award was given jointly by [[The Oceanography Society]], the [[Office of Naval Research]] and the US Department of Defense [[Naval Oceanographic Office]].<ref name=\"ocea-munk\" />  The award was retired in 2018, and The Oceanographic Society \"established the Walter Munk Medal to encompass a broader range of topics in physical oceanography.\"<ref name=\"munkaward\">{{cite web|url=https://tos.org/munk-award|title=The Walter Munk Award|publisher=Oceanography Society|accessdate=January 9, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"munkmedal\">{{cite web|url=https://tos.org/munk-medal|title=The Walter Munk Medal|publisher=Oceanography Society|accessdate=January 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Mobula breach 2.jpg|thumb|Munk's devil ray]]\nTwo marine species have been named after Munk. One is ''Sirsoe munki'', a deep-sea worm. The other is ''[[Mobula munkiana]]'', also known as Munk's devil ray, a pygmy ray with a remarkable ability to leap far out of the water.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tu |first1=Chau |title=Picture of the Week: Munk's Devil Ray |url=https://www.sciencefriday.com/articles/picture-of-the-week-munks-devil-ray/ |accessdate=10 January 2020 |work=Science Friday |date=9 June 2014}}</ref> A 2017 documentary, ''[[Spirit of Discovery (Documentary)]]'', follows Munk in an expedition with the discoverer, [[Giuseppe Notarbartolo di Sciara]], to [[Cabo Pulmo National Park]] in Baja Mexico, one of the few places in the world where the rays can be found.<ref name=Scripps_obit/><ref>{{cite web |last1=Martinez |first1=Eliana Alvarez |title=About |url=https://spiritofdiscovery.co/about/ |website=Spirit of Discovery |accessdate=10 January 2020 |language=en |date=2 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nAfter [[Nazi Germany]] annexed Austria in 1938, an event known as the [[Anschluss]], Munk applied to be a citizen of the United States.<ref name=\"DDay\"/> In his first attempt, he failed the citizenship test by giving an overly-detailed answer to a question about the [[United States Constitution|Constitution]].<ref name=\"70yrs\"/>{{rp|20}} He obtained American citizenship in 1939.<ref name=\"70yrs\"/>{{rp|20}}\n\nMunk married Martha Chapin in the late 1940s. The marriage ended in divorce in 1953.<ref name=\"70yrs\"/>{{rp|31}} On June 20, 1953, he married [[Judith Munk|Judith Horton]]. She was an active participant at Scripps for decades, where she contributed to campus planning, architecture, and the renovation and reuse of historical buildings. The Munks were frequent traveling companions.<ref name=\"Affairs\"/> Judith died in 2006.<ref name=JudithObit>{{cite news |last1=Aguilera |first1=Mario |title=Obituary Notice: Judith Munk, Friend and Artistic Influence |url=https://scripps.ucsd.edu/news/13867 |accessdate=8 January 2020 |work=Scripps Institution of Oceanography |date=24 May 2006 |language=en}}</ref> In 2011, Munk married La Jolla community leader Mary Coakley.<ref name=\"TimesSD\">{{Cite web|url=https://timesofsandiego.com/tech/2019/02/08/scripps-oceanographer-walter-munk-dead-at-101/|title=Pioneering Scripps Oceanographer Walter Munk Dead at 101|last=McAllister|first=Toni|date=February 8, 2019|website=Times of San Diego|language=en-US|access-date=February 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\nMunk [[centenarian|turned 100]] in October 2017.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Spence |first1=Paul |last2=Keating |first2=Shane |title=Walter Munk, known as the 'Einstein of the ocean,' has turned 100 |url=https://www.newsweek.com/sport-surfing-walter-munk-688360 |accessdate=7 January 2020 |work=Newsweek |date=19 October 2017 |language=en}}</ref> He died of [[pneumonia]] on February 8, 2019 at La Jolla, California, aged 101.<ref name=Scripps_obit/><ref>{{cite news |last1=Dicke |first1=William |title=Walter H. Munk, Scientist-Explorer Who Illuminated the Deep, Dies at 101 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/02/09/obituaries/walter-h-munk-scientist-explorer-who-illuminated-the-deep-dies-at-101.html |newspaper=[[New York Times]] |accessdate=February 10, 2019 |language=English |date=February 9, 2019 |quote=She said the cause of death was pneumonia.}}</ref>\n\n== Publications ==\n=== Scientific papers ===\nMunk published 181 scientific papers. They were cited over 11,000 times, an average of 63 times each. Some of the most highly cited papers in the [[Web of Science]] database are listed below.\n*{{cite journal |last1=Munk |first1=W. H. |title=On the wind-driven ocean circulation |journal=Journal of Meteorology |date=1950 |volume=7 |issue=2 |pages=79\u201393|doi=10.1175/1520-0469(1950)007<0080:OTWDOC>2.0.CO;2 |bibcode=1950JAtS....7...80M |doi-access=free }}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Cox |first1=Charles |last2=Munk |first2=Walter |title=Measurement of the Roughness of the Sea Surface from Photographs of the Sun's Glitter |journal=Journal of the Optical Society of America |date=1 November 1954 |volume=44 |issue=11 |pages=838 |doi=10.1364/JOSA.44.000838|bibcode=1954JOSA...44..838C |url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/315d0c8c6238f5f4f7dd16851069ab76b74ec0cc }}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Munk |first1=Walter H. |title=Abyssal recipes |journal=Deep Sea Research and Oceanographic Abstracts |date=August 1966 |volume=13 |issue=4 |pages=707\u2013730 |doi=10.1016/0011-7471(66)90602-4|bibcode=1966DSROA..13..707M }}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Munk |first1=W. H. |last2=Cartwright |first2=D. E. |title=Tidal Spectroscopy and Prediction |journal=Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society A: Mathematical, Physical and Engineering Sciences |date=19 May 1966 |volume=259 |issue=1105 |pages=533\u2013581 |doi=10.1098/rsta.1966.0024|bibcode=1966RSPTA.259..533M }}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Garrett |first1=Christopher |last2=Munk |first2=Walter |title=Space-time scales of internal waves: A progress report |journal=Journal of Geophysical Research |date=20 January 1975 |volume=80 |issue=3 |pages=291\u2013297 |doi=10.1029/JC080i003p00291|bibcode=1975JGR....80..291G |url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/fc045c47fd078c8d41465b70803e7682065b53ab }}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Munk |first1=Walter |last2=Wunsch |first2=Carl |title=Ocean acoustic tomography: a scheme for large scale monitoring |journal=Deep Sea Research Part A. Oceanographic Research Papers |date=February 1979 |volume=26 |issue=2 |pages=123\u2013161 |doi=10.1016/0198-0149(79)90073-6|bibcode=1979DSRA...26..123M }}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Garrett |first1=C |last2=Munk |first2=W |title=Internal Waves in the Ocean |journal=Annual Review of Fluid Mechanics |date=January 1979 |volume=11 |issue=1 |pages=339\u2013369 |doi=10.1146/annurev.fl.11.010179.002011|bibcode=1979AnRFM..11..339G }}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Munk |first1=Walter |last2=Wunsch |first2=Carl |title=Abyssal recipes II: energetics of tidal and wind mixing |journal=Deep Sea Research Part I: Oceanographic Research Papers |date=December 1998 |volume=45 |issue=12 |pages=1977\u20132010 |doi=10.1016/S0967-0637(98)00070-3|bibcode=1998DSRI...45.1977M }}\n\n=== Books ===\n* W. Munk and G.J.F. MacDonald, ''The Rotation of the Earth: A Geophysical Discussion'', Cambridge University Press, 1960, revised 1975. {{ISBN|0-521-20778-9}}\n* W. Munk, P. Worcester, and C. Wunsch, ''Ocean Acoustic Tomography'', Cambridge University Press, 1995. {{ISBN|0-521-47095-1}}\n* S. Flatt\u00e9 (ed.), R. Dashen, W. H. Munk, K. M. Watson, and F. Zachariasen, ''Sound Transmission through a Fluctuating Ocean'', Cambridge University Press, 1979. {{ISBN|978-0-521-21940-2}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Walter Munk}}\n*   {{YouTube|MX5cKoOm6Pk|Waves Across the Pacific}} (1967) \u2013 a documentary showcasing Munk's research on waves generated by Antarctic storms. The film documents Munk's collaboration as they track storm-driven waves from Antarctica across the Pacific Ocean to Alaska. The film features scenes of early digital equipment in use in field experiments with Munk's commentary on how unsure they were about using such new technology in remote locations.\n* {{YouTube|je3QvqNdHl0|One Man's Noise: Stories of An Adventuresome Oceanographer}} (1994) \u2013 a television program on the work and life of Walter Munk produced by the University of California.\n* {{YouTube|lks2hh6LGsE|Perspectives on Ocean Science: Global Sea Level: An Enigma}} (2004) \u2013 a seminar on global sea level and climate change by Walter Munk. (YouTube link)\n* [http://www.crafoordprize.se/events/crafoorddays2010.4.5ce3bd8012d79a5929580004998.html The Sound of Climate Change] (2010) \u2013 Munk's Crafoord Prize Lecture\n* [http://www.spiritofdiscovery.co Spirit of Discovery] (2017) \u2013 a documentary showcasing Munk as he goes in search of ''Mobula munkiana'' a species that bears his name.\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EaW_ghP7HPI A Conversation with Walter Munk] (2019) \u2013 Carl Wunsch interviews Walter Munk about his life, career, and scientific events and people during his life on the occasion of his 100th birthday in 2017.\n* [https://www.aip.org/history-programs/niels-bohr-library/oral-histories/4790 Oral History interview transcript with Walter Munk 30 June 1986, American Institute of Physics, Niels Bohr Library and Archives]\n* [http://faculty.washington.edu/dushaw/heard/index.shtml The Heard Island Feasibility Test]\n* [https://scripps.ucsd.edu/news/tributes-walter-munk Tributes to Walter Munk] (Scripps)\n\n{{Founding members of the World Cultural Council}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Munk, Walter}}\n[[Category:1917 births]]\n[[Category:2019 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from La Jolla, San Diego]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States National Academy of Sciences]]\n[[Category:California Institute of Technology alumni]]\n[[Category:Columbia University alumni]]\n[[Category:Foreign Members of the Royal Society]]\n[[Category:Foreign Members of the Russian Academy of Sciences]]\n[[Category:Jewish American scientists]]\n[[Category:Kyoto laureates in Basic Sciences]]\n[[Category:National Medal of Science laureates]]\n[[Category:American centenarians]]\n[[Category:American oceanographers]]\n[[Category:Fluid dynamicists]]\n[[Category:Guggenheim Fellows]]\n[[Category:Scripps Institution of Oceanography faculty]]\n[[Category:Scripps Institution of Oceanography alumni]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Gold Medal of the Royal Astronomical Society]]\n[[Category:American people of Austrian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Austrian Jews]]\n[[Category:Scientists from Vienna]]\n[[Category:Austrian centenarians]]\n[[Category:University of California, San Diego faculty]]\n[[Category:Members of JASON]]\n[[Category:Founding members of the World Cultural Council]]\n[[Category:Sverdrup Gold Medal Award Recipients]]\n[[Category:Writers from San Diego]]\n[[Category:Writers from Vienna]]\n", "text_old": "{{good article}}\n{{short description|American oceanographer}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| birth_name = Walter Heinrich Munk\n| image = Crafoordprize 2010-03.jpg\n| caption = Munk in [[Stockholm]] in 2010 to accept his [[Crafoord Prize]].\n| birth_date = {{birth date|mf=yes|1917|10|19}}\n| birth_place = [[Vienna]], [[Austria-Hungary]]\n| death_date = {{death date and age|2019|2|8|1917|10|19}}<ref name=Scripps_obit/>\n<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dicke |first1=William |title=Walter H. Munk, Scientist-Explorer Who Illuminated the Deep, Dies at 101 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/02/09/obituaries/walter-h-munk-scientist-explorer-who-illuminated-the-deep-dies-at-101.html |accessdate=11 February 2019 |work=The New York Times |date=9 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=NBC 7 Staff |title=World-Renowned Oceanographer Walter Munk Dies at 101 |url=https://www.nbcsandiego.com/news/local/World-Renowned-Oceanographer-Walter-Munk-Dies-at-101-505598621.html |accessdate=11 February 2019 |work=NBC 7 San Diego |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"latimesobit\">{{cite news |last1=Robbins |first1=Gary |title=Walter Munk, La Jolla scientist-explorer dubbed the 'Einstein of the Oceans,' dies at 101 |url=https://www.latimes.com/local/obituaries/la-me-ln-walter-munk-obit-20190209-story.html |accessdate=11 February 2019 |work=latimes.com}}</ref>\n| death_place  =  [[La Jolla, California]], U.S.\n| nationality = USA\n| fields = [[Oceanography]], [[geophysics]]\n| alma_mater        = [[California Institute of Technology]] (BS,MS)<br />[[Scripps Institution of Oceanography]]/[[University of California, Los Angeles]] (PhD)\n| doctoral_advisor = [[Harald Sverdrup (oceanographer)|Harald Ulrik Sverdrup]]\n| thesis_title =  Increase in the period of waves traveling over large distances : with applications to tsunamis, swell, and seismic surface waves (1946)\n<ref name=\"PhD\">{{cite web | url=https://catalog.library.ucla.edu/vwebv/holdingsInfo?bibId=2498202 | \ntitle =Increase in the period of waves traveling over large distances: with applications to tsunamis, swell, and seismic surface waves|author=Walter Munk|publisher =University of California, Los Angeles Library |date=1946|pages=41|accessdate=February 18, 2019}}</ref> \n| doctoral_students = [[Charles Shipley Cox]]\n| awards = {{nowrap|[[Maurice Ewing Medal]] (1976)<br />[[Alexander Agassiz Medal]] (1976)<br />[[National Medal of Science]] (1985)<br />[[Bakerian Lecture]] (1986)<br />[[William Bowie Medal]] (1989)<br />[[Vetlesen Prize]] (1993)<br />[[Kyoto Prize]] (1999)<br />[[Prince Albert I Medal]] (2001)<br />[[Crafoord Prize]] (2010)}}\n}}\n'''Walter Heinrich Munk''' (October 19, 1917,  [[Vienna]], [[Austria-Hungary]]<ref name=\"NYTimes1\" /> \u2013 February 8, 2019,  La Jolla, California.<ref name=\"Scripps_obit\">{{Cite web|url=https://scripps.ucsd.edu/news/obituary-notice-walter-munk-world-renowned-oceanographer-revered-scientist|title=Obituary Notice: Walter Munk, World-Renowned Oceanographer, Revered Scientist|date=February 8, 2019|website=Scripps Institution of Oceanography|language=en|access-date=February 9, 2019}}</ref> ) was an American [[physical oceanography|physical oceanographer]].<ref name=Scripps_obit/><ref name=\"Yam\">{{cite journal|last1=Yam|first1=P|year=1995|title=Profile: Walter H. Munk \u2013 The Man Who Would Hear Ocean Temperatures|url=|journal=[[Scientific American]]|volume=272|issue=1|pages=38\u201340|doi=10.1038/scientificamerican0195-38|bibcode=1995SciAm.272a..38Y}}</ref> One of the first scientists to bring statistical methods to the analysis of oceanographic data, Munk's work is noted for creating fruitful areas of research that continue to be explored by other scientists. For these achievements. Munk received a number of prestigious awards including the [[National Medal of Science]], the [[Kyoto Prize]], and induction to the French [[Legion of Honour]].\n\nMunk worked on a wide range of topics, including [[Surface wave|surface waves]], geophysical implications of [[Milankovitch cycles|variations in the Earth's rotation]], [[tide]]s, [[internal wave]]s, deep-ocean drilling into the sea floor, acoustical measurements of ocean properties, [[sea level rise]], and [[Global warming|climate change]]. Beginning in 1975, Munk and [[Carl Wunsch]] developed [[ocean acoustic tomography]], to exploit the ease with which sound travels in the ocean and use acoustical signals for measurement of broad-scale temperature and current. In a 1991 experiment, Munk and his collaborators investigated the ability of underwater sound to propagate from the Southern Indian Ocean across all ocean basins. The aim was to measure global ocean temperature. The experiment was criticized by environmental groups, who expected that the loud acoustic signals would adversely affect marine life. Munk continued to develop and advocate for acoustical measurements of the ocean throughout his career.\n\nMunk's career was long and complicated. World War II disrupted his doctoral studies at the [[Scripps Institution of Oceanography]] (Scripps), and led to his participation in U.S. military research efforts.  Munk and his doctoral advisor [[Harald Sverdrup (oceanographer)|Harald Sverdrup]] developed methods for forecasting wave conditions which were used in support of beach landings in all theaters of the war.  He was involved with oceanographic programs during the [[Operation Crossroads|atomic bomb tests in Bikini Atoll]].  For most of his career, he was a professor of [[geophysics]] at Scripps at the [[University of California]] in [[La Jolla, California|La Jolla]].  Additionally, Munk and his wife [[Judith Munk|Judy]] were active in developing the Scripps campus and integrating it with the new [[University of California, San Diego]]. Munk's career included a number of prestigious positions, including being a member of the [[JASON (advisory group)|JASON]] [[think tank]], and holding the Secretary of the Navy/Chief of Naval Operations Oceanography Chair.   \n\n== Early life and education ==\nIn 1917, Munk was born to a Jewish family in [[Vienna]], [[Austria-Hungary]].<ref name=\"NYTimes1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/25/science/walter-munk-einstein-of-the-oceans-at-97.html|title=Walter Munk, the 'Einstein of the Oceans'|last=Galbraith|first=Kate|date=August 24, 2015|work=The New York Times|access-date=February 10, 2019|language=en-US}}</ref> His father, Dr. Hans Munk, and his mother, Rega Brunner, divorced when he was ten years old.<ref name=\"70yrs\"/>{{rp|14}}<ref name=\"DDay\"/> His maternal grandfather was Lucian Brunner (1850\u20131914), a prominent banker and Austrian politician. His stepfather, Dr. Rudolf Engelsberg, was head of the salt mine monopoly of the Austrian government and a member of the Austrian governments of Chancellor [[Engelbert Dollfuss]] and Chancellor [[Kurt Schuschnigg]].<ref name=\"70yrs\"/>{{rp|14}}<ref name=\"munk30s\">{{cite journal|title=Introducing Walter Munk, or \"The Old Man and the Sea\"|last=Adelmann|first=Pepita|date=April 15, 2008|journal=Bridges|volume=17|url=https://ostaustria.org/bridges-magazine/volume-17-april-28-2008/item/3027-introducing-walter-munk-or-the-old-man-and-the-sea|access-date=February 16, 2019|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"Armi\">{{cite web | url=https://opensky.ucar.edu/islandora/object/archives%3A7621 | \ntitle =Transcript of Oral History interview of Walter Munk |author=Lawrence Armi|publisher =American Meteorological Society Oral History Project, National Center for Atmospheric Research |date=28 September 1994|accessdate=February 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 1932, Munk was performing poorly in school because he was spending too much time skiing, so his family sent him from Austria to a boys' preparatory school in upper New York state.<ref name=\"Affairs\">{{cite journal|doi=10.1146/annurev.ea.08.050180.000245|journal=[[Annual Review of Earth and Planetary Sciences]]|volume=8|date=1980|pages=1\u201317|title=Affairs of the Sea|author=Munk, Walter H.|bibcode=1980AREPS...8....1M|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/1f1caf61e70de4060320f71365ad11a95077a824}}</ref><ref name=\"70yrs\">{{cite book|publisher=Springer-Verlag|location=Berlin|title=Seventy Years of Exploration in Oceanography: A Prolonged Weekend Discussion with Walter Munk|date=2010|first=Hans|last=von Storch|author2=Klaus Hasselmann|isbn=978-3-642-12086-2|doi=10.1007/978-3-642-12087-9 |url=http://www.hvonstorch.de/klima/books/munk-springer-final.pdf}}</ref>{{rp|14}} His family envisioned a career for him in finance with a New York bank connected to the family business.<ref name=\"70yrs\"/>{{rp|14}} He worked at the family's banking firm for three years and studied at [[Columbia University]].<ref name=\"70yrs\"/>{{rp|14}}\n\nMunk hated banking. In 1937, he left the firm to attend the [[California Institute of Technology]] (Caltech) in [[Pasadena]].<ref name=\"70yrs\"/>{{rp|17}} While at Caltech, he took a summer job in 1939 at the [[Scripps Institution of Oceanography]] (Scripps) in [[La Jolla, California]].<ref name=\"munk30s\" /><ref name=WunschObit>{{cite journal |last1=Wunsch |first1=Carl |title=Walter Munk (1917-2019) |journal=Nature |date=28 February 2019 |volume=567 |issue=7747 |pages=176 |doi=10.1038/d41586-019-00750-5|bibcode=2019Natur.567..176W |doi-access=free }}</ref>  Munk earned a [[Bachelor's degree|B.S.]] in applied physics in 1939<ref name=\"Affairs\"/> and an [[master's degree|M.S.]] in geophysics (under [[Beno Gutenberg]]<ref name=\"Affairs\"/>) in 1940 at Caltech.<ref name=\"70yrs\"/>{{rp|105}}<ref name=\"msthesis\">{{cite thesis|last=Munk|first=Walter H.|date=1940|title=Internal waves in the Gulf of California|publisher=California Institute of Technology|url=http://resolver.caltech.edu/CaltechETD:etd-06162004-140251}}</ref> The master's degree work was based on oceanographic data collected in the [[Gulf of California]] by the [[Norway|Norwegian]] oceanographer [[Harald Sverdrup (oceanographer)|Harald Sverdrup]], then director of Scripps.<ref name=\"Armi\"/>\n\nIn 1939, Munk asked Sverdrup to take him on as a doctoral student. Sverdrup agreed, although Munk recalled him saying \"I can't think of a single job that's going to become available in the next ten years in oceanography\".<ref name=\"Armi\"/> Munk's studies were interrupted by the outbreak of [[World War II]]. He completed his doctoral degree in oceanography at Scripps under the [[University of California, Los Angeles]] in 1947.<ref name=\"PhD\"/><ref name=\"70yrs\"/>{{rp|105}} He wrote it in three weeks and it is the \"shortest Scripps dissertation on record.\" He later realized that its principal conclusion is wrong.<ref name=\"Affairs\"/>\n\n== Wartime activities ==\nIn 1940, Munk enlisted the [[U.S. Army]]. This was unusual for a student at Scripps: all the others joined the [[U.S. Naval Reserve]].<ref name=\"DDay\">{{cite web|url=http://scilib.ucsd.edu/sio/biogr/Munk_Biogr.pdf|title=Walter Heinrich Munk Biography|author=D. Day|date=August 31, 2005|work=Scripps Institution of Oceanography Archives|accessdate=February 17, 2019}}</ref> After serving 18 months in [[Field Artillery Branch (United States)|Field Artillery]] and the [[Ski warfare|Ski Troops]],<ref name=\"Affairs\"/> he was discharged at the request of Sverdrup and [[Roger Revelle]] so he could undertake defense-related research at Scripps. In December 1941, a week before the Japanese [[Attack on Pearl Harbor]], he joined several of his colleagues from Scripps at the [[U.S. Navy]] [[Radio and Sound Laboratory]].<ref name=\"70yrs\"/>{{rp|20}} For six years they developed methods related to [[Anti-submarine warfare|antisubmarine]] and [[amphibious warfare]].<ref name=\"Affairs\"/> This research involved marine acoustics, and eventually led to his work on [[#Ocean acoustic tomography|ocean acoustic tomography]].<ref name=\"Scripps_obit\"/>\n\n===Predicting surf conditions for Allied landings===\nIn 1943, Munk and Sverdrup began looking for a way to predict the heights of ocean surface waves. The Allies were preparing for a [[Operation Torch|landing in North Africa]], where two out of every three days the waves are above six feet. Practice beach landings in [[the Carolinas]] were suspended when waves reached this height because they were dangerous to people and landing craft.<ref name=\"Affairs\"/><ref name=\"70yrs\"/>{{rp|3}} Munk and Sverdrup found an empirical law that related wave height and period to the speed and duration of the wind and the [[Fetch (geography)|distance over which it blows]].<ref name=\"Affairs\"/> The Allies applied this method in the [[Pacific War|Pacific theater of war]] and the [[Normandy invasion]] on [[D-Day]].<ref name=\"munk30s\" /><ref>{{Citation|last=U.S. Navy|title=Dr Walter Munk explains his role in Operation Overlord|date=April 8, 2014|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=t7DtckkgvWQ|accessdate=June 7, 2018}}</ref> \n\nOfficials at the time estimated that many lives were saved by these predictions.<ref name=\"Kinsman\">{{cite book|publisher=Prentice Hall|location=Englewood Cliffs, N.J.|title=Wind Waves: Their Generation and Propagation on the Ocean Surface|date=1965|first=Blair|last=Kinsman|isbn=978-0139603440|doi=}}</ref>{{rp|321}} Munk commented in 2009:<ref name=\"CBS8\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cbs8.com/Global/story.asp?S=9866733|title=Walter Munk: One Of The World's Greatest Living Oceanographers|work=CBS 8|date=November 2, 2009|accessdate=August 20, 2010}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote|text=The Normandy landing is famous because weather conditions were very poor and you may not realize it was postponed by General Eisenhower for 24 hours because of the prevailing wave conditions. And then he did decide, in spite of the fact that conditions were not favorable, it would be better to go in than lose the surprise element, which would have been lost if they waited for the next tidal cycle [in] two weeks.}}\n\n===Oceanographic measurements during atomic weapons tests in the Pacific===\nIn 1946, the United States tested two fission [[nuclear weapons]] (20 kilotons) at [[Bikini Atoll]] in the equatorial Pacific in [[Operation Crossroads]]. Munk helped to determine the [[Ocean current|currents]], diffusion, and water exchanges affecting the radiation contamination from the second test, code-named Baker.<ref name=\"munk30s\"/><ref name=\"NYTimes1\"/> Six years later he returned to the equatorial Pacific for the 1952 test of the first fusion nuclear weapon (10 megatons) at [[Eniwetok Atoll]], code-named [[Ivy Mike]].<ref name=\"70yrs\"/>{{rp|25}}  [[Roger Revelle]], [[John Dove Isaacs|John Isaacs]], and Munk had initiated a program for monitoring for the possibility of a large [[tsunami]] generated from the test.<ref name=\"70yrs\"/>{{rp|26}}\n\n===Later association with the military===\nMunk continued to have a close association with the military in later decades. He was one of the first academics to be funded by the [[Office of Naval Research]], and had his last grant from them when he was 97.<ref name=WunschObit/> In 1968, he became a member of [[JASON (advisory group)|JASON]], a panel of scientists who advise the Pentagon, and he continued in that role until the end of his life.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Walter Munk|date=October 17, 2017|work=Physics Today|language=en-US|doi=10.1063/PT.6.6.20171019a}}</ref> He held a Secretary of the Navy/Chief of Naval Operations Oceanography Chair from 1985 until his death in 2019.<ref name=\"70yrs\"/>{{rp|99,105}}\n\n==The Institute of Geophysics and Planetary Physics in La Jolla==\nAfter receiving his doctorate in 1947, Munk was hired by Scripps as an assistant professor of geophysics. He became a full professor there in 1954,<ref>{{cite web|title=Walter Munk Biography, Research Professor of Geophysics Cecil H. and Ida M. Green Institute of Geophysics and Planetary Physics|work= Scripps Institution of Oceanography University of California, San Diego|date=March 2017|access-date=February 14, 2019|url=http://scrippsscholars.ucsd.edu/wmunk/biocv}}</ref> but his appointment was at the Institute of Geophysics (IGP) at the [[University of California, Los Angeles]] (UCLA). In 1955, Munk took a sabbatical at Cambridge, England.<ref name=\"70yrs\"/>{{rp|75}}  His experience at Cambridge led to the idea of starting a new IGP branch at Scripps.<ref name=\"70yrs\"/>{{rp|75}}\n\nAt the time of Munk's return to Scripps, it was still under the administration of UCLA, as it had been since 1938. It became part of the [[University of California, San Diego]] (UCSD) when that campus was founded in 1958.<ref name=\"Stadtman1\">{{cite book |url=https://archive.org/details/universityofcali00stad|url-access=registration|last=Stadtman |first=Verne A. |year=1970 |title=The University of California, 1868-1968|pages= [https://archive.org/details/universityofcali00stad/page/407 407]\u2013411|publisher=[[McGraw-Hill]]|accessdate=May 5, 2013}}</ref> Revelle, its director at the time, was a primary advocate for establishing the La Jolla campus.<ref>{{cite journal|journal = Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America|title =Tribute to Roger Revelle and his contribution to studies of carbon dioxide and climate change | year = 1997| last1 = Munk|first1 = W.|volume = 94|issue = 16|pages = 8275\u20138279|doi = 10.1073/pnas.94.16.8275 |pmid = 11607733|pmc = 33716|bibcode =1997PNAS...94.8275M }}</ref> At this time Munk was considering offers for new positions at the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] and [[Harvard University]], but Revelle encouraged Munk to remain in La Jolla.<ref name=\"70yrs\"/>{{rp|75}} Munk's founding of IGP at La Jolla was concurrent with the creation of the UCSD campus.\n\nThe IGPP laboratory was built between 1959 and 1963 with funding from the University of California, the U.S. Air Force Office of Scientific Research, the [[National Science Foundation]], and private foundations.<ref name=\"IGPP\">{{cite news|title=The Cecil H. and Ida M. Green Institute of Geophysics and Planetary Physics (IGPP)|author=W. Munk|author2=F. Gilbert|author3=J. Orcutt|author4=M. Zumberg|author5=R. Parker|journal=Oceanography|volume=16|pages=34\u201344|date=2003|url=http://scilib.ucsd.edu/sio/hist/igpp-oceanography.pdf|doi=10.5670/oceanog.2003.29}}</ref><ref name=\"IGPPWEB\">{{cite news|title=The Cecil H. and Ida M. Green Institute of Geophysics and Planetary Physics (IGPP)|url=http://igpp.ucsd.edu/about/history|accessdate=November 2, 2010}}</ref> (After planetary physics was added, IGP changed its name to the Institute of Geophysics and Planetary Physics (IGPP).<ref name=\"70yrs\"/>{{rp|75}}) The redwood building was designed by architect Lloyd Ruocco, in close consultation with Judith and Walter Munk. The IGPP buildings have become the center of the Scripps campus. Among the early faculty appointments were [[Carl Eckart]], [[George E. Backus|George Backus]], [[Freeman Gilbert]] and [[John W. Miles|John Miles]]. The eminent geophysicist [[Edward Bullard|Sir Edward \"Teddy\" Bullard]] was a regular visitor to IGPP. In 1971 an endowment of $600,000 was established by [[Cecil Howard Green|Cecil Green]] to support visiting scholars, now known as Green Scholars. Munk served as director of IGPP/LJ from 1962 to 1982.<ref name=\"IGPP\"/><ref name=\"70yrs\"/>{{rp|81}}\n\nIn the late 1980s, plans for an expansion of IGPP were developed by Judith and Walter Munk, and Sharyn and John Orcutt, in consultation with a local architect, Fred Liebhardt.<ref name=\"IGPP\"/> The Revelle Laboratory was completed in 1993. At this time the original IGPP building was renamed the Walter and Judith Munk Laboratory for Geophysics. In 1994 the Scripps branch of IGPP was renamed the Cecil H. and Ida M. Green Institute of Geophysics and Planetary Physics.<ref name=\"IGPP\"/>\n\n==Research==\nMunk's career in oceanography and geophysics touched on disparate and innovative topics.  A pattern of Munk's work was that he would initiate a completely new topic; ask challenging, fundamental questions about the subject and its larger meaning; and then, having created an entirely new sub-field of science, move on to another new topic.<ref name=Scripps_obit/><ref name=\"RSPW\">{{cite journal|last1=Spindel|first1=R.C.|last2=Worcester|first2=P.F. |year=2016|title=Walter H. Munk: Seventy-Five Years of Exploring the Seas|journal=Acoustics Today|volume=12|issue=1|pages=36\u201342|url=https://acousticstoday.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/Walter-H.-Munk-Seventy-Five-Years-of-Exploring-the-Seas.pdf|access-date=February 19, 2019|doi=|bibcode=}}</ref>  As [[Carl Wunsch]], one of Munk's frequent collaborators,<ref name=\"Wunsch\">{{cite journal|title=A Conversation with Walter Munk|last1=Munk|first1=Walter|last2=Wunsch|first2=Carl|year=2019|journal=Annual Review of Marine Science|volume=11|pages=15\u201325|doi=10.1146/annurev-marine-010318-095353|pmid=29751736|bibcode=2019ARMS...11...15M}}</ref> commented:<ref name=\"70yrs\"/>{{rp|vi}}\n\n{{Quote|text=[Walter has] a sometimes uncanny ability to delineate the essence - that had eluded his predecessors - of a central problem. He has the knack of defining a field in a way that requires decades of subsequent work by others to fully flesh-out, while he himself moves on. One of his explicitly stated themes is that it is more important to ask the right questions than it is to give the right answers.}}\n\n===Wind-driven gyres===\n[[File:Oceanic gyres.png|thumb|300px|right|The five major ocean gyres]]\nIn 1948, Munk took a year's sabbatical to visit Sverdrup in [[Oslo]], Norway on his first [[Guggenheim Fellowship]].<ref name=\"DDay\"/>  He worked on the problem of wind-driven [[ocean circulation]],<ref name=\"70yrs\"/>{{rp|34}} obtaining the first comprehensive solution for currents based on observed wind patterns.<ref name=Pond>{{cite book |last1=Pond |first1=Stephen |last2=Pickard |first2=George L. |title=Introductory dynamical oceanography |date=2013 |publisher=Elsevier |isbn=9780080570549 |pages=138\u2013144 |edition=Second}}</ref> This included two types of [[viscosity|friction]]: horizontal friction between water masses moving at different velocities or between water and the edges of the oceanic basin,<ref name=CrafoordInfo>{{cite web |last1=Royal Swedish Academy of Sciences |title=Always count on the oceans |url=https://s3.eu-de.cloud-object-storage.appdomain.cloud/crafoord-image-pdf/2017/11/pop_CraGeo_en_100121_FINAL.pdf |website=The Crafoord Prize |accessdate=9 January 2020}}</ref> and friction from a vertical velocity gradient in the top layer of the ocean (the [[Ekman layer]]).<ref name=Pond/> The model predicted the five main [[ocean gyre]]s (pictured), with rapid, narrow currents  in the west flowing towards the poles and broader, slower currents in the east flowing away from the poles.<ref name=CrafoordInfo/> Munk coined the term \"ocean gyres,\" a term now widely used.<ref name=\"70yrs\"/>{{rp|34}} The currents predicted for the western boundaries (e.g., for the [[Gulf Stream]] and the [[Kuroshio Current]]) were about half of the accepted values at the time, but those only considered the most intense flow and neglected a large return flow. Later estimates agreed well with Munk's predictions.<ref name=Pond/>\n\n===Rotation of the Earth===\nIn the 1950s, Munk investigated irregularities in the Earth's rotation \u2013 [[Day length fluctuations|changes in the length of day]] (rate of the Earth's rotation) and changes in the axis of rotation (such as the [[Chandler wobble]], which has a period of about 14 months). The latter gives rise to a small tide called the [[Long period tide#Pole tide|pole tide]]. Although the scientific community knew of these fluctuations, they did not have adequate explanations for them. With [[Gordon J. F. MacDonald]], Munk published ''The Rotation of the Earth: A Geophysical Discussion'' in 1960. This book discusses the effects from a geophysical, rather than astronomical, perspective. It shows that short-term variations are caused by movement in the atmosphere, ocean, underground water, and interior of the Earth, including [[tide]]s in the ocean and solid Earth. Over longer times (a century or more), the largest influence is the [[tidal acceleration]] that causes the Moon to move away from the Earth at about four centimeters per year. This gradually slows Earth's rotation, so that over 500 million years the length of day has increased from 21 hours to 24.<ref name=CrafoordInfo/> The monograph remains a standard reference.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Groves|first1=G.W. |editor1-last=Kopal |editor1-first=Zden\u011bk |title=Physics and Astronomy of the Moon|publisher=Academic Press|date=1961|chapter=Dynamics of the Earth-Moon System|pages=61\u201398|location=New York|isbn=9781483270784}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|journal=Phil. Trans. Roy. Soc. A|title=The Earth's variable rate of rotation: A discussion of some meteorological and oceanic causes and consequences|date=1977|last1=Lambeck|first1=K.|last2=Cazenave|first2=A.|volume=284|issue=1326|pages=495\u2013506|doi=10.1098/rsta.1977.0025|bibcode=1977RSPTA.284..495L}}</ref>\n<!-- Munk was the first to show rigorously why one side of the [[Moon]] always faces the Earth (Munk and McDonald, 1960; and later papers up to 1975), a phenomenon known as [[tidal locking]].{{cn|date=February 2019}}{{dubious|Tidal locking|date=February 2019}} [[William Thomson, 1st Baron Kelvin|Lord Kelvin]] had also considered this question, and had fashioned a non-quantitative answer being roughly correct. The Moon does not have a molten liquid core, so cannot rotate through the egg-shaped distortion caused by the Earth's gravitational pull. Rotation through this shape requires internal shearing, and only fluids are capable of such rotation with small frictional losses. Thus, the pointy end of the \"egg\" is gravitationally locked to always point directly towards the Earth, with some small [[Libration|''librations'']], or wobbles. Large objects may strike the Moon from time to time, causing it to rotate about some axis, but it will quickly stop rotating. All frictional effects from such events will also cause the Moon to regress further away from the Earth.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Groves|first1=G.W. |editor1-last=Kopal |editor1-first=Z.|title=Physics and Astronomy of the Moon|publisher=Academic Press|date=1961|chapter=Dynamics of the Earth-Moon System|pages=61-98|location=New York}}</ref> -->\n\n=== Project Mohole ===\n{{Main|Project Mohole}}\n[[File:Mohopix-1.gif|thumb|200px|Project Mohole contracted with a consortium of oil companies to use their oil drillship ''CUSS I''.<ref name=\"IODP\">{{cite web|url=http://www.iodp.org/project-mohole|title=Project Mohole|publisher=[[International Ocean Discovery Program|IODP]]|accessdate=5 March 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140306005146/http://www.iodp.org/project-mohole|archivedate = 6 March 2014 }}</ref>]]\nIn 1957, Munk and [[Harry Hammond Hess|Harry Hess]] suggested the idea behind [[Project Mohole]]: to drill into the [[Mohorovi\u010di\u0107 discontinuity] and obtain a sample of the Earth's [[mantle (geology)|mantle]]. While such a project was not feasible on land, drilling in the open ocean would be more feasible, because the mantle is much closer to the [[sea floor]]. Initially led by the informal group of scientists known as the [[American Miscellaneous Society]] (AMSOC), a group that included Hess, [[Maurice Ewing]], and [[Roger Revelle]],<ref name=\"70yrs\" />{{rp|67}} the project was eventually taken over by the National Science Foundation. Initial test drillings into the sea floor led by [[Willard Bascom]] occurred off [[Guadalupe Island]], Mexico in March and April 1961.<ref name=\"Life Mohole\">{{cite news|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9lEEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA110&source=gbs_toc_r&cad=2#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=High drama of bold thrust through the ocean floor: Earth's second layer is tapped in prelude to MOHOLE|first=John|last=Steinbeck|work=Life Magazine|date=April 14, 1961|accessdate=September 11, 2010}}</ref> However, the project was mismanaged and grew in expense after the construction company [[KBR (company)|Brown and Root]] won the contract to continue the effort. Toward the end of 1966, Congress discontinued the project.<ref name=\"nomohole\">{{cite news|url=http://americanheritage.com/articles/magazine/it/1993/1/1993_1_54.shtml|title=Why Mohole was no hole|first=Daniel|last=Sweeney|work=Invention and Technology Magazine \u2013 American Heritage|date=1993|pages=55\u201363|volume=9|accessdate=August 14, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201150256/http://americanheritage.com/articles/magazine/it/1993/1/1993_1_54.shtml|archivedate=December 1, 2008}}</ref> While Project Mohole was not successful, the idea and its innovative initial phase directly led to the successful NSF [[Deep Sea Drilling Program]] for obtaining sediment cores.<ref name=\"mohole\">{{cite news |url=http://www.nationalacademies.org/mohole/index.html |title=Project Mohole: Commemorating the Accomplishments of Project Mohole 1961-2011|author=The National Academies|accessdate=July 7, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Winterer\">{{Cite book |first1=Edward L. |last1=Winterer |date= 2000 |chapter=Scientific Ocean Drilling, from AMSOC to COMPOST |title=50 Years of Ocean Discovery: National Science Foundation 1950-2000|location=Washington, D.C.|chapter-url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK208831/ |publisher=National Academies Press (US) }}</ref>\n\n=== Ocean swell ===\n[[File:FLoatingInstrumentPlatform.jpg|thumb|alt=FLIP: FLoating Instrument Platform|Munk used [[R/P FLIP]] to measure waves traveling across ocean basins.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ocean.si.edu/human-connections/exploration/flip-floating-instrument-platform|title=FLIP: The FLoating Instrument Platform|last=Waters|first=Hannah|date=July 2012|work=[[Smithsonian Institution]]|accessdate=June 7, 2018}}</ref>]]\nStarting in the late 1950s, Munk returned to the study of [[Swell (ocean)|ocean waves]]. Thanks to his acquaintance with [[John Tukey]], he pioneered the use of [[spectral density|power spectra]] in describing wave behavior. This work culminated with an expedition that he led in 1963 called \"Waves Across the Pacific\" to observe waves generated by storms in the Southern Indian Ocean. Such waves traveled northward for thousands of miles across the Pacific Ocean. To trace the path and decay of the waves, he established measurement stations on islands and at sea (on [[R/P FLIP]]) along a great circle from [[New Zealand]], to the [[Palmyra Atoll]], and finally to [[Alaska]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Munk|first1=Walter|title=Excerpts from Waves Across the Pacific|url=http://palmyraarchive.org/items/show/147|website=Palmyra Atoll Digital Archive|year=1964}}</ref> Munk and his family spent nearly the whole of 1963 on [[American Samoa]] for this experiment. Walter and Judith Munk collaborated in making a film to document the experiment.<ref name=\"Dutton2013\">{{cite book|author=Lee S. Dutton|title=Anthropological Resources: A Guide to Archival, Library, and Museum Collections|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rcbIgOCqreIC&pg=PA77|date=May 13, 2013|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-134-81893-8|page=77}}</ref> The results show little decay of wave energy with distance traveled.<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1098/rsta.1966.0022|journal=Philos. Trans. R. Soc. Lond. A|title=Propagation of ocean swell across the Pacific|date=1966|last=Snodgrass|first=F.E.|author2=G.W. Groves|author3=K.F. Hasselmann|author4=G.R. Miller|author5=W.H. Munk|author6=W.H. Powers|volume=259|pages=431\u2013497|issue=1103|bibcode=1966RSPTA.259..431S}}</ref> This work, together with the wartime work on wave forecasting, led to the science of [[surf forecasting]], one of Munk's best-known accomplishments.<ref name=\"CBS8\" /> Munk's pioneering research into surf forecasting was acknowledged in 2007 with an award from the Groundswell Society, a surfing advocacy organization.<ref name=\"NCT\">{{cite news|url=http://www.nctimes.com/app/blogs/wp/?p=6809|title=SIO's Walter Munk Wins Crafoord Prize|first=Bradley|last=Fikes|work=North County Times blogs|date=January 21, 2010|accessdate=August 20, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100126133745/http://www.nctimes.com/app/blogs/wp/?p=6809|archivedate=January 26, 2010|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"Explorations Swell\">{{cite news|url=http://explorations.ucsd.edu/Around_the_Pier/2007/May/Munk/|title=Isn't He Swell?|first=Shannon|last=Casey|work=Explorations|date=May 2007|accessdate=August 20, 2010}}</ref>{{refn|In 2019, the Groundswell Society established the Dr. Walter Munk Scholarship \"to support a student intending to pursue a career in oceanography, meteorology, or marine biology.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Groundswell Society |title=Dr. Walter Munk Scholarship |url=http://groundswell-society.org/2019/02/dr-walter-munk-scholarship/ |accessdate=10 January 2020 |date=23 February 2019}}</ref>}}\n\n=== Ocean tides ===\nBetween 1965 and 1975, Munk turned to investigations of [[tide|ocean tides]], partly motivated by their effects on the Earth's rotation. Modern methods of [[time series]] and [[Spectral density estimation|spectral analysis]] were brought to bear on [[Theory of tides#Tidal analysis and prediction|tidal analysis]], leading to work with [[David Edgar Cartwright|David Cartwright]] developing the \"response method\" of tidal analysis.<ref name=\"Response\">{{cite journal|journal=Philos Trans R Soc Lond|title=Tidal spectroscopy and prediction|date=1966|last=Munk|first=W.|author2=D.E Cartwright|volume=A 259|pages=533\u2013581}}</ref> With [[Frank E. Snodgrass|Frank Snodgrass]], Munk developed deep-ocean pressure sensors that could be used to provide tidal data far from any land.<ref name=\"Affairs\" /><ref name=\"Cartwright\">{{cite book|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge|title=Tides: A Scientific History|url=https://archive.org/details/tidesscientifich0000cart|url-access=registration|date=1999|first=David|last=Cartwright|isbn=978-0-521-62145-8}}</ref> One highlight of this work was the discovery of the semidiurnal [[Amphidromic point|amphidrome]] midway between California and Hawaii.<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1080/03091927009365772|journal=Geophys. Fluid Dyn.|title=Tides off shore: transition from California coastal to deep-sea waters|date=1970|last=Munk|first=W.|author2=F. Snodgrass| author2-link = Frank E. Snodgrass|author3=M. Wimbush| last-author-amp = yes|volume=1|issue=1\u20132|pages=161\u2013235|bibcode=1970GApFD...1..161M}}</ref>\n\n===Internal waves: The Garrett-Munk Spectrum===\nAt the time of Munk's dissertation for his master's degree in 1939, [[internal wave]]s were considered an uncommon phenomenon.<ref name=\"70yrs\"/>{{rp|48}}  By the 1970s, there were extensive published observations of internal-wave variability in the oceans in temperature, salinity, and velocity as functions of time, horizontal distance, and depth.  Motivated by a 1958 paper by [[Owen Martin Phillips|Owen Philips]] that described a universal spectral form for the variance of ocean surface waves as a function of [[wave number]],<ref name=\"Affairs\"/> [[Christopher Garrett|Chris Garrett]] and Munk attempted to make sense of the observations by postulating a universal spectrum for internal waves.<ref name=\"GM72\">{{cite journal|journal=Geophys. Fluid Dyn.|title=Space-time scales of internal waves|date=1972|last1=Munk|first1=W.|last2=Garrett|first2=C.J.R.|volume=2|issue=1|pages=225\u2013264|doi=10.1080/03091927208236082|bibcode=1972GApFD...3..225G}}</ref> \n\nAccording to Munk,<ref name=\"70yrs\" />{{rp|48}} they chose a spectrum that could be factored into a function of frequency times a function of vertical wave number.  The resulting spectrum, now called the Garrett-Munk Spectrum, is roughly consistent with a large number of diverse measurements that had been obtained over the global ocean.  The model evolved over the subsequent decade, denoted GM72, GM75, GM79, etc.,<ref name=\"GM79\">{{cite journal|journal=Annual Review of Fluid Mechanics|title=Internal waves in the ocean|date=1979|last1=Munk|first1=W.|last2=Garrett|first2=C.J.R.|volume=11|issue=1|pages=339\u2013369|doi=10.1146/annurev.fl.11.010179.002011|bibcode=1979AnRFM..11..339G}}</ref> according to the year of publication of the revised model.  Although Munk expected the model to be rapidly obsolete, it proved to be a universal model that is still in use. Its universality is interpreted as a sign of profound processes governing internal wave dynamics, turbulence and fine-scale mixing.<ref name=\"Affairs\" />  [[Klaus Hasselmann]] commented in 2010, \"...the publication of the GM spectrum has indeed been extremely fruitful for oceanography, both in the past and still today.\"<ref name=\"70yrs\" />{{rp|50}}\n\n=== Ocean acoustic tomography ===\n{{Main|Ocean acoustic tomography}}\n[[File:1991 Heard Island Feasibility Test.png|thumb|Ocean topography (see scale) and some paths traveled by sound waves during the \n1991 Heard Island Feasibility Test.]]\nBeginning in 1975, Munk and [[Carl Wunsch]] of the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] pioneered the development of [[Ocean acoustic tomography|acoustic tomography]] of the ocean.<ref name=\"OAT\">{{cite book|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge|title=Ocean Acoustic Tomography|date=1995|first=Walter|last=Munk|author2=Peter Worcester|author3=Carl Wunsch| last-author-amp = yes|isbn=978-0-521-47095-7}}</ref> With Peter Worcester and Robert Spindel,<ref name=\"RSPW\"/> Munk developed the use of sound propagation, particularly sound arrival patterns and travel times, to infer important information about the ocean's large-scale temperature and current. This work, together with the work of other groups,<ref name=\"JLS\">{{cite journal|last=Spiesberger|first=J.L.|author2=K. Metzger|year=1991|title=Basin-scale tomography: A new tool for studying weather and climate|journal=J. Geophys. Res.|volume=96|issue=C3|pages=4869\u20134889|doi=10.1029/90JC02538|bibcode=1991JGR....96.4869S}}</ref> eventually motivated the 1991 \"Heard Island Feasibility Test\" (HIFT), to determine if man-made acoustic signals could be transmitted over [[Antipodes|antipodal]] distances to measure the ocean's [[climate change|climate]]. The experiment came to be called \"the sound heard around the world.\" During six days in January 1991, acoustic signals were transmitted by sound sources lowered from the [[MV Cory Chouest|M/V Cory Chouest]] near [[Heard Island]] in the southern Indian Ocean. These signals traveled half-way around the globe to be received on the east and west coasts of the United States, as well as at many other stations around the world.<ref name=\"HIFT\">{{cite journal|doi=10.1121/1.411316|journal=Journal of the Acoustical Society of America|title=The Heard Island Papers: A contribution to global acoustics|date=1994|last=Munk|first=W.|author2=A. Baggeroer|volume=96|pages=2327\u20132329|issue=4|bibcode=1994ASAJ...96.2327M}}</ref>\n\nThe follow-up to this experiment was the 1996\u20132006 [[Ocean acoustic tomography|Acoustic Thermometry of Ocean Climate]] (ATOC) project in the North Pacific Ocean.<ref name=\"Yam\" /><ref name=\"Science-1998\">{{cite news|author=The ATOC Consortium|title=Ocean Climate Change: Comparison of Acoustic Tomography, Satellite Altimetry, and Modeling|date=August 28, 1998|publisher=Science Magazine|url=http://www.sciencemag.org/cgi/content/abstract/281/5381/1327?maxtoshow=&HITS=150&hits=150&RESULTFORMAT=&fulltext=ocean&searchid=QID_NOT_SET&FIRSTINDEX=&fdate=3/1/1998|pages=1327\u20131332|accessdate=May 28, 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"decade\">{{cite news|first=B.D.|last=Dushaw|display-authors=etal|title=A decade of acoustic thermometry in the North Pacific Ocean|date=July 19, 2009|publisher=J. Geophys. Res.|volume=114, C07021|doi=10.1029/2008JC005124|bibcode=2009JGRC..114.7021D}}</ref>  Both HIFT and ATOC engendered considerable public controversy concerning the possible effects of man-made sounds on marine mammals.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/NATURE/9906/30/sea.noise.part1/|title=Low-frequency sonar raises whale advocates' hackles|work=CNN|date=June 30, 1999|author=Stephanie Siegel|accessdate=October 23, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/library/national/science/102798sci-sound.html|title=Global Thermometer Imperiled by Dispute|work=NY Times|date=June 30, 1999|author=Malcolm W. Browne|accessdate=October 23, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=J. R.|last=Potter|title=ATOC: Sound Policy or Enviro-Vandalism? Aspects of a Modern Media-Fueled Policy Issue|date=1994|publisher=The Journal of Environment & Development|url=http://jed.sagepub.com/cgi/content/abstract/3/2/47|volume=3|doi=10.1177/107049659400300205|pages=47\u201362|accessdate=November 20, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"Yam\" /> In addition to the decade-long measurements obtained in the North Pacific, acoustic thermometry has been employed to measure temperature changes of the upper layers of the Arctic Ocean basins,<ref name=\"PNM\">{{cite journal|doi=10.3402/polar.v20i2.6516|journal=Polar Research|title=Acoustic thermometry in the Arctic Ocean|date=2001|last1=Mikhalevsky|first1=P. N.|last2=Gavrilov|first2=A.N.|volume=20|issue=2|pages=185\u2013192|url=http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/j.1751-8369.2001.tb00055.x/abstract| access-date=February 19, 2015|bibcode=2001PolRe..20..185M}}</ref> which continues to be an area of active interest.<ref name=\"PNM_Arctic\">{{cite journal|doi=10.14430/arctic4449|journal=Arctic|title=Multipurpose acoustic networks in the integrated Arctic Ocean observing system|date=2015|last1=Mikhalevsky|first1=P. N.|last2=Sagan|first2=H.| display-authors = etal|volume=28, Suppl. 1|issue=5|pages=17|hdl=20.500.11937/9445|url=https://espace.curtin.edu.au/bitstream/20.500.11937/9445/2/235904_235904.pdf}}</ref> Acoustic thermometry has also been used to determine changes to global-scale ocean temperatures using data from acoustic pulses traveling from Australia to Bermuda.<ref name=\"ABMunk\">{{cite journal|doi=10.1175/1520-0485(1988)018<1876:ABSTER>2.0.CO;2|journal=Journal of Physical Oceanography|title=Australia-Bermuda Sound Transmission Experiment (1960) Revisited.|date=1988|last1=Munk|first1=W.H.|last2=O'Reilly|first2=W.C.|last3=Reid|first3=J.L.|volume=18|issue=12|pages=1876\u20131998|bibcode=1988JPO....18.1876M|doi-access=free}}</ref><ref name=\"ABDushaw\">{{cite journal|doi=10.1016/j.dsr.2013.12.008|journal=Deep-Sea Research Part I|title=Antipodal acoustic thermometry: 1960, 2004|date=2014|last1=Dushaw|first1=B.D.|last2=Menemenlis|first2=D.|volume=86|pages=1\u201320|bibcode=2014DSRI...86....1D|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\nTomography has come to be a valuable method of ocean observation,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Fischer|first1=A.S.|last2=Hall|first2=J.|last3=Harrison|first3=D.E.|last4=Stammer|first4=D.|last5=Benveniste|first5=J. |editor1-last=Hall |editor1-first=J.|editor2-last=Harrison |editor2-first=D.E.|editor3-last=Stammer |editor3-first=D.|title=Proceedings of OceanObs'09: Sustained Ocean Observations and Information for Society|volume=1|publisher=ESA Publication WPP-306|date=2010|chapter=Conference Summary-Ocean Information for Society: Sustaining the Benefits, Realizing the Potential|chapterurl=http://www.oceanobs09.net/proceedings/summary/}}</ref> exploiting the characteristics of long-range acoustic propagation to obtain synoptic measurements of average ocean temperature or current. Applications have included the measurement of deep water formation in the Greenland Sea in 1989,<ref name=\"GSP\">{{cite journal|doi=10.1175/1520-0485(1996)026<2316:TDOOAD>2.0.CO;2|journal=Journal of Physical Oceanography|title=Three-dimensional observations of a deep convective chimney in the Greenland sea during Winter 1988/89|date=1996|last1=Morawitz|first1=W.M.L.|last2=Sutton|first2=P.J.|last3=Worcester|first3=P.F.|last4=Cornuelle|first4=B.D.|last5=Lynch|first5=J.F.|last6=Pawlowicz|first6=R.|volume=26|issue=11|pages=2316\u20132343|bibcode=1996JPO....26.2316M|doi-access=free}}</ref> measurement of ocean tides,<ref name=\"Stammer\">{{cite journal|doi=10.1002/2014RG000450|journal=Reviews of Geophysics|title=Accuracy assessment of global barotropic ocean tide models|date=2014|last1=Stammer|first1=D.| display-authors= etal|volume=52|issue=3|pages=243\u2013282|bibcode=2014RvGeo..52..243S|hdl=2027.42/109077|hdl-access=free}}</ref><ref name=\"Dushaw\">{{cite journal|doi=10.1016/j.dsr.2011.04.002|journal=Deep-Sea Research Part I|title=On the predictability of mode-1 internal tides|date=2011|last1=Dushaw|first1=B.D.|last2=Worcester|first2=P.F.|last3=Dzieciuch|first3=M.A.|volume=58|issue=6|pages=677\u2013698|bibcode=2011DSRI...58..677D}}</ref> and the estimation of [[Eddy (fluid dynamics)#Mesoscale ocean eddies|ocean mesoscale dynamics]] by combining tomography, [[Satellite geodesy|satellite altimetry]], and ''in situ'' data with ocean dynamical models.<ref name=\"Lebedev\">{{cite journal|journal=Journal of Physical Oceanography|title=Monitoring the Kuroshio Extension through dynamically constrained synthesis of the acoustic tomography, satellite altimeter and in situ data|date=2003|last1=Lebedev|first1=K.V.|last2=Yaremchuck|first2=M.|last3=Mitsudera|first3=H.|last4=Nakano|first4=I.|last5=Yuan|first5=G.|volume=59|issue=6|pages=751\u2013763|doi=10.1023/b:joce.0000009568.06949.c5}}</ref> \n\nMunk advocated for acoustical measurements of the ocean for much of his career, such as his 1986 [[Bakerian Lecture]] ''Acoustic Monitoring of Ocean Gyres'',<ref name=\"Bakerian\"/> the 1995 monograph ''Ocean Acoustic Tomography'' written with Worcester and Wunsch,<ref name=\"OAT\"/> and his 2010 [[Crafoord Prize]] lecture ''The Sound of Climate Change''.<ref name=\"Crafoord\"/><ref name=\"Crafoord_Lecture\">{{cite journal|journal=Tellus|title=The Sound of Climate Change|date=2011|last1=Munk|first1=W.|volume=63|issue=2|pages=190\u2013197|doi=10.1111/j.1600-0870.2010.00494.x|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\n=== Tides and mixing ===\nIn the 1990s, Munk returned to the work on the role of tides in producing mixing in the ocean.<ref>{{Cite journal|doi=10.1016/S0967-0637(98)00070-3|author=Munk, W.|author2=Wunsch, C. | last-author-amp = yes|date=1998|title=Abyssal recipes II: Energetics of tidal and wind mixing|journal=Deep-Sea Research|volume=45|pages=1977\u20132010|bibcode=1998DSRI...45.1977M|issue=12}}</ref> In a 1966 paper \"Abyssal Recipes\", Munk was one of the first to assess quantitatively the rate of mixing in the abyssal ocean in maintaining oceanic [[Stratification (water)|stratification]].<ref>{{Cite journal|author=Munk, W.|date=1966|title=Abyssal recipes|journal=Deep-Sea Research|volume=13|issue=4|pages=707\u2013730|doi=10.1016/0011-7471(66)90602-4|bibcode=1966DSROA..13..707M}}</ref>  At that time, the tidal energy available for mixing was thought to occur by processes near ocean boundaries. According to [[Johan Sandstr\u00f6m|Sandstr\u00f6m's theorem]] (1908), without the occurrence deep mixing, driven by, e.g., [[internal tides]] or tidally-driven turbulence in shallow regions, most of the ocean would become cold and stagnant, capped by a thin, warm surface layer.<ref>{{Cite journal|doi=10.1111/j.1600-0870.2008.00357.x|author=Kuhlbrodt, T.|date=2008|title=On Sandstr\u00f6m's inferences from his tank experiments: a hundred years later|journal=Tellus A: Dynamic Meteorology and Oceanography|volume=60|pages=819\u2013836|issue=5|bibcode=2008TellA..60..819K|doi-access=free}}</ref>  The question of tidal energy available for mixing was reawakened in the 1990s with the discovery, by acoustic tomography and satellite altimetry, of large-scale internal tides radiating energy away from the [[Hawaiian\u2013Emperor seamount chain|Hawaiian Ridge]] into the interior of the North Pacific Ocean.<ref name=\"Dushaw2\">{{cite journal |journal = Journal of Physical Oceanography| title = Baroclinic and barotropic tides in the central North Pacific Ocean determined from long-range reciprocal acoustic transmissions|year = 1995|last1 = Dushaw|first1 = B.D.|last2= Cornuelle|first2= B.D.|last3= Worcester|first3= P.F.|last4=Howe|first4= B.M.|last5= Luther|first5= D.S.|volume = 25| issue = 4|pages = 631\u2013647|doi=10.1175/1520-0485(1995)025<0631:BABTIT>2.0.CO;2 | issn = 1520-0485|doi-access= free}}</ref><ref name=\"Ray2\">{{cite journal|journal = Geophys. Res. Lett.|title = Surface manifestation of internal tides generated near Hawaii| year = 1996| last1 = Ray|first1 = R.D.|last2 = Mitchum|first2 = G.T.|volume = 23|issue = 16|pages = 2101\u20132104|doi = 10.1029/96GL02050 |bibcode = 1996GeoRL..23.2101R}}</ref> Munk recognized that the tidal energy from the scattering and radiation of large-scale internal waves from mid-ocean ridges was significant, hence it could drive abyssal mixing.<ref name=\"MunkMoon\">{{cite journal | journal = Oceanography|year=1997|title = The Moon, of course...|last1=Munk|first1=W. M.|last2=Wunsch|first2=C.|volume = 10|issue = 3 |pages = 132\u2013134|doi=10.5670/oceanog.1997.06|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\n===Munk's enigma===\nIn his later work, Munk focused on the relation between changes in ocean temperature, sea level, and the transfer of mass between continental ice and the ocean.<ref>{{cite journal|journal = Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America|title = Twentieth century sea level: An enigma| year = 2002| last1 = Munk|first1 = W.|volume = 99|issue = 10|pages = 6550\u20136555|doi = 10.1073/pnas.092704599 |pmid = 12011419|pmc = 124440}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|journal = Science|title = Ocean Freshening, Sea Level Rising| year = 2003| last1 = Munk|first1 = W.|volume = 300|issue = 5628|pages = 2041\u20132043|doi = 10.1126/science.1085534 |pmid = 12829770}}</ref>  This work described what came to be known as \"Munk's enigma\", a large discrepancy between observed rate of sea level rise and its expected effects on the earth's rotation.<ref>{{cite journal | doi=10.1126/sciadv.1500679 | pmid=26824058 | pmc=4730844 | title=Reconciling past changes in Earth's rotation with 20th century global sea-level rise: Resolving Munk's enigma | journal=Science Advances | volume=1 | issue=11 | pages=e1500679 | year=2015 | authorlink1=Jerry X. Mitrovica|last1=Mitrovica | first1=Jerry X. | last2=Hay | first2=Carling C. | last3=Morrow | first3=Eric | last4=Kopp | first4=Robert E. | last5=Dumberry | first5=Mathieu | last6=Stanley | first6=Sabine | bibcode=2015SciA....1E0679M }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Scientists may have just solved one of the most troubling mysteries about sea-level rise|author=C. Harvey |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/energy-environment/wp/2015/12/11/scientists-may-have-just-solved-one-of-the-most-troubling-mysteries-about-sea-level-rise/ |accessdate=17 February 2019 |work=Washington Post |date=11 December 2015 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=San Diego Oceanographer, 98, Spurs Research Proving Climate Change Makes Days Longer|author=D. Wagner |url=https://www.kpbs.org/news/2016/may/16/climate-change-making-days-earth-longer/ |accessdate=17 February 2019 |publisher=KPBS, San Diego Public Radio and TV |date=16 May 2016 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\n[[File:Crafoordprize 2010-34.jpg|thumb|[[Carl XVI Gustaf of Sweden]] presents the Crafoord Prize to Munk]]\nMunk was elected to the [[United States National Academy of Sciences|National Academy of Sciences]] in 1956 and to the [[Royal Society of London]] in 1976. He was both a [[Guggenheim Fellow]] (1948, 1953, 1962)<ref>{{cite web|title=Walter H. Munk|publisher=John Simon Guggenheim Memorial Foundation|url=https://www.gf.org/fellows/all-fellows/walter-h-munk/|accessdate=February 17, 2019}}</ref> and a [[Fulbright Fellow]]. He was named California Scientist of the Year by the [[California Museum of Science and Industry]] in 1969. Munk gave the 1986 [[Bakerian Lecture]] at the [[Royal Society]] on ''Ships from Space'' (paper)<ref>{{cite journal|journal=Phil. Trans. Roy. Soc. A|title=The Bakerian Lecture, 1986: Ships from Space|date=1987|last1=Munk|first1=W.H.|last2=Scully-Power|first2=P.|last3=Zachariasen|first3=F.|volume=412|issue=1843|pages=231\u2013254|bibcode=1987RSPSA.412..231M|doi=10.1098/rspa.1987.0087}}</ref> and ''Acoustic monitoring of ocean gyres'' (lecture).<ref name=\"Bakerian\">{{cite journal|journal= Bulletin of the American Meteorological Society|volume=67|issue=6|title= Conference on the variability of the atmosphere and the oceans on time scales of a month to several years |date=1986|pages=785\u2013803|doi=10.1175/1520-0477-67.6.785|bibcode=1986BAMS...67..785.|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web|publisher=The Royal Society|title=Walter Munk Biography|url=https://royalsociety.org/people/walter-munk-11986/| access-date=February 14, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|journal=J. Fluid Mech.|title=Acoustic monitoring of ocean gyres|date=1986|last1=Munk|first1=W.H.|volume=173|pages=43\u201353|doi=10.1017/S0022112086001064|bibcode=1986JFM...173...43M}}</ref> In July 2018 at the age of 100, Munk was appointed a Chevalier of France's [[Legion of Honour]] in recognition of his contributions to oceanography.<ref name=\"latimesobit\"/>\n\nAmong the many other awards and honors Munk received are the [[Arthur L. Day Medal]] of the [[Geological Society of America]] in 1965, the [[Sverdrup Gold Medal Award|Sverdrup Gold Medal]] of the [[American Meteorological Society]] in 1966, the Gold Medal of the [[Royal Astronomical Society]] in 1968, the first [[Maurice Ewing Medal]] of the [[American Geophysical Union]] and the [[U.S. Navy]] in 1976, the [[Alexander Agassiz Medal]] of the [[United States National Academy of Sciences|National Academy of Sciences]] in 1976, the [[Captain Robert Dexter Conrad Award]] of the U.S. Navy in 1978, the [[National Medal of Science]] in 1983,<ref>{{cite web |title=Walter H. Munk |url=https://www.nsf.gov/od/nms/recip_details.jsp?recip_id=248 |website=The President's National Medal of Science: Recipient Details |publisher=National Science Foundation |accessdate=8 January 2020}}</ref> the [[William Bowie Medal]] of the [[American Geophysical Union]] in 1989,<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Revelle |first1=Roger |title=1989 Bowie Medal to Walter H. Munk |journal=Eos, Transactions American Geophysical Union |date=1990 |volume=71 |issue=1 |pages=13 |doi=10.1029/EO071i001p00013|bibcode=1990EOSTr..71...13R }}</ref> the [[Vetlesen Prize]] in 1993,<ref>{{cite web |title=Walter H. Munk |url=https://www.ldeo.columbia.edu/the-vetlesen-prize/past-recipients/walter-h-munk |website=The Vetlesen Prize |publisher=Lamont-Doherty Earth Observatory |accessdate=8 January 2020}}</ref> the [[Kyoto Prize]] in 1999,<ref>{{cite web |title=Walter H. Munk |url=https://www.kyotoprize.org/en/laureates/walter_h_munk/ |website=Kyoto Prize |accessdate=8 January 2020}}</ref> the first [[Prince Albert I Medal]] in 2001, and the [[Crafoord Prize]] of the [[Royal Swedish Academy of Sciences]] in 2010 \"for his pioneering and fundamental contributions to our understanding of ocean circulation, tides and waves, and their role in the Earth's dynamics\".<ref name=\"Crafoord\">{{cite web |title=The Crafoord Prize in Geosciences 2010 |url=https://www.crafoordprize.se/press_release/the-crafoord-prize-in-geosciences-2010 |publisher=The Royal Swedish Academy of Sciences |accessdate=8 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Crafoord_Lecture\"/>\n\nIn 1993, Munk was the first recipient of the [[Oceanography Society#Walter Munk Award|Walter Munk Award]] given \"in Recognition of Distinguished Research in Oceanography Related to Sound and the Sea.\"<ref name=\"ocea-munk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tos.org/awards_honors/munk_award.html|title=The Walter Munk Award|publisher=Oceanography Society|accessdate=July 26, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100323035643/http://www.tos.org/awards_honors/munk_award.html|archivedate=March 23, 2010}}</ref> This award was given jointly by [[The Oceanography Society]], the [[Office of Naval Research]] and the US Department of Defense [[Naval Oceanographic Office]].<ref name=\"ocea-munk\" />  The award was retired in 2018, and The Oceanographic Society \"established the Walter Munk Medal to encompass a broader range of topics in physical oceanography.\"<ref name=\"munkaward\">{{cite web|url=https://tos.org/munk-award|title=The Walter Munk Award|publisher=Oceanography Society|accessdate=January 9, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"munkmedal\">{{cite web|url=https://tos.org/munk-medal|title=The Walter Munk Medal|publisher=Oceanography Society|accessdate=January 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Mobula breach 2.jpg|thumb|Munk's devil ray]]\nTwo marine species have been named after Munk. One is ''Sirsoe munki'', a deep-sea worm. The other is ''[[Mobula munkiana]]'', also known as Munk's devil ray, a pygmy ray with a remarkable ability to leap far out of the water.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tu |first1=Chau |title=Picture of the Week: Munk's Devil Ray |url=https://www.sciencefriday.com/articles/picture-of-the-week-munks-devil-ray/ |accessdate=10 January 2020 |work=Science Friday |date=9 June 2014}}</ref> A 2017 documentary, ''[[Spirit of Discovery (Documentary)]]'', follows Munk in an expedition with the discoverer, [[Giuseppe Notarbartolo di Sciara]], to [[Cabo Pulmo National Park]] in Baja Mexico, one of the few places in the world where the rays can be found.<ref name=Scripps_obit/><ref>{{cite web |last1=Martinez |first1=Eliana Alvarez |title=About |url=https://spiritofdiscovery.co/about/ |website=Spirit of Discovery |accessdate=10 January 2020 |language=en |date=2 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nAfter [[Nazi Germany]] annexed Austria in 1938, an event known as the [[Anschluss]], Munk applied to be a citizen of the United States.<ref name=\"DDay\"/> In his first attempt, he failed the citizenship test by giving an overly-detailed answer to a question about the [[United States Constitution|Constitution]].<ref name=\"70yrs\"/>{{rp|20}} He obtained American citizenship in 1939.<ref name=\"70yrs\"/>{{rp|20}}\n\nMunk married Martha Chapin in the late 1940s. The marriage ended in divorce in 1953.<ref name=\"70yrs\"/>{{rp|31}} On June 20, 1953, he married [[Judith Munk|Judith Horton]]. She was an active participant at Scripps for decades, where she contributed to campus planning, architecture, and the renovation and reuse of historical buildings. The Munks were frequent traveling companions.<ref name=\"Affairs\"/> Judith died in 2006.<ref name=JudithObit>{{cite news |last1=Aguilera |first1=Mario |title=Obituary Notice: Judith Munk, Friend and Artistic Influence |url=https://scripps.ucsd.edu/news/13867 |accessdate=8 January 2020 |work=Scripps Institution of Oceanography |date=24 May 2006 |language=en}}</ref> In 2011, Munk married La Jolla community leader Mary Coakley.<ref name=\"TimesSD\">{{Cite web|url=https://timesofsandiego.com/tech/2019/02/08/scripps-oceanographer-walter-munk-dead-at-101/|title=Pioneering Scripps Oceanographer Walter Munk Dead at 101|last=McAllister|first=Toni|date=February 8, 2019|website=Times of San Diego|language=en-US|access-date=February 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\nMunk [[centenarian|turned 100]] in October 2017.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Spence |first1=Paul |last2=Keating |first2=Shane |title=Walter Munk, known as the 'Einstein of the ocean,' has turned 100 |url=https://www.newsweek.com/sport-surfing-walter-munk-688360 |accessdate=7 January 2020 |work=Newsweek |date=19 October 2017 |language=en}}</ref> He died of [[pneumonia]] on February 8, 2019 at La Jolla, California, aged 101.<ref name=Scripps_obit/><ref>{{cite news |last1=Dicke |first1=William |title=Walter H. Munk, Scientist-Explorer Who Illuminated the Deep, Dies at 101 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/02/09/obituaries/walter-h-munk-scientist-explorer-who-illuminated-the-deep-dies-at-101.html |newspaper=[[New York Times]] |accessdate=February 10, 2019 |language=English |date=February 9, 2019 |quote=She said the cause of death was pneumonia.}}</ref>\n\n== Publications ==\n=== Scientific papers ===\nMunk published 181 scientific papers. They were cited over 11,000 times, an average of 63 times each. Some of the most highly cited papers in the [[Web of Science]] database are listed below.\n*{{cite journal |last1=Munk |first1=W. H. |title=On the wind-driven ocean circulation |journal=Journal of Meteorology |date=1950 |volume=7 |issue=2 |pages=79\u201393|doi=10.1175/1520-0469(1950)007<0080:OTWDOC>2.0.CO;2 |bibcode=1950JAtS....7...80M |doi-access=free }}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Cox |first1=Charles |last2=Munk |first2=Walter |title=Measurement of the Roughness of the Sea Surface from Photographs of the Sun's Glitter |journal=Journal of the Optical Society of America |date=1 November 1954 |volume=44 |issue=11 |pages=838 |doi=10.1364/JOSA.44.000838|bibcode=1954JOSA...44..838C |url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/315d0c8c6238f5f4f7dd16851069ab76b74ec0cc }}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Munk |first1=Walter H. |title=Abyssal recipes |journal=Deep Sea Research and Oceanographic Abstracts |date=August 1966 |volume=13 |issue=4 |pages=707\u2013730 |doi=10.1016/0011-7471(66)90602-4|bibcode=1966DSROA..13..707M }}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Munk |first1=W. H. |last2=Cartwright |first2=D. E. |title=Tidal Spectroscopy and Prediction |journal=Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society A: Mathematical, Physical and Engineering Sciences |date=19 May 1966 |volume=259 |issue=1105 |pages=533\u2013581 |doi=10.1098/rsta.1966.0024|bibcode=1966RSPTA.259..533M }}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Garrett |first1=Christopher |last2=Munk |first2=Walter |title=Space-time scales of internal waves: A progress report |journal=Journal of Geophysical Research |date=20 January 1975 |volume=80 |issue=3 |pages=291\u2013297 |doi=10.1029/JC080i003p00291|bibcode=1975JGR....80..291G |url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/fc045c47fd078c8d41465b70803e7682065b53ab }}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Munk |first1=Walter |last2=Wunsch |first2=Carl |title=Ocean acoustic tomography: a scheme for large scale monitoring |journal=Deep Sea Research Part A. Oceanographic Research Papers |date=February 1979 |volume=26 |issue=2 |pages=123\u2013161 |doi=10.1016/0198-0149(79)90073-6|bibcode=1979DSRA...26..123M }}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Garrett |first1=C |last2=Munk |first2=W |title=Internal Waves in the Ocean |journal=Annual Review of Fluid Mechanics |date=January 1979 |volume=11 |issue=1 |pages=339\u2013369 |doi=10.1146/annurev.fl.11.010179.002011|bibcode=1979AnRFM..11..339G }}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Munk |first1=Walter |last2=Wunsch |first2=Carl |title=Abyssal recipes II: energetics of tidal and wind mixing |journal=Deep Sea Research Part I: Oceanographic Research Papers |date=December 1998 |volume=45 |issue=12 |pages=1977\u20132010 |doi=10.1016/S0967-0637(98)00070-3|bibcode=1998DSRI...45.1977M }}\n\n=== Books ===\n* W. Munk and G.J.F. MacDonald, ''The Rotation of the Earth: A Geophysical Discussion'', Cambridge University Press, 1960, revised 1975. {{ISBN|0-521-20778-9}}\n* W. Munk, P. Worcester, and C. Wunsch, ''Ocean Acoustic Tomography'', Cambridge University Press, 1995. {{ISBN|0-521-47095-1}}\n* S. Flatt\u00e9 (ed.), R. Dashen, W. H. Munk, K. M. Watson, and F. Zachariasen, ''Sound Transmission through a Fluctuating Ocean'', Cambridge University Press, 1979. {{ISBN|978-0-521-21940-2}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Walter Munk}}\n*   {{YouTube|MX5cKoOm6Pk|Waves Across the Pacific}} (1967) \u2013 a documentary showcasing Munk's research on waves generated by Antarctic storms. The film documents Munk's collaboration as they track storm-driven waves from Antarctica across the Pacific Ocean to Alaska. The film features scenes of early digital equipment in use in field experiments with Munk's commentary on how unsure they were about using such new technology in remote locations.\n* {{YouTube|je3QvqNdHl0|One Man's Noise: Stories of An Adventuresome Oceanographer}} (1994) \u2013 a television program on the work and life of Walter Munk produced by the University of California.\n* {{YouTube|lks2hh6LGsE|Perspectives on Ocean Science: Global Sea Level: An Enigma}} (2004) \u2013 a seminar on global sea level and climate change by Walter Munk. (YouTube link)\n* [http://www.crafoordprize.se/events/crafoorddays2010.4.5ce3bd8012d79a5929580004998.html The Sound of Climate Change] (2010) \u2013 Munk's Crafoord Prize Lecture\n* [http://www.spiritofdiscovery.co Spirit of Discovery] (2017) \u2013 a documentary showcasing Munk as he goes in search of ''Mobula munkiana'' a species that bears his name.\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EaW_ghP7HPI A Conversation with Walter Munk] (2019) \u2013 Carl Wunsch interviews Walter Munk about his life, career, and scientific events and people during his life on the occasion of his 100th birthday in 2017.\n* [https://www.aip.org/history-programs/niels-bohr-library/oral-histories/4790 Oral History interview transcript with Walter Munk 30 June 1986, American Institute of Physics, Niels Bohr Library and Archives]\n* [http://faculty.washington.edu/dushaw/heard/index.shtml The Heard Island Feasibility Test]\n* [https://scripps.ucsd.edu/news/tributes-walter-munk Tributes to Walter Munk] (Scripps)\n\n{{Founding members of the World Cultural Council}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Munk, Walter}}\n[[Category:1917 births]]\n[[Category:2019 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from La Jolla, San Diego]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States National Academy of Sciences]]\n[[Category:California Institute of Technology alumni]]\n[[Category:Columbia University alumni]]\n[[Category:Foreign Members of the Royal Society]]\n[[Category:Foreign Members of the Russian Academy of Sciences]]\n[[Category:Jewish American scientists]]\n[[Category:Kyoto laureates in Basic Sciences]]\n[[Category:National Medal of Science laureates]]\n[[Category:American centenarians]]\n[[Category:American oceanographers]]\n[[Category:Fluid dynamicists]]\n[[Category:Guggenheim Fellows]]\n[[Category:Scripps Institution of Oceanography faculty]]\n[[Category:Scripps Institution of Oceanography alumni]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Gold Medal of the Royal Astronomical Society]]\n[[Category:American people of Austrian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Austrian Jews]]\n[[Category:Scientists from Vienna]]\n[[Category:Austrian centenarians]]\n[[Category:University of California, San Diego faculty]]\n[[Category:Members of JASON]]\n[[Category:Founding members of the World Cultural Council]]\n[[Category:Sverdrup Gold Medal Award Recipients]]\n[[Category:Writers from San Diego]]\n[[Category:Writers from Vienna]]\n", "name_user": "Bdushaw", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eProject Mohole:ditto", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Walter_Munk"}
{"title_page": "John Beaumont, 1st Viscount Beaumont", "text_new": "{{good article}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2015}}\n{{Infobox nobility\n| name                 = John Beaumont\n| title                = [[Viscount Beaumont]]\n| image                = Coat of Arms of Sir John Beaumont, 1st Viscount Beaumont, KG.png\n| image_size           = 243px\n| caption              = Arms of Sir John Beaumont, 1st Viscount Beaumont, KG\n| spouse               = Elizabeth Phelip<br> [[Katherine Neville, Duchess of Norfolk|Katherine Strangways]]\n| issue                = [[William Beaumont, 2nd Viscount Beaumont]]\n| full name            =\n| noble family         = [[House of Beaumont]]\n| father               = Henry, 5th Baron Beaumont\n| mother               = Elizabeth Willoughby of Eresby\n| birth_date           = c. 1409\n| birth_place          = [[Folkingham|Folkingham Castle]], [[Lincolnshire]]\n| death_date           = 10 July 1460, \n| death_place          = [[Northampton]], [[Northamptonshire]]\n|}}\n\n'''John Beaumont, 1st Viscount Beaumont''' {{postnominals|country=GBR|KG}} (c. 1409\u201310 July 1460), was an English nobleman and [[magnate]] from [[Folkingham]], [[Lincolnshire]]. He was a councillor to King [[Henry VI of England|Henry VI]] and was rewarded for his services, becoming a leading member of the [[East Anglia]]n [[nobility]]. Beaumont held numerous offices for the crown, and was promoted up the [[peerage]] to become the first man with the rank of [[viscount]]. He also amassed immense personal wealth, acquired through inheritance, marriage, and royal patronage.\n\nBeaumont was present for some of the most notable events of Henry VI's reign. He was present at the arrest of [[Humphrey, Duke of Gloucester|Humphrey, duke of Gloucester]] in 1447, helped defend the king against [[Jack Cade's Rebellion]] in 1450, and helped suppress the rebellion of [[Richard of York, 3rd Duke of York|Richard, duke of York]] in 1452. While York and his allies ended up fighting against the king, Beaumont remained loyal to the [[House of Lancaster|Lancastrian]] crown during the 1450s, which saw the beginning of the [[Wars of the Roses]]. His personal loyalty to Henry VI eventually cost him his life \u2013 he was killed, bodyguarding the king, at the [[Battle of Northampton (1460)|battle of Northampton]] in 1460. Beaumont's son, [[William Beaumont, 2nd Viscount Beaumont|William Beaumont]], continued the struggle against the [[House of York|Yorkists]].\n\n==Early life==\nBorn at [[Folkingham|Folkingham Castle]], the eldest son of Henry Beaumont, 5th Baron Beaumont,<ref name=\"oxforddnb\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/50239|title=John Beaumont|publisher=oxforddnb.com|accessdate=14 September 2015|doi=10.1093/ref:odnb/50239|year=2004}}{{subscription required}}</ref> and orphaned by the age of four,<ref name=\"auto\">Cockayne, G.E., ''The Complete Peerage'' II, ed. H.E. Doubleday (London, 1912), 62.</ref> Beaumont became [[Henry V of England|Henry V's]] [[ward (law)|ward]], who quickly put him in the custody of [[Henry Beaufort|Henry Beaufort, Bishop of Winchester]].<ref name=\"oxforddnb\"/> On 24 July 1425 his marriage rights were granted by the council to Sir John Radcliffe as part-payment for debts owed him by the crown.<ref>[[Ralph A. Griffiths|Griffiths, R.A.]], ''The Reign of Henry VI'' (Berkeley, 1981)</ref> He was first summoned to parliament as Lord Beaumont in 1431,<ref name=\"auto\"/> and at some point between 1425 and 1436 he married Elizabeth Phelip. She was the daughter and heiress of Sir [[William Phelip, 6th Baron Bardolf|William Phelip]], a [[knight of the Garter]] who was recognised as sixth [[Baron Bardolf|Lord Bardolf]].<ref name=\"auto\"/> On his death in 1441, his large [[East Anglia]]n [[Estate (land)|estates]] went to his daughter, and so to Viscount Beaumont.<ref name=\"auto\"/> This made him a leading figure in the region.<ref name=\"oxforddnb\"/> Combined with his own inheritance in Leicestershire, he was a figure worthy of the association of [[William de la Pole, 1st Duke of Suffolk|William de la Pole, earl of Suffolk]] (died 1450) and from there entered the [[household]] of King [[Henry VI of England|Henry VI]].<ref>Griffiths, R.A., ''The Reign of Henry VI'' (Berkeley, 1981), 190.</ref>  In 1429 Beaumont was [[Order of the Bath|knighted]] by the seven-year-old king on the eve of his [[coronation]]<ref>Grummitt, D., ''Henry VI'' (Oxford, 2013), 75.</ref> and was in France with Henry the following year.<ref>Griffiths, R.A., ''The Reign of Henry VI'' (Berkeley, 1981), p. 279</ref> Dr. [[John Watts (historian)|John Watts]] has suggested that, as a royal ward, he may have been brought up in the king's household as a young man, and that his later generous treatment was a consequence of this. Watts  noted that a [[council]] act of 1425 brought wards of his status 'permanently about the king.'<ref name=\"oxforddnb\"/>\n\n==Royal service==\n[[File:Folkingham castle (geograph 3763852).jpg|thumb|left|All that remains of Beaumont's birthplace, Folkingham Castle, today]]\nHis first major activity on the king's behalf was in [[Hundred Years' War|France]] with the king's uncle, the [[Humphrey, Duke of Gloucester|duke of Gloucester]] in June\u2013July 1436, which had the goal of relieving [[Calais]], in a short, sharp campaign; albeit using the largest English army seen on French soil since Henry V's campaign. He briefly reinforced the [[Richard of York, 3rd Duke of York|Duke of York]] in [[Normandy]], but all returned to England in late July 1437.<ref>Griffiths, R.A., ''The Reign of Henry VI'' (Berkeley, 1981), p. 204\u20135</ref> For this service he was granted the [[Boulogne|county of Boulogne]] in reward; he was not, however, to ever return, even though the [[Richard Beauchamp, 13th Earl of Warwick|earl of Warwick]] had named him as one of the preferred nobles to accompany him back to France that year to relieve York.<ref>Griffiths, R.A., ''The Reign of Henry VI'' (Berkeley, 1981), p. 455</ref> On 5 January the following year (by now a 'prominent Household servant,' according to [[Ralph A. Griffiths|Ralph Griffiths]])<ref name=\"Griffiths 1981 238\">Griffiths, R.A., ''The Reign of Henry VI'' (Berkeley, 1981), p. 238</ref> he was made steward of the [[Duchy of Lancaster]]<ref name=\"oxforddnb\"/> and steward of [[Leicester]], [[Castle Donington]], and [[Higham Ferrers]].<ref>Griffiths, R.A., ''The Reign of Henry VI'' (Berkeley, 1981), p. 233</ref> In 1439 he was sworn onto the [[Curia regis|king's council]], which was effectively running the country during the king's [[minor (law)|minor]]ity,<ref>Castor, H., ''The King, the Crown, and the Duchy of Lancaster: Public Authority and Private Power, 1399\u20131461'' (Oxford, 2000), p. 140</ref> and in 1446 he was 'intimately involved' in peace negotiations with the French.<ref>Griffiths, R.A., ''The Reign of Henry VI'' (Berkeley, 1981), p. 493</ref>  In 1445, he was appointed [[Constable of England]], an envoy to France that same year beginning those negotiations, and five years later, to the [[Scottish people|Scots]].<ref>Griffiths, R.A., ''The Reign of Henry VI'' (Berkeley, 1981), p. 762 n. 69</ref>\n\nIn June 1457 he was personally responsible for intervening in the activities of [[Reginald Pecock|Bishop Pecock]], a virulent anti-[[Lollard]]. However, his virulence led to suspicions of [[heresy]], which resulted in Beaumont's instigation of a [[Inquisition|formal examination]] into the bishop's sermons and writings; Peckock agreed to [[recant]] and [[abjured]] his heresy in November 1457, resigning his [[bishopric]] a year later.<ref>Griffiths, R.A., ''The Reign of Henry VI'' (Berkeley, 1981), p. 796\u20137</ref>\n\n===Royal favour===\nBy 1440 he was firmly in the king's favour, being made in succession the first ever English [[viscount]] as [[Viscount Beaumont]] (1440),<ref>Goodwin, page 65</ref> possibly because by then Boulogne was effectively lost to him<ref>Griffiths, R.A., ''The Reign of Henry VI'' (Berkeley, 1981), p. 356</ref> and then granted royal lands in East Anglia, further official positions in royal castles, [[Lord Great Chamberlain]], appointed a [[Order of the Garter|Knight of the Garter]] and the feudal Viscountcy of Beaumont in France.<ref name=\"auto\"/> In 1445 he was made premier viscount, and granted precedence over any other- as-yet unmade- viscounts.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>Hicks, M.A., ''English Political Culture in the Fifteenth Century'' (London, 2002), p. 55</ref> These consistent promotions and favouritism have been the subject of some speculation by historians; [[John Watts (historian)|John Watts]] has questioned why he 'attracted such an extraordinary heap of honours and perquisites from the crown in these years.' He suggests that as a major noble in East Anglia- with all the territorial and regional significance that meant- was enough to make him worthy of promotion.<ref name=\"oxforddnb\"/> Beaumont commissioned a contemporary [[Illuminated manuscript|manuscript]] on chivalry, ''[[Knyghthode and Bataile]]'', an adaption of [[Vegetius]] for presentation to the king,<ref>Harriss, G.L., ''Shaping the Nation: England 1360\u20131461'' (Oxford, 2005), p. 118</ref> and was also a major benefactor of [[Queens' College, Cambridge]] which the king had granted by charter to his wife Queen [[Margaret of Anjou|Margaret]] in 1448.<ref>Griffiths, R.A., ''The Reign of Henry VI'' (Berkeley, 1981), p. 271 n. 135</ref>\n\n==Second marriage==\nHis wife having died by October 1441, within two years he married [[Katherine Neville, Duchess of Norfolk|Katherine Strangways, n\u00e9e Neville]], who was [[dowager]] [[duchess of Norfolk]]<ref name=\"auto\"/> and noble in her own right, being sister of [[Richard Neville, 5th Earl of Salisbury|Richard Neville, earl of Salisbury]], and thus what would have been considered a great marital prize. She brought him further territorial and financial augmentation.<ref name=\"oxforddnb\"/>\n\n==Political career==\nBeaumont was fully involved in the political crises that punctuated the reign of Henry VI: Griffiths has labelled him one of 'a small group of like-minded men, led by Suffolk' who could work for the king whether in council or on [[royal progress]],<ref>Griffiths, R.A., ''The Reign of Henry VI'' (Berkeley, 1981), p. 282</ref> although his attendance at council seems to have become more sporadic by 1443.<ref>Griffiths, R.A., ''The Reign of Henry VI'' (Berkeley, 1981), p. 292 n. 30</ref> As [[Lord Steward|Steward of England]],<ref>Harriss, G.L., ''Shaping the Nation: England 1360\u20131461'' (Oxford, 2005), p. 613</ref> he personally- although accompanied by, for example, other lords such as [[Humphrey Stafford, 1st Duke of Buckingham|Buckingham]] and the [[Richard Neville, 5th Earl of Salisbury|earl of Salisbury]]<ref>Jacob, E.F., The Fifteenth Century, (Oxford, 1993), 483</ref>- arrested [[Humphrey, Duke of Gloucester|Humphrey, duke of Gloucester]] for [[treason]], in [[Bury St Edmunds]] 18 February 1447.<ref name=\"Goodwin2011\">{{cite book|author=George Goodwin|title=Fatal Colours: Towton, 1461 \u2013 England's Most Brutal Battle|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=A9EGec-o2joC|date=10 March 2011|publisher=Orion|isbn=978-0-297-86072-3|page=30}}</ref>\nThroughout the subsequent period of foreign catastrophe which, to contemporaries, came to symbolise the failure of [[William de la Pole, 1st Duke of Suffolk|Suffolk's]] government in the late 1440s, Beaumont not only supported the duke's policy but backed him during his [[impeachment]].<ref>Harriss, G.L., ''Shaping the Nation: England 1360\u20131461'' (Oxford, 2005), p. 611</ref> With Suffolk's fall in 1450, it has been described as 'rather surprising' that Beaumont did not fall with him, having 'been involved in some of the regime's most unpopular activities.'<ref name=\"oxforddnb\"/> For instance, he was a close associate and a 'protector'<ref>Jacob, E.F., The Fifteenth Century, (Oxford, 1993), 494</ref> of the 'headstrong' Sir [[William Tailboys]] (whom Griffiths also called '[[wikt:knave|knave]]-in-chief')<ref>Griffiths, R.A., ''The Reign of Henry VI'' (Berkeley, 1981), p. 580</ref> when Tailboys attempted to assassinate [[Ralph de Cromwell, 3rd Baron Cromwell|Lord Cromwell]] in broad daylight in November 1449.<ref>Griffiths, R.A., ''The Reign of Henry VI'' (Berkeley, 1981), p. 286</ref> He had also suffered a minor assault on his [[Boston, Lincolnshire|Boston]] [[manor]] the previous year, but it is likely that he was seen as more impartial at the time than he has seen since.<ref name=\"oxforddnb\"/> Indeed, far from suffering from his patron's fall, he was appointed to Suffolk's old position of [[Lord Chamberlain]] of England, although only for three weeks.<ref>Griffiths, R.A., ''The Reign of Henry VI'' (Berkeley, 1981), p. 288</ref>\n\nAt the outbreak of [[Jack Cade's Rebellion]], he was commissioned on 10 June 1450 to reinforce [[London]],<ref>Griffiths, R.A., ''The Reign of Henry VI'' (Berkeley, 1981), p. 611</ref> and accompanied Henry VI back to the capital in July.<ref>Griffiths, R.A., ''The Reign of Henry VI'' (Berkeley, 1981), p. 623</ref> Later, with the [[Humphrey Stafford, 1st Duke of Buckingham|duke of Buckingham]] negotiated with the rebels at [[Blackheath, London|Blackheath]], offering them [[royal pardons]].<ref>Harriss, G.L., ''Shaping the Nation: England 1360\u20131461'' (Oxford, 2005), p. 620</ref>\n\nAt the time of the [[William de la Pole, 1st Duke of Suffolk|duke of Suffolk]]'s murder, Beaumont had been an associate of the by now recalcitrant [[Richard of York, 3rd Duke of York|Richard, duke of York]], having been one of the duke's [[feoffee]]s in May 1436 and March 1441,<ref>Griffiths, R.A., ''The Reign of Henry VI'' (Berkeley, 1981), p. 701 n. 15</ref> and possibly even acting as the duke's councillor on occasion.<ref name=\"oxforddnb\"/> He had also joined York on the king's council during York's first [[Protectorate]] (March 1453 \u2013 January 1454).<ref>Harriss, G.L., ''Shaping the Nation: England 1360\u20131461'' (Oxford, 2005), p. 629</ref> But as York drew further from the court, so Beaumont appears to have moved towards it; although he appears to have not been present at the [[first battle of St Albans]] in 1455,<ref name=\"oxforddnb\"/> he had already stood with the king against York at the latter's [[Impasse|stand-off]] with king at [[Dartford]] in 1452,<ref>Griffiths, R.A., ''The Reign of Henry VI'' (Berkeley, 1981), p. 709 n. 134</ref> and then sat in judgment on some of his men. He eventually joined the anti-Neville faction at court; although his wife was a [[House of Neville|Neville]], her family had by now [[Wars of the Roses|aligned themselves with the duke of York]]. He was amongst the party of lords that reported to parliament that the king was sick and they 'coud not rouse him' in March 1454.<ref>Goodwin, pages 51\u201352</ref> He was also an arbitrator between York and the king's party, headed by the [[Edmund Beaufort, 2nd Duke of Somerset|duke of Somerset]] after the king's recovery in 1454; although Griffiths says not a 'strictly impartial' one.<ref>Griffiths, R.A., ''The Reign of Henry VI'' (Berkeley, 1981), p. 739</ref> Indeed, Griffiths suggests that his appointment to the council on 15 April 1454, after the king's recovery and York's dismissal, was part of a concerted attempt to 're-balance' the council after the protectorate.<ref>Griffiths, R.A., ''The Reign of Henry VI'' (Berkeley, 1981), p. 727, 762 n. 70</ref> He was even reported (although wrongly) to have been recruiting an army to march against London in 1454.<ref>Jacob, E.F., The Fifteenth Century, (Oxford, 1993), 508.</ref> He was one of the few [[Lords Temporal]] to remain in Henry VI's council in the closing years of the decade, by which time he was the queen's chief steward.<ref>Jacob, E.F., ''The Fifteenth Century'', (Oxford, 1993), 481.</ref> He was also part of the [[royal commission]] set up by parliament in July 1455 to examine royal household expenditure;<ref>Griffiths, R.A., ''The Reign of Henry VI'' (Berkeley, 1981), p. 750, 769 n. 192</ref> the trust the Queen placed in him was demonstrated on 28 January 1457 when he was appointed to the council of the young [[Edward of Westminster, Prince of Wales|Prince of Wales]],<ref>Griffiths, R.A., ''The Reign of Henry VI'' (Berkeley, 1981), p. 781</ref> which had responsibility for his estate management, expenditure, personnel, and administration.<ref>Griffiths, R.A., ''The Reign of Henry VI'' (Berkeley, 1981), p. 781\u20132</ref>\n\nHis loyalty the crown was such that in 1460 the [[House of York|Yorkists]] proclaimed him one of their most mortal enemies among the king's supporters.<ref>Goodwin, page 105</ref> They also claimed that Beaumont, along with the earls of [[James Butler, 5th Earl of Ormond|Wiltshire]] and [[John Talbot, 2nd Earl of Shrewsbury|Shrewsbury]], orchestrated the Yorkists' [[attainder]] at the 1459 [[Parliament of Devils|Coventry parliament]], in order to seize the Yorkists' lands.<ref>Lander, J.R., ''Government and Community, 1450\u20131509'' (London, 1980), p. 205</ref> It is likely that they were the public focus of the Yorkists' enmity in a way that Henry VI's queen (to whom he was a personal adviser), [[Margaret of Anjou]] could not be.<ref>Hicks, M.A., ''The Wars of the Roses'' (London, 2010), p. 142</ref><ref>Griffiths, R.A., ''The Reign of Henry VI'' (Berkeley, 1981), p. 262</ref>\n\n==Wealth and estates==\n[[File:Map for Battle of Northampton by Ramsay.jpg|thumb|left|Map of the Battle of Northampton]]\nIn 1444, further expanding his wealth, he bought the [[reversion (law)|reversion]] of Sir Thomas Erdington's estates, as the latter was dying with no heir.<ref>Harriss, G.L., ''Shaping the Nation: England 1360\u20131461'' (Oxford, 2005), p. 148</ref> Like other lords involved in the fall of Gloucester in 1447, he benefitted immensely from the subsequent redistribution of the duke's lands.<ref>Harriss, G.L., ''Shaping the Nation: England 1360\u20131461'' (Oxford, 2005), p. 615</ref>\n\n==Death and legacy==\nHis allegiance to the [[House of Lancaster|Lancastrian]] regime remained strong enough for him to take arms against the [[House of York]], and eventually cost him his life. Commanding the central [[Battle (formation)|battle]] of the king's army<ref>Sadler, J., ''Towton: The Battle of Palmsunday Field 1461''(Barnsley, 2011), 55.</ref> he fell, with the [[Humphrey Stafford, 1st Duke of Buckingham|duke of Buckingham]] and [[Thomas Percy, 1st Baron Egremont|Lord Egremont]] whilst forming a human shield in defence of the king,<ref>Sadler, J., ''Towton: The Battle of Palmsunday Field 1461''(Barnsley, 2011), 56.</ref><ref>Santiuste, E., Edward IV and the Wars of the Roses (Barnsley, 2010), 28.</ref> against the victorious Yorkists in the [[Battle of Northampton (1460)|battle of Northampton]] on 10 July 1460.<ref>Santiuste, E., ''Edward IV and the Wars of the Roses'' (Barnsley, 2010), 30.</ref> Even though the king had fallen into Yorkist hands, Beaumont was not attainted, and his son was allowed to enter into his inheritance.<ref name=\"Ross1974\">{{cite book|author=Charles Derek Ross|title=Edward IV|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zbmkggaM_k8C|date=January 1974|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-02781-7|page=66}}</ref> Presumably in an attempt to reconcile his family to the new regime. This failed,<ref name=\"oxforddnb\"/> and Beaumont's second son (but who was his heir)<ref name=\"auto\"/> \u2013 the by now [[William Beaumont, 2nd Viscount Beaumont|second Viscount]] fought against the victorious army of the Yorkist king, [[Edward IV of England|Edward IV]] at the [[battle of Towton]] in April the next year.<ref name=\"Ross1974\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{cite book|author=George Goodwin|title=Fatal Colours: Towton, 1461 \u2013 England's Most Brutal Battle|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=A9EGec-o2joC|date=10 March 2011|publisher=Orion|isbn=978-0-297-86072-3|page=30}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://books.google.co.uk/books/about/The_Reign_of_King_Henry_VI.html?id=frWDmbf_mXEC&redir_esc=y R.A. Griffiths, ''The Reign of Henry VI'', at Google books]\n\n{{Wars of the Roses}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Beaumont, John Beaumont, 1st Viscount}}\n[[Category:People of the Wars of the Roses]]\n[[Category:Medieval English nobility]]\n[[Category:People from Folkingham]]\n[[Category:1460 deaths]]\n[[Category:1400s births]]\n[[Category:15th-century English people]]\n[[Category:Viscounts Beaumont]]\n[[Category:Barons Beaumont]]\n", "text_old": "{{good article}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2015}}\n{{Infobox nobility\n| name                 = John Beaumont\n| title                = [[Viscount Beaumont]]\n| image                = Coat of Arms of Sir John Beaumont, 1st Viscount Beaumont, KG.png\n| image_size           = 243px\n| caption              = Arms of Sir John Beaumont, 1st Viscount Beaumont, KG\n| spouse               = Elizabeth Phelip<br> [[Katherine Neville, Duchess of Norfolk|Katherine Strangways]]\n| issue                = [[William Beaumont, 2nd Viscount Beaumont]]\n| full name            =\n| noble family         = [[House of Beaumont]]\n| father               = Henry, 5th Baron Beaumont\n| mother               = Elizabeth Willoughby of Eresby\n| birth_date           = c. 1409\n| birth_place          = [[Folkingham|Folkingham Castle]], [[Lincolnshire]]\n| death_date           = 10 July 1460, \n| death_place          = [[Northampton]], [[Northamptonshire]]\n|}}\n\n'''John Beaumont, 1st Viscount Beaumont''' {{postnominals|country=GBR|KG}} (c. 1409\u201310 July 1460), was an English nobleman and [[magnate]] from [[Folkingham]], [[Lincolnshire]]. He was a councillor to King [[Henry VI of England|Henry VI]] and was rewarded for his services, becoming a leading member of the [[East Anglia]]n [[nobility]]. Beaumont held numerous offices for the crown, and was promoted up the [[peerage]] to become the first man with the rank of [[viscount]]. He also amassed immense personal wealth, acquired through inheritance, marriage, and royal patronage.\n\nBeaumont was present for some of the most notable events of Henry VI's reign. He was present at the arrest of [[Humphrey, Duke of Gloucester|Humphrey, duke of Gloucester]] in 1447, helped defend the king against [[Jack Cade's Rebellion]] in 1450, and helped suppress the rebellion of [[Richard of York, 3rd Duke of York|Richard, duke of York]] in 1452. While York and his allies ended up fighting against the king, Beaumont remained loyal to the [[House of Lancaster|Lancastrian]] crown during the 1450s, which saw the beginning of the [[Wars of the Roses]]. His personal loyalty to Henry VI eventually cost him his life \u2013 he was killed, bodyguarding the king, at the [[Battle of Northampton (1460)|battle of Northampton]] in 1460. Beaumont's son, [[William Beaumont, 2nd Viscount Beaumont|William Beaumont]], continued the struggle against the [[House of York|Yorkists]].\n\n==Early life==\nBorn at [[Folkingham|Folkingham Castle]], the eldest son of Henry Beaumont, 5th Baron Beaumont,<ref name=\"oxforddnb\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/50239|title=John Beaumont|publisher=oxforddnb.com|accessdate=14 September 2015|doi=10.1093/ref:odnb/50239|year=2004}}{{subscription required}}</ref> and orphaned by the age of four,<ref name=\"auto\">Cockayne, G.E., ''The Complete Peerage'' II, ed. H.E. Doubleday (London, 1912), 62.</ref> Beaumont became [[Henry V of England|Henry V's]] [[ward (law)|ward]], who quickly put him in the custody of [[Henry Beaufort|Henry Beaufort, Bishop of Winchester]].<ref name=\"oxforddnb\"/> On 24 July 1425 his marriage rights were granted by the council to Sir John Radcliffe as part-payment for debts owed him by the crown.<ref>[[Ralph A. Griffiths|Griffiths, R.A.]], ''The Reign of Henry VI'' (Berkeley, 1981)</ref> He was first summoned to parliament as Lord Beaumont in 1431,<ref name=\"auto\"/> and at some point between 1425 and 1436 he married Elizabeth Phelip. She was the daughter and heiress of Sir [[William Phelip, 6th Baron Bardolf|William Phelip]], a [[knight of the Garter]] who was recognised as sixth [[Baron Bardolf|Lord Bardolf]].<ref name=\"auto\"/> On his death in 1441, his large [[East Anglia]]n [[Estate (land)|estates]] went to his daughter, and so to Viscount Beaumont.<ref name=\"auto\"/> This made him a leading figure in the region.<ref name=\"oxforddnb\"/> Combined with his own inheritance in Leicestershire, he was a figure worthy of the association of [[William de la Pole, 1st Duke of Suffolk|William de la Pole, earl of Suffolk]] (died 1450) and from there entered the [[household]] of King [[Henry VI of England|Henry VI]].<ref>Griffiths, R.A., ''The Reign of Henry VI'' (Berkeley, 1981), 190.</ref>  In 1429 Beaumont was [[Order of the Bath|knighted]] by the seven-year-old king on the eve of his [[coronation]]<ref>Grummitt, D., ''Henry VI'' (Oxford, 2013), 75.</ref> and was in France with Henry the following year.<ref>Griffiths, R.A., ''The Reign of Henry VI'' (Berkeley, 1981), p. 279</ref> Dr. [[John Watts (historian)|John Watts]] has suggested that, as a royal ward, he may have been brought up in the king's household as a young man, and that his later generous treatment was a consequence of this. Watts  noted that a [[council]] act of 1425 brought wards of his status 'permanently about the king.'<ref name=\"oxforddnb\"/>\n\n==Royal service==\n[[File:Folkingham castle (geograph 3763852).jpg|thumb|left|All that remains of Beaumont's birthplace, Folkingham Castle, today]]\nHis first major activity on the king's behalf was in [[Hundred Years' War|France]] with the king's uncle, the [[Humphrey, Duke of Gloucester|duke of Gloucester]] in June\u2013July 1436, which had the goal of relieving [[Calais]], in a short, sharp campaign; albeit using the largest English army seen on French soil since Henry V's campaign. He briefly reinforced the [[Richard of York, 3rd Duke of York|Duke of York]] in [[Normandy]], but all returned to England in late July 1437.<ref>Griffiths, R.A., ''The Reign of Henry VI'' (Berkeley, 1981), p. 204\u20135</ref> For this service he was granted the [[Boulogne|county of Boulogne]] in reward; he was not, however, to ever return, even though the [[Richard Beauchamp, 13th Earl of Warwick|earl of Warwick]] had named him as one of the preferred nobles to accompany him back to France that year to relieve York.<ref>Griffiths, R.A., ''The Reign of Henry VI'' (Berkeley, 1981), p. 455</ref> On 5 January the following year (by now a 'prominent Household servant,' according to [[Ralph A. Griffiths|Ralph Griffiths]])<ref name=\"Griffiths 1981 238\">Griffiths, R.A., ''The Reign of Henry VI'' (Berkeley, 1981), p. 238</ref> he was made steward of the [[Duchy of Lancaster]]<ref name=\"oxforddnb\"/> and steward of [[Leicester]], [[Castle Donington]], and [[Higham Ferrers]].<ref>Griffiths, R.A., ''The Reign of Henry VI'' (Berkeley, 1981), p. 233</ref> In 1439 he was sworn onto the [[Curia regis|king's council]], which was effectively running the country during the king's [[minor (law)|minor]]ity,<ref>Castor, H., ''The King, the Crown, and the Duchy of Lancaster: Public Authority and Private Power, 1399\u20131461'' (Oxford, 2000), p. 140</ref> and in 1446 he was 'intimately involved' in peace negotiations with the French.<ref>Griffiths, R.A., ''The Reign of Henry VI'' (Berkeley, 1981), p. 493</ref>  In 1445, he was appointed [[Constable of England]], an envoy to France that same year beginning those negotiations, and five years later, to the [[Scottish people|Scots]].<ref>Griffiths, R.A., ''The Reign of Henry VI'' (Berkeley, 1981), p. 762 n. 69</ref>\n\nIn June 1457 he was personally responsible for intervening in the activities of [[Reginald Pecock|Bishop Pecock]], a virulent anti-[[Lollard]]. However, his virulence led to suspicions of [[heresy]], which resulted in Beaumont's instigation of a [[Inquisition|formal examination]] into the bishop's sermons and writings; Peckock agreed to [[recant]] and [[abjured]] his heresy in November 1457, resigning his [[bishopric]] a year later.<ref>Griffiths, R.A., ''The Reign of Henry VI'' (Berkeley, 1981), p. 796\u20137</ref>\n\n===Royal favour===\nBy 1440 he was firmly in the king's favour, being made in succession the first ever English [[viscount]] as [[Viscount Beaumont]] (1440),<ref>Goodwin, page 65</ref> possibly because by then Boulogne was effectively lost to him<ref>Griffiths, R.A., ''The Reign of Henry VI'' (Berkeley, 1981), p. 356</ref> and then granted royal lands in East Anglia, further official positions in royal castles, [[Lord Great Chamberlain]], appointed a [[Order of the Garter|Knight of the Garter]] and the feudal Viscountcy of Beaumont in France.<ref name=\"auto\"/> In 1445 he was made premier viscount, and granted precedence over any other- as-yet unmade- viscounts.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>Hicks, M.A., ''English Political Culture in the Fifteenth Century'' (London, 2002), p. 55</ref> These consistent promotions and favouritism have been the subject of some speculation by historians; [[John Watts (historian)|John Watts]] has questioned why he 'attracted such an extraordinary heap of honours and perquisites from the crown in these years.' He suggests that as a major noble in East Anglia- with all the territorial and regional significance that meant- was enough to make him worthy of promotion.<ref name=\"oxforddnb\"/> Beaumont commissioned a contemporary [[Illuminated manuscript|manuscript]] on chivalry, ''[[Knyghthode and Bataile]]'', an adaption of [[Vegetius]] for presentation to the king,<ref>Harriss, G.L., ''Shaping the Nation: England 1360\u20131461'' (Oxford, 2005), p. 118</ref> and was also a major benefactor of [[Queens' College, Cambridge]] which the king had granted by charter to his wife Margaret in 1448.<ref>Griffiths, R.A., ''The Reign of Henry VI'' (Berkeley, 1981), p. 271 n. 135</ref>\n\n==Second marriage==\nHis wife having died by October 1441, within two years he married [[Katherine Neville, Duchess of Norfolk|Katherine Strangways, n\u00e9e Neville]], who was [[dowager]] [[duchess of Norfolk]]<ref name=\"auto\"/> and noble in her own right, being sister of [[Richard Neville, 5th Earl of Salisbury|Richard Neville, earl of Salisbury]], and thus what would have been considered a great marital prize. She brought him further territorial and financial augmentation.<ref name=\"oxforddnb\"/>\n\n==Political career==\nBeaumont was fully involved in the political crises that punctuated the reign of Henry VI: Griffiths has labelled him one of 'a small group of like-minded men, led by Suffolk' who could work for the king whether in council or on [[royal progress]],<ref>Griffiths, R.A., ''The Reign of Henry VI'' (Berkeley, 1981), p. 282</ref> although his attendance at council seems to have become more sporadic by 1443.<ref>Griffiths, R.A., ''The Reign of Henry VI'' (Berkeley, 1981), p. 292 n. 30</ref> As [[Lord Steward|Steward of England]],<ref>Harriss, G.L., ''Shaping the Nation: England 1360\u20131461'' (Oxford, 2005), p. 613</ref> he personally- although accompanied by, for example, other lords such as [[Humphrey Stafford, 1st Duke of Buckingham|Buckingham]] and the [[Richard Neville, 5th Earl of Salisbury|earl of Salisbury]]<ref>Jacob, E.F., The Fifteenth Century, (Oxford, 1993), 483</ref>- arrested [[Humphrey, Duke of Gloucester|Humphrey, duke of Gloucester]] for [[treason]], in [[Bury St Edmunds]] 18 February 1447.<ref name=\"Goodwin2011\">{{cite book|author=George Goodwin|title=Fatal Colours: Towton, 1461 \u2013 England's Most Brutal Battle|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=A9EGec-o2joC|date=10 March 2011|publisher=Orion|isbn=978-0-297-86072-3|page=30}}</ref>\nThroughout the subsequent period of foreign catastrophe which, to contemporaries, came to symbolise the failure of [[William de la Pole, 1st Duke of Suffolk|Suffolk's]] government in the late 1440s, Beaumont not only supported the duke's policy but backed him during his [[impeachment]].<ref>Harriss, G.L., ''Shaping the Nation: England 1360\u20131461'' (Oxford, 2005), p. 611</ref> With Suffolk's fall in 1450, it has been described as 'rather surprising' that Beaumont did not fall with him, having 'been involved in some of the regime's most unpopular activities.'<ref name=\"oxforddnb\"/> For instance, he was a close associate and a 'protector'<ref>Jacob, E.F., The Fifteenth Century, (Oxford, 1993), 494</ref> of the 'headstrong' Sir [[William Tailboys]] (whom Griffiths also called '[[wikt:knave|knave]]-in-chief')<ref>Griffiths, R.A., ''The Reign of Henry VI'' (Berkeley, 1981), p. 580</ref> when Tailboys attempted to assassinate [[Ralph de Cromwell, 3rd Baron Cromwell|Lord Cromwell]] in broad daylight in November 1449.<ref>Griffiths, R.A., ''The Reign of Henry VI'' (Berkeley, 1981), p. 286</ref> He had also suffered a minor assault on his [[Boston, Lincolnshire|Boston]] [[manor]] the previous year, but it is likely that he was seen as more impartial at the time than he has seen since.<ref name=\"oxforddnb\"/> Indeed, far from suffering from his patron's fall, he was appointed to Suffolk's old position of [[Lord Chamberlain]] of England, although only for three weeks.<ref>Griffiths, R.A., ''The Reign of Henry VI'' (Berkeley, 1981), p. 288</ref>\n\nAt the outbreak of [[Jack Cade's Rebellion]], he was commissioned on 10 June 1450 to reinforce [[London]],<ref>Griffiths, R.A., ''The Reign of Henry VI'' (Berkeley, 1981), p. 611</ref> and accompanied Henry VI back to the capital in July.<ref>Griffiths, R.A., ''The Reign of Henry VI'' (Berkeley, 1981), p. 623</ref> Later, with the [[Humphrey Stafford, 1st Duke of Buckingham|duke of Buckingham]] negotiated with the rebels at [[Blackheath, London|Blackheath]], offering them [[royal pardons]].<ref>Harriss, G.L., ''Shaping the Nation: England 1360\u20131461'' (Oxford, 2005), p. 620</ref>\n\nAt the time of the [[William de la Pole, 1st Duke of Suffolk|duke of Suffolk]]'s murder, Beaumont had been an associate of the by now recalcitrant [[Richard of York, 3rd Duke of York|Richard, duke of York]], having been one of the duke's [[feoffee]]s in May 1436 and March 1441,<ref>Griffiths, R.A., ''The Reign of Henry VI'' (Berkeley, 1981), p. 701 n. 15</ref> and possibly even acting as the duke's councillor on occasion.<ref name=\"oxforddnb\"/> He had also joined York on the king's council during York's first [[Protectorate]] (March 1453 \u2013 January 1454).<ref>Harriss, G.L., ''Shaping the Nation: England 1360\u20131461'' (Oxford, 2005), p. 629</ref> But as York drew further from the court, so Beaumont appears to have moved towards it; although he appears to have not been present at the [[first battle of St Albans]] in 1455,<ref name=\"oxforddnb\"/> he had already stood with the king against York at the latter's [[Impasse|stand-off]] with king at [[Dartford]] in 1452,<ref>Griffiths, R.A., ''The Reign of Henry VI'' (Berkeley, 1981), p. 709 n. 134</ref> and then sat in judgment on some of his men. He eventually joined the anti-Neville faction at court; although his wife was a [[House of Neville|Neville]], her family had by now [[Wars of the Roses|aligned themselves with the duke of York]]. He was amongst the party of lords that reported to parliament that the king was sick and they 'coud not rouse him' in March 1454.<ref>Goodwin, pages 51\u201352</ref> He was also an arbitrator between York and the king's party, headed by the [[Edmund Beaufort, 2nd Duke of Somerset|duke of Somerset]] after the king's recovery in 1454; although Griffiths says not a 'strictly impartial' one.<ref>Griffiths, R.A., ''The Reign of Henry VI'' (Berkeley, 1981), p. 739</ref> Indeed, Griffiths suggests that his appointment to the council on 15 April 1454, after the king's recovery and York's dismissal, was part of a concerted attempt to 're-balance' the council after the protectorate.<ref>Griffiths, R.A., ''The Reign of Henry VI'' (Berkeley, 1981), p. 727, 762 n. 70</ref> He was even reported (although wrongly) to have been recruiting an army to march against London in 1454.<ref>Jacob, E.F., The Fifteenth Century, (Oxford, 1993), 508.</ref> He was one of the few [[Lords Temporal]] to remain in Henry VI's council in the closing years of the decade, by which time he was the queen's chief steward.<ref>Jacob, E.F., ''The Fifteenth Century'', (Oxford, 1993), 481.</ref> He was also part of the [[royal commission]] set up by parliament in July 1455 to examine royal household expenditure;<ref>Griffiths, R.A., ''The Reign of Henry VI'' (Berkeley, 1981), p. 750, 769 n. 192</ref> the trust the Queen placed in him was demonstrated on 28 January 1457 when he was appointed to the council of the young [[Edward of Westminster, Prince of Wales|Prince of Wales]],<ref>Griffiths, R.A., ''The Reign of Henry VI'' (Berkeley, 1981), p. 781</ref> which had responsibility for his estate management, expenditure, personnel, and administration.<ref>Griffiths, R.A., ''The Reign of Henry VI'' (Berkeley, 1981), p. 781\u20132</ref>\n\nHis loyalty the crown was such that in 1460 the [[House of York|Yorkists]] proclaimed him one of their most mortal enemies among the king's supporters.<ref>Goodwin, page 105</ref> They also claimed that Beaumont, along with the earls of [[James Butler, 5th Earl of Ormond|Wiltshire]] and [[John Talbot, 2nd Earl of Shrewsbury|Shrewsbury]], orchestrated the Yorkists' [[attainder]] at the 1459 [[Parliament of Devils|Coventry parliament]], in order to seize the Yorkists' lands.<ref>Lander, J.R., ''Government and Community, 1450\u20131509'' (London, 1980), p. 205</ref> It is likely that they were the public focus of the Yorkists' enmity in a way that Henry VI's queen (to whom he was a personal adviser), [[Margaret of Anjou]] could not be.<ref>Hicks, M.A., ''The Wars of the Roses'' (London, 2010), p. 142</ref><ref>Griffiths, R.A., ''The Reign of Henry VI'' (Berkeley, 1981), p. 262</ref>\n\n==Wealth and estates==\n[[File:Map for Battle of Northampton by Ramsay.jpg|thumb|left|Map of the Battle of Northampton]]\nIn 1444, further expanding his wealth, he bought the [[reversion (law)|reversion]] of Sir Thomas Erdington's estates, as the latter was dying with no heir.<ref>Harriss, G.L., ''Shaping the Nation: England 1360\u20131461'' (Oxford, 2005), p. 148</ref> Like other lords involved in the fall of Gloucester in 1447, he benefitted immensely from the subsequent redistribution of the duke's lands.<ref>Harriss, G.L., ''Shaping the Nation: England 1360\u20131461'' (Oxford, 2005), p. 615</ref>\n\n==Death and legacy==\nHis allegiance to the [[House of Lancaster|Lancastrian]] regime remained strong enough for him to take arms against the [[House of York]], and eventually cost him his life. Commanding the central [[Battle (formation)|battle]] of the king's army<ref>Sadler, J., ''Towton: The Battle of Palmsunday Field 1461''(Barnsley, 2011), 55.</ref> he fell, with the [[Humphrey Stafford, 1st Duke of Buckingham|duke of Buckingham]] and [[Thomas Percy, 1st Baron Egremont|Lord Egremont]] whilst forming a human shield in defence of the king,<ref>Sadler, J., ''Towton: The Battle of Palmsunday Field 1461''(Barnsley, 2011), 56.</ref><ref>Santiuste, E., Edward IV and the Wars of the Roses (Barnsley, 2010), 28.</ref> against the victorious Yorkists in the [[Battle of Northampton (1460)|battle of Northampton]] on 10 July 1460.<ref>Santiuste, E., ''Edward IV and the Wars of the Roses'' (Barnsley, 2010), 30.</ref> Even though the king had fallen into Yorkist hands, Beaumont was not attainted, and his son was allowed to enter into his inheritance.<ref name=\"Ross1974\">{{cite book|author=Charles Derek Ross|title=Edward IV|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zbmkggaM_k8C|date=January 1974|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-02781-7|page=66}}</ref> Presumably in an attempt to reconcile his family to the new regime. This failed,<ref name=\"oxforddnb\"/> and Beaumont's second son (but who was his heir)<ref name=\"auto\"/> \u2013 the by now [[William Beaumont, 2nd Viscount Beaumont|second Viscount]] fought against the victorious army of the Yorkist king, [[Edward IV of England|Edward IV]] at the [[battle of Towton]] in April the next year.<ref name=\"Ross1974\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{cite book|author=George Goodwin|title=Fatal Colours: Towton, 1461 \u2013 England's Most Brutal Battle|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=A9EGec-o2joC|date=10 March 2011|publisher=Orion|isbn=978-0-297-86072-3|page=30}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://books.google.co.uk/books/about/The_Reign_of_King_Henry_VI.html?id=frWDmbf_mXEC&redir_esc=y R.A. Griffiths, ''The Reign of Henry VI'', at Google books]\n\n{{Wars of the Roses}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Beaumont, John Beaumont, 1st Viscount}}\n[[Category:People of the Wars of the Roses]]\n[[Category:Medieval English nobility]]\n[[Category:People from Folkingham]]\n[[Category:1460 deaths]]\n[[Category:1400s births]]\n[[Category:15th-century English people]]\n[[Category:Viscounts Beaumont]]\n[[Category:Barons Beaumont]]\n", "name_user": "MrDevonshire", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRoyal favour:Queen Margaret of Anjou.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Beaumont,_1st_Viscount_Beaumont"}
{"title_page": "Barton Hollow", "text_new": "{{About|the Civil Wars album|the album's title track|Barton Hollow (song)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2018}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Barton Hollow\n| type       = Studio\n| artist     = [[The Civil Wars]]\n| cover      = The Civil Wars - Barton Hollow.png\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Start date|2011|2|1|mf=yes}}\n| recorded   = The Art House, [[Nashville, Tennessee]]\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Folk rock]], [[alternative country]], [[indie folk]]\n| length     = {{Duration|m=46|s=27}}\n| label      = sensibility\n| producer   = [[Charlie Peacock]]\n| prev_title = [[Poison & Wine]]\n| prev_year  = 2009\n| next_title = [[The Civil Wars (album)|The Civil Wars]]\n| next_year  = 2013\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Barton Hollow\n | type        = Studio\n | single1     = [[Barton Hollow (song)|Barton Hollow]]\n | single1date = January 10, 2011\n}}\n}}\n'''''Barton Hollow''''' <ref>{{cite web|title=Barton Hollow|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/gp/product/B006VP1ONK?ie=UTF8&camp=1634&creativeASIN=B006VP1ONK&linkCode=xm2|publisher=Amazon.co.uk|accessdate=October 16, 2012}}</ref> is the first full-length studio album from [[The Civil Wars]]. Produced by [[Charlie Peacock]], it was released on February 1, 2011. It peaked at No.&nbsp;1 on the ''Billboard'' Digital Albums chart, No.&nbsp;10 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], No.&nbsp;1 on the ''Billboard'' Folk Albums chart, and No.&nbsp;2 on the ''Billboard'' Rock Albums chart, selling 25,000 copies in its first week.<ref>Billboard. Retrieved May 11, 2012 by [http://billboard.com/charts/billboard-200#/album/the-civil-wars/barton-hollow/1474607 Billboard.biz]</ref>  {{As of|2013|August}}, the album has sold 623,000 copies in the US.<ref name=yahoo>{{cite news|title=Week Ending Aug. 11, 2013. Albums: The Civil Wars, On Hiatus And On Top |url=http://music.yahoo.com/blogs/chart-watch/week-ending-aug-11-2013-albums-civil-wars-145540604.html |last=Grein |first=Paul |work=Chart Watch |publisher=Yahoo |date=August 14, 2013 |accessdate=August 24, 2013}}</ref>\n\nBarton Hollow was preceded by the lead single and title track, which was performed live on ''[[The Tonight Show with Jay Leno]]'' on January 14, 2011.<ref>[http://theaudioperv.com/2011/01/14/the-civil-wars-barton-hollow-113-leno/ The Audio Perv.] Retrieved May 11, 2012</ref>  A track on this album, \"Poison and Wine\" was previously released as a single from their EP ''[[Poison & Wine]]'' in 2009. On November 30, 2011, ''Barton Hollow'' was nominated for Grammys in the [[Grammy Award for Best Folk Album|Best Folk Album]] and [[Grammy Award for Best Country Duo/Group Performance|Best Country Duo/Group Performance]] categories, the latter for the title song. The album ended up winning both awards. Numerous publications noted that The Civil Wars were snubbed a Best New Artist nomination by [[The Grammys]]. At the ceremony The Civil Wars performed a portion of \"[[Barton Hollow (song)|Barton Hollow]]\".<ref>Roberts, Randall (November 30, 2011) Grammy Awards? Your Granny's Awards. Retrieved 2011-12-2, from [http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/music_blog/2011/11/critics-notebook-your-grannys-awards.html LATimes.com]</ref><ref>Maerz, Melissa (December 1, 2011) Grammys: Who Got Snubbed? Retrieved 2011-12-2, from [http://music-mix.ew.com/2011/12/01/grammys-snubs-nominees EW.com]</ref><ref>Christman, Ed (December 1, 2011) Retailers Predict Grammy Sales Bumps. Retrieved 2011-12-2, from [http://www.billboard.biz/bbbiz/industry/retail/adele-bruno-mars-skrillex-retailers-project-1005601552.story Billboard.biz]</ref> The vinyl LP version of the record was pressed at [[United Record Pressing]] in Nashville, TN.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/media/set/?set=a.10150570730304775.403926.45121499774&type=3 |title=Civil Wars - Barton Hollow (Sensibility Music) |publisher=Facebook |date= |accessdate=August 24, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album reviews\n| rev1 = Allmusic\n| rev1Score = {{rating|4|5}}<ref name=allm/>\n| rev2 = MusicOMH\n| rev2Score = {{rating|4|5}}<ref name=momh/>\t\n}}\n''Barton Hollow'' was included on the 2011 Best Album lists of [[NPR Music]],<ref>NPR Music: 50 Favorite Albums of 2011 (December 3, 2011) Retrieved 2011-12-5, from [http://npr.org/2011/12/05/142860882/50-favorites-b-e NPR.org]</ref> ''[[Paste (magazine)|Paste Magazine]]'',<ref>Jackson, Josh (November 29, 2011) Paste Magazine: The 50 Best Albums of 2011. Retrieved 2011-12-5, from [http://pastemagazine.com/blogs/lists/2011/11/the-50-best-albums-of-2011.html?p=4 PasteMagazine.com]</ref> ''[[American Songwriter]]'',<ref>(2011, November 29) American Songwriter's 50 Top Albums of 2011. Retrieved 2011-12-5, from [http://americansongwriter.com/2011/11/american-songwriters-top-50-albums-of-2011/3/ AmericanSongwriter.com]</ref> ''[[Rough Trade (shops)|Rough Trade]]'',<ref>(2011, November 29) Albums of the Year Top 100. Retrieved 2011-12-5, from [http://roughtrade.com/site/content.lasso?page=AOY_2011_page2.html RoughTrade.com] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111205030858/http://roughtrade.com/site/content.lasso?page=AOY_2011_page2.html |date=December 5, 2011 }}</ref> [[Amazon.com]],<ref>Amazon (December 3, 2011) The Best Albums of 2011. Retrieved 2011-12-7, from [https://www.amazon.com/gp/feature.html/?docId=1000757031 Amazon.com]</ref> ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'',<ref>Time (December 7, 2011) Top 10 Albums of 2011. Retrieved 2011-12-7, from [http://time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,2101344_2101364_2101591,00.html ''Time'']</ref> [[iTunes]],<ref>iTunes Rewind 2011 (December 8, 2011) Retrieved 2011-12-10, from [http://tw.itunes.com/jCf iTunes]</ref> ''[[The Huffington Post]]'',<ref>Chenfeld, Cliff (December 8, 2011) The Best Music of 2011. Retrieved 2011-12-10, from [http://huffingtonpost.com/cliff-chenfeld/the-best-music-of-2011_b_1134189.html The Huffington Post]</ref> [[Associated Press]],<ref>Moody, Nekessa Mumbi (December 20, 2011) Adele tops AP's list of Best Albums of 2011. Retrieved 2011-12-22, from [http://sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/n/a/2011/12/20/entertainment/e071732S71.DTL SFGate.com]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111221155939/http://sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=%2Fn%2Fa%2F2011%2F12%2F20%2Fentertainment%2Fe071732S71.DTL |date=December 21, 2011  }}</ref> ''[[The Tennessean]]'',<ref>Tennessean Music Team (December 21, 2011) 2011's Biggest Albums: Music That Made a Mark. Retrieved 2011-12-22, from [http://blogs.tennessean.com/tunein/2011/12/21/2011s-biggest-albums-music-that-made-a-mark Tennessean.com]</ref> [[AllMusic.com]]<ref>AMG Staff (December 14, 2011) AllMusic's Favorite Folk Albums of 2011. Retrieved 2011-12-25, from [http://blog.allmusic.com/2011/12/14/allmusics-favorite-folk-albums-of-2011 AllMusic.com]</ref> and more.\n\nAndrew Leahey of AllMusic said that Williams and White \"trace each other's melodies with close harmonies that never fail to lose their romance\". He gave ''Barton Hollow'' four of five star and called it \"Good stuff\".<ref name=allm>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/barton-hollow-r2127823/review |work=[[Allmusic]]|first=Andrew|last=Leahey|title=Barton Hollow - The Civil Wars Review |date=|accessdate=March 28, 2012}}</ref> Darren Lee of MusicOMH also gave four of five stars, saying \"The album's songs of love, loss and longing are an immediate pleasure to listen to, displaying real restraint in a disc that it is pleasingly sparse and unembellished.\"<ref name=momh>{{cite web |url=http://www.musicomh.com/albums/civil-wars_0312.htm |work=[[MusicOMH]] |first=Darren |last=Lee |title=The Civil Wars - Barton Hollow |accessdate=March 28, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120312201652/http://www.musicomh.com/albums/civil-wars_0312.htm |archivedate=March 12, 2012  }}</ref>\n\nIn 2017 it was ranked No.&nbsp;66 in ''Paste'' magazine's \"The 100 Best Indie Folk Albums\" list.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2017/04/the-best-indie-folk-albums-1.html?p=2 | title= The 100 Best Indie Folk Albums | accessdate=October 11, 2018 |publisher=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\nAll songs written by [[Joy Williams (singer)|Joy Williams]] and [[John Paul White]], except where noted. The two bonus tracks are available with electronic versions of the album, but not on the CD. An extended version of '''''Barton Hollow''''' was released in Europe through Sony Music on March 1, 2012, which contained the 12 tracks included with the North American release, the 2 bonus tracks from the electronic version, plus 4 additional tracks.\n\n{{track listing\n| collapsed = \n| headline = \n| title1 = 20 Years\n| length1 = 3:02\n| title2 = I've Got This Friend\n| length2 = 3:24\n| title3 = C'est la mort\n| length3 = 2:30\n| title4 = To Whom It May Concern\n| length4 = 3:32\n| title5 = Poison & Wine\n| writer5 = Williams, White, [[Chris Lindsey]]\n| length5 = 3:40\n| title6 = My Father's Father\n| length6 = 3:21\n| title7 = [[Barton Hollow (song)|Barton Hollow]]\n| length7 = 3:26\n| title8 = The Violet Hour\n| length8 = 3:26\n| title9 = Girl With the Red Balloon\n| length9 = 3:50\n| title10 = Falling\n| length10 = 3:59\n| title11 = Forget Me Not\n| length11 = 2:57\n| title12 = Birds of a Feather\n| length12 = 3:06\n}}\n\n{{track listing\n| collapsed = yes\n| headline = Electronic version bonus tracks\n| title13 = [[I Want You Back]] \n| writer13 = [[Berry Gordy]], [[Freddie Perren]], [[Alphonzo Mizell]] and [[Deke Richards]]\n| length13 = 3:15\n| title14 = [[Dance Me to the End of Love]]\n| writer14 = [[Leonard Cohen]]\n| length14 = 3:05\n}}\n\n{{track listing\n| collapsed =  yes\n| headline = European edition bonus tracks\n| title13 = [[Billie Jean]]\n| writer13 = Michael Jackson\n| length13 = 4:09\n| title14 = [[I Want You Back]] \n| writer14 = [[Berry Gordy]], [[Freddie Perren]], [[Alphonzo Mizell]] and [[Deke Richards]]\n| length14 = 3:15\n| title15 = [[Dance Me to the End of Love]]\n| writer15 = Leonard Cohen\n| length15 = 3:05\n| title16 = [[You Are My Sunshine]]\n| writer16 = Jimmie Davis and [[Charles Mitchell (songwriter)|Charles Mitchell]]\n| length16 = 3:09\n| title17 = Goodbye Girl\n| writer17 = John Paul White; Joy Williams\n| length17 = 4:00\n| title18 = Marionette\n| note18 = Demo) (Bonus\n| writer18 = John Paul White; Joy Williams\n| length18 = 3:01\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\nListed in AllMusic.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/barton-hollow-mw0002103142/credits |title=Barton Hollow - The Civil Wars &#124; Credits |publisher=AllMusic |date=February 1, 2011 |accessdate=August 24, 2013}}</ref>\n\n* [[Joy Williams (singer)|Joy Williams]]: lead vocals, background vocals, piano, [[Hohner]] organ, [[bell (instrument)|bell]]s\n* [[John Paul White]]: lead vocals, background vocals, acoustic guitar, electric guitar, [[resonator guitar]], banjo, bass guitar\n* Andy Leftwich: fiddle, [[mandolin]]\n* David Davidson: violin\n* John Catchings: cello\n* Jerry McPherson: electric guitar\n* [[J.T. Corenflos]]: electric guitar\n* [[Dan Dugmore]]: [[pedal steel guitar]]\n* Tim Lauer: keyboards, synthesizer, [[keyboard bass]], organ, \"tiny keyboard\"\n* [[Charlie Peacock]]: electric piano, trumpet, producer, additional engineering\n* [[Barry Bales]]: double bass\n* Ken Lewis: percussion\n* Richie Biggs: engineer, mixer\n* Richard Dodd: mastering\n\n==Charts==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! Chart (2011\u201312)\n! Peak<br />position\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Belgian Albums Chart]] (Wallonia)<ref name=bdch>{{cite web|author=Steffen Hung |url=http://dutchcharts.nl/showitem.asp?interpret=The+Civil+Wars&titel=Barton+Hollow&cat=a |title=The Civil Wars - Barton Hollow |publisher=dutchcharts.nl |date=March 17, 2012 |accessdate=March 26, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141104063022/http://dutchcharts.nl/showitem.asp?interpre