{"title_page": "Barrow Bombers", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox motorcycle speedway team\n|clubname = Barrow Bombers\n|image =\n|track = [[Holker Street]]<br />[[Barrow-in-Furness]]\n|country = [[England]]\n|founded = 1972\n|closed = 1974\n|manager  =\n|captain =\n|league =\n|website =\n|colours = Yellow\n|tracksize = {{convert|379|m|yd}}\n|track record time=\n|track record date=\n|track record holder=\n|honour1 =\n|year1 =\n}}\n\nThe '''Barrow Bombers''' were a [[motorcycle speedway|Speedway]] team promoted in [[Barrow-in-Furness]]. Speedway had been promoted at a number of venues. In  1930 a number of meetings were held at [[Holker Street]], the home of [[Barrow A.F.C.]] the towns football club.<ref>Pavey, A. (2004) ''Speedway in the North-West'', Tempus Publishing Ltd. {{ISBN|0-7524-3192-7}}</ref> Racing moved to Little Park, Roose in 1931 but crowd levels were insufficient. Speedway returned to Barrow in 1972 back at [[Holker Street]] when the former [[Romford Bombers]] promotion who started the season at the [[West Ham Stadium]] in [[London]] moved the team north.\n\nThe team were initially called the '''Barrow Happy Faces''' as their sponsor at the time was Duckhams oil - its happy face logo was prominently displayed on the team's race jackets. The team were renamed '''Barrow Bombers''' for the 1973 and 1974 seasons. Despite good crowds, a new home had to be found for the team after the end of the 1974 season, when problems with ground sharing became insurmountable.<ref>Bamford, R & Jarvis J.(2001). ''Homes of British Speedway''.  {{ISBN|0-7524-2210-3}}</ref>\n\nLocal businessman Cliff Hindle built a new stadium at [[Barrow Park Road Stadium|Park Road]], which opened halfway through the 1977 season for a short series of open meetings. In 1978 a team was entered under the name '''Furness Flyers''', but finished bottom of the [[Speedway British League Division Two|National League]]. Crowds were poor and the track closed after only one season.\n\nSpeedway in Barrow was revived under ex-Barrow rider Chris Roynon in 1984. A series of challenge matches were held to gauge public support. Interest was such that a team was entered for the 1985 season under the name of the '''Barrow Blackhawks'''. After a disastrous start to the season with an understrength team, the Blackhawks were thrown out of the league. A number of challenge matches were held for the remainder of the season in front of low crowds before the track once again closed.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*https://web.archive.org/web/20071022095136/http://home.clara.net/barrowfan/BarrowSpeedway.htm\nThis link leads to a page unavailable message as of 15/05/2013\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Barrow Bombers}}\n[[Category:Sport in Barrow-in-Furness]]\n[[Category:Defunct British speedway teams]]\n\n\n{{England-sport-team-stub}}\n{{motorcycle-speedway-team-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox motorcycle speedway team\n|clubname = Barrow Bombers\n|image =\n|track = [[Holker Street]]<br />[[Barrow-in-Furness]]\n|country = [[England]]\n|founded = 1972\n|closed = 1974\n|manager  =\n|captain =\n|league =\n|website =\n|colours = Yellow\n|tracksize = {{convert|379|m|yd}}\n|track record time=\n|track record date=\n|track record holder=\n|honour1 =\n|year1 =\n}}\n\nThe '''Barrow Bombers''' were a [[motorcycle speedway|Speedway]] team promoted in [[Barrow-in-Furness]]. Speedway had been promoted at a number of venues. In  1930 a number of meetings were held at [[Holker Street]], the home of [[Barrow A.F.C.]] the towns football club.<ref>Pavey,A. (2004) ''Speedway in the North-West'', Tempus Publishing Ltd. {{ISBN|0-7524-3192-7}}</ref> Racing moved to Little Park, Roose in 1931 but crowd levels were insufficient. Speedway returned to Barrow in 1972 back at [[Holker Street]] when the former [[Romford Bombers]] promotion who started the season at the [[West Ham Stadium]] in [[London]] moved the team north.\n\nThe team were initially called the '''Barrow Happy Faces''' as their sponsor at the time was Duckhams oil - its happy face logo was prominently displayed on the teams race jackets. The team were renamed '''Barrow Bombers''' for the 1973 and 1974 seasons. Despite good crowds, a new home had to be found for the team after the end of the 1974 season, when problems with ground sharing became insurmountable.<ref>Bamford, R & Jarvis J.(2001). ''Homes of British Speedway''.  {{ISBN|0-7524-2210-3}}</ref>\n\nLocal businessman Cliff Hindle built a new stadium at [[Barrow Park Road Stadium|Park Road]], which opened halfway through the 1977 season for a short series of open meetings. In 1978 a team was entered under the name '''Furness Flyers''', but finished bottom of the [[Speedway British League Division Two|National League]]. Crowds were poor and the track closed after only one season.\n\nSpeedway in Barrow was revived under ex-Barrow rider Chris Roynon in 1984. A series of challenge matches were held to gauge public support. Interest was such that a team was entered for the 1985 season under the name of the '''Barrow Blackhawks'''. After a disastrous start to the season with an understrength team, the Blackhawks were thrown out of the league. A number of challenge matches were held for the remainder of the season in front of low crowds before the track once again closed.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*https://web.archive.org/web/20071022095136/http://home.clara.net/barrowfan/BarrowSpeedway.htm\nThis link leads to a page unavailable message as of 15/05/2013\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Barrow Bombers}}\n[[Category:Sport in Barrow-in-Furness]]\n[[Category:Defunct British speedway teams]]\n\n\n{{England-sport-team-stub}}\n{{motorcycle-speedway-team-stub}}\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Typo fixing, replaced: teams race \u2192 team's race", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barrow_Bombers"}
{"title_page": "Climbers' Club", "text_new": "The '''Climbers' Club''' is the senior rock-climbing club in Wales and England  (outside the [[Lake District]]). It was founded in 1898 and publishes guidebooks in the main climbing areas in Wales and Southern England. It also owns several climbing huts in these areas.\n\n==Early history==\nThe Club developed from [[England]]'s and [[Wales]]' earliest attempt to formally organize and bring together those who were active in participating and developing the \"new\" sport of [[rock climbing]].\n\nIn 1870, [[C. E. Mathews]] founded the ''[[Society of Welsh Rabbits]]'', which was a loose association of climbers who were largely English. By 1897, members of the Society saw a need for something more formal, and forty met at the [[Caf\u00e9 Monico]] in London to discuss forming a new Club.<ref>[http://www.thebmc.co.uk/Feature.aspx?id=1483 Clublife] at thebmc.co.uk, dated 02/11/2003 (accessed 6 January 2008)</ref>\n\nOriginally perceived as merely a dining club, meeting once a year in London, one-third of the original members were also affiliated with the venerable  [[Alpine Club (UK)|Alpine Club]] -  generally more conservative and populated largely by alpinists who had little regard for climbing in Great Britain, except as training for the Alps. The first president, C. E. Mathews, was, himself, a pillar of  the AC, but supported this new adventurous but parochial initiative. Not without the wry criticism so fashionable at the time, however, as the arch-conservative mountaineer [[Douglas Freshfield]] punned:<ref>Clark, R. W. and Pyatt, E. C. (1957). \"Mountaineering in Britain\", Phoenix House.</ref>\n\n:::Why is it to the Alpine Club\n:::Our C. E. M. no longer keeps?\n:::Why should he found - himself as hub \u2013\n:::A Climbers' Club for ''chimney sweeps''.\n\n==See also==\nOther UK Mountaineering 'Senior Clubs'\n*[[Alpine Club (UK)|Alpine Club]]\n*[[Fell and Rock|Fell and Rock Climbing Club]]\n*[[The Rucksack Club]]\n*[[Scottish Mountaineering Club]]\n*[[The Wayfarers' Club]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n* Hankinson, Alan (1972). \"The First Tigers\", J. M. Dent & Sons\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.climbers-club.co.uk - climbers club main web page]\n\n[[Category:Climbing clubs in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Climbing organizations]]\n\n\n{{climbing-stub}}\n", "text_old": "The '''Climbers' Club''' is the senior rock-climbing club in Wales and England  (outside the [[Lake District]]). It was founded in 1898 and publishes guidebooks in the main climbing areas in Wales and Southern England. It also owns several climbing huts in these areas.\n\n==Early history==\nThe Club developed from [[England]]'s and [[Wales]]' earliest attempt to formally organize and bring together those who were active in participating and developing the \"new\" sport of [[rock climbing]].\n\nIn 1870, C. E. Mathews founded the ''[[Society of Welsh Rabbits]]'', which was a loose association of climbers who were largely English. By 1897, members of the Society saw a need for something more formal, and forty met at the [[Caf\u00e9 Monico]] in London to discuss forming a new Club.<ref>[http://www.thebmc.co.uk/Feature.aspx?id=1483 Clublife] at thebmc.co.uk, dated 02/11/2003 (accessed 6 January 2008)</ref>\n\nOriginally perceived as merely a dining club, meeting once a year in London, one-third of the original members were also affiliated with the venerable  [[Alpine Club (UK)|Alpine Club]] -  generally more conservative and populated largely by alpinists who had little regard for climbing in Great Britain, except as training for the Alps. The first president, C. E. Mathews, was, himself, a pillar of  the AC, but supported this new adventurous but parochial initiative. Not without the wry criticism so fashionable at the time, however, as the arch-conservative mountaineer [[Douglas Freshfield]] punned:<ref>Clark, R. W. and Pyatt, E. C. (1957). \"Mountaineering in Britain\", Phoenix House.</ref>\n\n:::Why is it to the Alpine Club\n:::Our C. E. M. no longer keeps?\n:::Why should he found - himself as hub \u2013\n:::A Climbers' Club for ''chimney sweeps''.\n\n==See also==\nOther UK Mountaineering 'Senior Clubs'\n*[[Alpine Club (UK)|Alpine Club]]\n*[[Fell and Rock|Fell and Rock Climbing Club]]\n*[[The Rucksack Club]]\n*[[Scottish Mountaineering Club]]\n*[[The Wayfarers' Club]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n* Hankinson, Alan (1972). \"The First Tigers\", J. M. Dent & Sons\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.climbers-club.co.uk - climbers club main web page]\n\n[[Category:Climbing clubs in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Climbing organizations]]\n\n\n{{climbing-stub}}\n", "name_user": "AtticTapestry", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly history:Link toC. E. Mathews", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Climbers%27_Club"}
{"title_page": "Paul Steed", "text_new": "{{pp-semi-blp|small=yes}}\n'''Paul Howard Steed, Jr.''' (November 6, 1964<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.quake2.com/oldnews/10-30-97_11-7-97.html|title=Happy Birthday Mr. Steed!|date=November 6, 1997|author=Rotwang|accessdate=November 8, 2013}}</ref> &ndash; August 11, 2012) was a video game modeller and artist. He worked for [[Origin Systems]], [[Electronic Arts]], [[id Software]], [[Wild Tangent]], [[Microsoft's]] [[Xbox (console)|Xbox]], [[Atari]], and Exigent. He created artwork or models for several prominent game series including ''[[Wing Commander (franchise)|Wing Commander]]'' and ''[[Quake (video game)|Quake]]''. He was employed by id Software until he was fired in retaliation for conflict over the creation of ''[[Doom 3]]'' (according to [[John D. Carmack|John Carmack]]).<ref name=\".plan\">{{cite web\n  | last = Carmack\n  | first = John\n  | authorlink = John D. Carmack\n  | coauthors = \n  | title = 6/1/00 .plan document for Doom 3\n  | publisher = GameFinger\n  | date = June 1, 2000\n  | url = http://finger.planetquake.com/plan.asp?userid=johnc&id=14425\n  | accessdate =  2010-07-10 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20060506064251/http://finger.planetquake.com/plan.asp?userid=johnc&id=14425 |archivedate = 2006-05-06}}</ref>\n\nSteed began his career with videogames in 1991 at Origin Systems, after answering a newspaper ad that said \"Fantasy artist wanted\". Starting as a game design sketcher, he moved up to art director then project director. Steed has indicated he \"didn't touch a mouse until I was 27.\" He worked as an art director at Virgin Entertainment and a designer at Iguana entertainment as well. In 2000 after being fired from id Software he went to work for Wild Tangent making several dancing girl visualizers for Winamp and a third-person shooter called ''Betty Bad'' (an homage to Steed's favorite arcade game, ''[[Tempest (arcade game)|Tempest]]'').\n\nSteed gained press and controversy with the release of a \"Crackwhore\" female model for ''[[Quake II]]'' in response to a skin (character texture) contest for the first ''Quake'' sponsored by a group of female gamers who called themselves the \"Crackwhore Clan\". The Crackwhore model was released after ''Quake II'' was released as a downloadable character as an homage to that same female gamer clan. While ''Quake II'' included a female character as an option when playing, both the phraseology and approach to the Crackwhore model received some amount of criticism despite the 'Crackwhore Clan' having been created and organized by and composed solely of female gamers - not Paul Steed.\n\nHe was active in the game development community and gave talks not only at the annual Game Developer's Conference, but also at universities and art institutes. He initiated and sponsored several modeling contests such as the Bad Girl and Cute Doll contests by which he challenged any and all other modelers to compete against him for sponsored prizes. Paul convinced many vendors like Autodesk to contribute those prizes as well as recognition to the contest winners.\n\nA published author, Paul Steed wrote three books on modeling and animating game characters for 3D games. He served on the Advisory Board for GDC for many years and as creative director for Microsoft's Xbox and Atari he gained experience on the other side of the developer fence. He left Atari in 2006 to co-found [[Exigent3d|Exigent]] with Garland Wong and Jesse Rapczak. As President and Chief Creative Officer at Exigent, a global game art company for next generation and casual games, Paul oversaw more than 100 artists in India and China while consulting with top developers and publishers. Lately he provided creative and managerial leadership for an unannounced UTV Ignition Entertainment project, but subsequently moved on to a series of casual and console projects.\n\nSteed died on August 11, 2012.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Takahashi|first1=Dean|title=Legendary and controversial video game artist Paul Steed passes away|url=https://venturebeat.com/2012/08/13/legendary-and-controversial-video-game-artist-paul-steed-passes-away/|website=Venture Beat|date=August 13, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Good|first1=Owen|title=Paul Steed, Artist on Wing Commander and Quake Series, Dies|url=http://kotaku.com/5933919/paul-steed-artist-on-wing-commander-and-quake-series-dies|website=Kotaku|date=August 11, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Steed, Paul (2001). ''Modelling a Character in 3DS Max''. Wordware Publishing. {{ISBN|1-55622-815-5}}.\n* Steed, Paul (2002). ''Animating Real-Time Game Characters''. Charles River Media. {{ISBN|1-58450-270-3}}.\n* Steed, Paul (2005). ''Modelling a Character in 3DS Max, 2nd Edition''. Wordware Publishing. {{ISBN|1-55622-088-X}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.mobygames.com/developer/sheet/view/developerId,1065/ ''Paul Steed''] profile on [[MobyGames]]\n\n{{id Software}}\n\n{{Origin Systems}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Steed, Paul}}\n[[Category:Video game artists]]\n[[Category:2012 deaths]]\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Id Software people]]\n[[Category:Origin Systems people]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-semi-blp|small=yes}}\n'''Paul Howard Steed, Jr.''' (November 6, 1964<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.quake2.com/oldnews/10-30-97_11-7-97.html|title=Happy Birthday Mr. Steed!|date=November 6, 1997|author=Rotwang|accessdate=November 8, 2013}}</ref> &ndash; August 11, 2012) was a video game modeller and artist. He worked for [[Origin Systems]], [[Electronic Arts]], [[id Software]], [[Wild Tangent]], [[Microsoft's]] [[Xbox (console)|Xbox]], [[Atari]], and Exigent. He created artwork or models for several prominent game series including ''[[Wing Commander (franchise)|Wing Commander]]'' and ''[[Quake (video game)|Quake]]''. He was employed by id Software until he was fired in retaliation for conflict over the creation of ''[[Doom 3]]'' (according to [[John D. Carmack|John Carmack]]).<ref name=\".plan\">{{cite web\n  | last = Carmack\n  | first = John\n  | authorlink = John D. Carmack\n  | coauthors = \n  | title = 6/1/00 .plan document for Doom 3\n  | publisher = GameFinger\n  | date = June 1, 2000\n  | url = http://finger.planetquake.com/plan.asp?userid=johnc&id=14425\n  | accessdate =  2010-07-10 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20060506064251/http://finger.planetquake.com/plan.asp?userid=johnc&id=14425 |archivedate = 2006-05-06}}</ref>\n\nSteed began his career with videogames in 1991 at Origin Systems, after answering a newspaper ad that said \"Fantasy artist wanted\". Starting as a game design sketcher, he moved up to art director then project director. Steed has indicated he \"didn't touch a mouse until I was 27.\" He worked as an art director at Virgin Entertainment and a designer at Iguana entertainment as well. In 2000 after being fired from id Software he went to work for Wild Tangent making several dancing girl visualizers for Winamp and a third-person shooter called ''Betty Bad'' (an homage to Steed's favorite arcade game, ''[[Tempest (arcade game)|Tempest]]'').\n\nSteed gained press and controversy with the release of a \"Crackwhore\" female model for ''[[Quake II]]'' in response to a skin (character texture) contest for the first ''Quake'' sponsored by a group of female gamers who called themselves the \"Crackwhore Clan\". The Crackwhore model was released after ''Quake II'' was released as a downloadable character as an homage to that same female gamer clan. While ''Quake II'' included a female character as an option when playing, both the phraseology and approach to the Crackwhore model received some amount of criticism despite the 'Crackwhore Clan' having been created and organized by and composed solely of female gamers - not Paul Steed.\n\nHe was active in the game development community and gave talks not only at the annual Game Developer's Conference, but also at universities and art institutes. He initiated and sponsored several modeling contests such as the Bad Girl and Cute Doll contests by which he challenged any and all other modelers to compete against him for sponsored prizes. Paul convinced many vendors like Autodesk to contribute those prizes as well as recognition to the contest winners.\n\nA published author, Paul Steed wrote three books on modeling and animating game characters for 3D games. He served on the Advisory Board for GDC for many years and as creative director for Microsoft's Xbox and Atari he gained experience on the other side of the developer fence. He left Atari in 2006 to co-found [[Exigent3d|Exigent]] with Garland Wong and Jesse Rapczak. As President and Chief Creative Officer at Exigent, a global game art company for next generation and casual games, Paul oversaw more than 100 artists in India and China while consulting with top developers and publishers. Lately he provided creative and managerial leadership for an unannounced UTV Ignition Entertainment project, but subsequently moved on to a series of casual and console projects.\n\nSteed died on August 11, 2012.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Takahashi|first1=Dean|title=Legendary and controversial video game artist Paul Steed passes away|url=https://venturebeat.com/2012/08/13/legendary-and-controversial-video-game-artist-paul-steed-passes-away/|website=Venture Beat|date=August 13, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Good|first1=Owen|title=Paul Steed, Artist on Wing Commander and Quake Series, Dies|url=http://kotaku.com/5933919/paul-steed-artist-on-wing-commander-and-quake-series-dies|website=Kotaku|date=August 11, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Steed, Paul (2001). ''Modelling a Character in 3DS Max''. Wordware Publishing. {{ISBN|1-55622-815-5}}.\n* Steed, Paul (2002). ''Animating Real-Time Game Characters''. Charles River Media. {{ISBN|1-58450-270-3}}.\n* Steed, Paul (2005). ''Modelling a Character in 3DS Max, 2nd Edition''. Wordware Publishing. {{ISBN|1-55622-088-X}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.mobygames.com/developer/sheet/view/developerId,1065/ ''Paul Steed''] profile on [[MobyGames]]\n\n{{id Software}}\n\n{{Origin Systems}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Steed, Paul}}\n[[Category:Video game artists]]\n[[Category:2012 deaths]]\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Id Software people]]\n\n[[Category:Origin Systems]]\n", "name_user": "Mika1h", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Steed"}
{"title_page": "Before You Go (Lewis Capaldi song)", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Before You Go\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Lewis Capaldi]]\n| album      = [[Divinely Uninspired to a Hellish Extent]] {{noitalic|(extended edition)}}\n| released   = {{start date|2019|11|19|df=y}}\n| format     =\n* [[Music download|Digital download]]\n* [[Streaming media|streaming]]\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = <!-- Please source genres -->\n| length     = {{duration|m=3|s=36}}\n| label      =\n* [[Vertigo Records|Vertigo Berlin]]\n* [[Universal Music Group|Universal]]\n| writer     =\n* Lewis Capaldi\n* [[TMS (production team)|Ben Kohn]]\n* [[TMS (production team)|Pete Kelleher]]\n* Phil Plested\n* [[TMS (production team)|Tom Bames]]\n| producer   = [[TMS (production team)|TMS]]\n| prev_title = [[Hold Me While You Wait]]\n| prev_year  = 2019\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n| misc       =\n}}\n\"'''Before You Go'''\" is a song by Scottish singer-songwriter [[Lewis Capaldi]], released as a single from the extended edition of his debut studio album ''[[Divinely Uninspired to a Hellish Extent]]'' on 19 November 2019. The song was made available upon pre-order of the extended edition.<ref name=\"NME\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/lewis-capaldi-reflects-absolutely-wild-2019-before-you-go-2569609|title=Lewis Capaldi reflects on \"absolutely wild\" 2019 on new track \"Before You Go\" \u2013 listen|last=Skinner|first=Tom|website=[[NME]]|date=19 November 2019|accessdate=19 November 2019}}</ref> The song was sent to US radio stations on January 6, 2020 as his second US single. It reached number one on the [[Irish Singles Chart]] in November 2019 and on the [[UK Singles Chart]] in January 2020, becoming Capaldi's second chart-topper in the UK and third in Ireland.\n\n==Background and composition==\nAbout the song, Capaldi revealed in a social media post that it \"is by far the most personal tune\" he has ever written and stated that the previous year has been \"absolutely wild\" for him.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.spinsouthwest.com/music/lewis-capaldi-releases-new-track-go-926862|title=Lewis Capaldi Releases New Track \"Before You Go\"|last=Lucey|first=Tuathla|website=[[Spin South West]]|date=19 November 2019|accessdate=19 November 2019}}</ref> According to ''[[Idolator (website)|Idolator]]'', the song \"deals with the emotional aftermath of suicide\", and was inspired by the suicide of Capaldi\u2019s aunt while Capaldi was a child.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.idolator.com/7903230/lewis-capaldi-new-single-before-you-go|title=Lewis Capaldi Releases Poignant New Single \"Before You Go\"|last=Wass|first=Mike|website=[[Idolator (website)|Idolator]]|date=19 November 2019|accessdate=19 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\nGary James of ''Entertainment Focus'' described the song as an \"emotional track\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.entertainment-focus.com/uncategorized/lewis-capaldi-releases-most-personal-song-yet-with-before-you-go/|title=Lewis Capaldi releases most personal song yet with Before You Go|last=James|first=Gary|website=Entertainment Focus|date=19 November 2019|accessdate=19 November 2019}}</ref> Maxamillion Polo of ''Ones to Watch'' thought that the song \"is a tried-and-true song of heartbreak, one that is not looking to place blame but solve those questions lacking answers\" and questioned if Capaldi's emotional tone was \"the result of a greater sense of loss\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.onestowatch.com/blog/lewis-capaldi-reflects-in-before-you-go-his|title=Lewis Capaldi Reflects in \"Before You Go,\" His Most Personal Tune to Date|last=Polo|first=Maxamillion|website=Ones to Watch|date=19 November 2019|accessdate=19 November 2019}}</ref> ''[[Clash (magazine)#ClashMusic.com|Clash Music]]'''s Robin Murray called the track \"trademark Capaldi\", further describing it as \"a rousing piece of acoustic songwriting with a driving vocal\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.clashmusic.com/news/lewis-capaldi-shares-new-single-before-you-go|title=Lewis Capaldi Shares New Single \"Before You Go\"|last=Murray|first=Robin|website=[[Clash (magazine)#ClashMusic.com|Clash Music]]|date=19 November 2019|accessdate=19 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| headline = Stream<ref>{{cite web|url=https://open.spotify.com/album/0488X5veBK6t3vSmIiTDJY|title=Before You Go|website=[[Spotify]]|accessdate=19 November 2019}}</ref>\n| title1 = Before You Go\n| length1 = 3:36\n| title2 = [[Bruises (Lewis Capaldi song)|Bruises]]\n| length2 = 3:38\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\nCredits adapted from [[Tidal (service)|Tidal]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://listen.tidal.com/album/122351387/track/122351390|title=Before You Go / Lewis Capaldi \u2013 Tidal|website=[[Tidal (service)|Tidal]]|accessdate=19 November 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Lewis Capaldi]] \u2013 songwriting, vocals\n* [[TMS (production team)|Ben Kohn]] \u2013 songwriting, production, bass guitar\n* [[TMS (production team)|Pete Kelleher]] \u2013 songwriting, production, keyboards\n* [[TMS (production team)|Tom Bames]] \u2013 songwriting, production, drums\n* Phil Plested \u2013 songwriting, background vocals\n* Vern Asbury \u2013 guitar\n* Robert Vosgien \u2013 master engineering\n* [[Spike Stent|Mark \"Spike\" Stent]] \u2013 mixing\n* Chris Bishop \u2013 vocal engineering\n\n==Charts==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2019\u20132020)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{single chart|Australia|7|artist=Lewis Capaldi|song=Before You Go|rowheader=true|accessdate=29 February 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Austria|20|artist=Lewis Capaldi|song=Before You Go|rowheader=true|accessdate=19 March 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Flanders|2|artist=Lewis Capaldi|song=Before You Go|rowheader=true|accessdate=21 March 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Wallonia|4|artist=Lewis Capaldi|song=Before You Go|rowheader=true|accessdate=4 April 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Canada|27|artist=Lewis Capaldi|rowheader=true|accessdate=10 March 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Czech Republic|1|year=2020|week=11|rowheader=true|accessdate=17 March 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Czechdigital|21|year=2020|week=12|rowheader=true|accessdate=24 March 2020}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Denmark ([[Tracklisten]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hitlisten.nu/default.asp?w=11&y=2020&list=t40|title=Track Top-40 Uge 11, 2020|publisher=[[Hitlisten]]|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n| 18\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Ecuador ([[National-Report]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.national-report.com/top-ecuador/|title=Top 100 Ecuador|publisher=[[National-Report]]|accessdate=3 April 2020|language=Spanish|archiveurl=http://archive.today/PCqyn|archivedate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n| 64\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| France ([[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique|SNEP]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://snepmusique.com/les-tops/le-top-de-la-semaine/top-albums/?semaine=9?&annee=2020&categorie=Top%20Singles|title=Top Singles (Week 9, 2020)|publisher=[[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique]]|language=French|accessdate=3 March 2020}}</ref>\n| 54\n|-\n{{single chart|Germany2|42|songid=1921258|artist=Lewis Capaldi|song=Before You Go|rowheader=true|accessdate=21 February 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Hungary|21|year=2020|week=14|rowheader=true|accessdate=10 April 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Hungarysingle|26|year=2020|week=8|rowheader=true|accessdate=28 February 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Hungarystream|39|year=2020|week=7|rowheader=true|accessdate=22 February 2020}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Ireland ([[Irish Recorded Music Association|IRMA]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://irma.ie/index.cfm?page=irish-charts&chart=Singles|title=IRMA \u2013 Irish Charts|publisher=[[Irish Recorded Music Association]]|accessdate=30 November 2019}}</ref>\n| 1\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Italy ([[Federazione Industria Musicale Italiana|FIMI]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fimi.it/top-